<SECOND>AM-Computer Break-in, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0754,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense-NASA Computer Network Penetrated By Hackers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with a third computer and possibly others
entered, no damage, other nations also on network, network name,
third JPL computer break-in last summer, details on how hacker
gained access, Pentagon comment; No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hackers penetrated a non-classified <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> computer network last month, rummaging through data at a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> base, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Propulsion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, and at least one other center, the space agency said Thursday. The break-in occurred the night of May 16 and lasted into the early morning hours of May 17, but no damage was done, said <PERSON> Haskell </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, the laboratory's manager of communications and computing network services. `` <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> security people are working with the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigating the details of this,'' <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> told a news conference. It was unknown whether more than one person was involved or if the break-in was achieved from inside or outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. Unauthorized computer access is illegal, he added. Thousands of computers are linked to the network at hundreds of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and foreign universities and research centers, including military research centers and other <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> offices, he said. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> described it as a non-classified network for sharing scientific information. The network, named ARPANET, is operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Projects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. He said he considered the incident serious because programs used to design microcircuits could have been damaged and because `` if someone burglarizes my house, I'm offended. If someone accesses my computer, I'm equally offended.'' `` The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> regards as serious any attempt to gain unauthorized access to its computer systems,'' <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Let me assure you, however, that there is no indication that any classified information has been obtained by such hacker activity.'' The break-in was the third known violation of computer security at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in two years, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. He cited a previously publicized August 1986 break-in by a West German hacker, or computer buff, and another last summer, in which the perpetrator was caught but not prosecuted. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said the hacker in last month's incident first gained access to the Pentagon network through another computer at an undisclosed location. Once inside, the hacker guessed a password _ the name of a <ORGANIZATION> JPL </ORGANIZATION> employee _ to enter the lab's computer, he added. The hacker then used the <ORGANIZATION> JPL </ORGANIZATION> computer as a conduit to enter another ARPANET computer at <LOCATION> Patuxent </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, where authorities noticed something was amiss and notified the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. He added that he did n't know how many other computers also were penetrated. The lab's chief spokesman, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, initially said members of the <ORGANIZATION> Chaos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, broke into the <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> computer at the laboratory, but he later retracted the statement. `` We do n't know for a fact that it was Chaos. ... There are things that make us suspicious, but the bottom line fact is we do n't know,'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said. `` They're not kids,'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said of the club's members. `` They're adults. They are a worrisome group to American computer experts. They're not just hackers doing pranks. They are group whose motives and aims are not entirely clear.'' A spokesman for the club told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, that he was unaware of the break-in, but would check into the matter further. `` One thing I can tell you with absolute certainty is they -LRB- the hackers -RRB- did n't get into any classified data banks nor did they get into any sensitive information in the lab,'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said that as soon as the break-in was discovered, `` we pulled <ORGANIZATION> JPL </ORGANIZATION> out of the network.'' Several days after the break-in, <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> JPL </ORGANIZATION> officials `` rebuilt the system to make sure that if they -LRB- hackers -RRB- planted any viruses, we were not going to continue using the operating system they had been mucking around with,'' he said. A computer virus is a program surreptitiously inserted into a computer to disrupt its normal program. In April, a West German prosecutor revealed that a 24-year-old West German hacker linked his home computer to about 50 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military computers by telephone. The electronic break-ins were detected in August 1986. Targets included computers at <ORGANIZATION> JPL </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Segundo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and at the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Berkeley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. In September, members of <ORGANIZATION> Chaos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> announced that youths who were n't club members used home computers to break into a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> computer information network used by at least nine nations, and that they obtained secrets about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space program. The club said the hackers gained regular access to at least 20 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> computers between May and September 1987 through a flaw in the security system. At the time, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> denied that secret information had been obtained through its computer network.
