<HEAD>Hispanic Organizer Dead Of Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON>, who dedicated his career to increasing Hispanic political power, died Wednesday after a bout with cancer, officials said. He was 44. <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON>, 44, president of the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Registration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> he helped found in 1972, died at 12:55 a.m. at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rosa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Terrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. SVREP initially focused on voter registration and later, with other organizations, sued local governments to convert from at-large voting systems to single-member districts to assure equal Hispanic representation. <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON>, who was diagnosed with a cancerous left kidney, was admitted to the hospital Monday. He had received treatment at M.D. <LOCATION> Anderson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> last month and was to begin chemotherapy within weeks. <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON>' nonpartisan efforts helped to increase Hispanic voter registration, which has increased from 2.5 million in 1976 to an expected 5 million for the general election in November. <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON> was a founder of the activist <ORGANIZATION> Mexican-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and later became a coordinator of <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movimiento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unida </ORGANIZATION>, before it became the Chicano political party. While in his last semester of graduate school of economics at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1968, <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON> was recruited by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> to organize a strike in the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. After the strike, he became director of the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> and in June 1970, field director in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raza </ORGANIZATION>, parent organization of the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON> is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>; two daughters and a son.
