<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Willie Velasquez</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON>, whose 16-year effort to increase Hispanic voter registration led to the ethnic group becoming a viable political force, died Wednesday of cancer. He was 44. In 1972, <PERSON> Velasquez </PERSON> helped found the SVREP, a non-profit organization that initially sought to register Hispanic voters and later, with other organizations, sued local governments to convert from at-large voting systems to single-member districts to assure equal Hispanic representation. He gained politicians' respect for his unpartisan effort to increase Hispanic voter registration, which has increased from 2.5 million in 1976 to an expected 5 million for the general election in November.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Vincent Hoyman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyman </PERSON>, a veteran <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> newsman who retired in 1968 after 38 years with the news service, died Thursday at age 83. <PERSON> Hoyman </PERSON> worked at the <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>., <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> before joining the AP in <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> He transferred to the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> bureau in 1937. <PERSON> Hoyman </PERSON> was named news editor in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in 1939, a post he held until his retirement. After his retirement he was manager of the <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state for several years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Frank Beach</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Frank A. Beach, a pioneer in animal behavior research and a emeritus professor of psychology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-Berkeley </ORGANIZATION>, died Wednesday. He was 77. Beach was a highly acclaimed researcher in the fields of behavorial endocrinology and animal behavior for more than four decades. He was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philosophical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. Beach joined the UC faculty in 1958, attaining emeritus status in 1978. His major research had concentrated on the neural and endocrinological controls of sexual behavior, resulting in a crucial body of research results, books and articles.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Palmer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, managing editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Pensacola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> since 1986, died Wednesday at age 38. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> was a reporter for the <LOCATION> Johnson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, Press-Chronicle from 1969 to 1971. He left to work at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roanoke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> for two years, then returned to the Press-Chronicle. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> was Press-Chronicle wire editor for a year, then was promoted to managing editor, a position he held for 10 years. In 1983 he joined the <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, Register Star, first as city editor, then as assistant managing editor-news. He left the Register Star for the position at the <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Billings</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> <PERSON> Billings </PERSON>, whose career as a journalist for <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> newspapers spanned nearly five decades, died Tuesday. He was 78. Billings worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Springfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, before becoming a page editor with the <ORGANIZATION> Springfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leader </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Over the years he worked in public relations and for a local weekly news magazine, The Bias. Billings was news editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Coffeyville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, for two years before returning to the Leader & amp; Press in 1957.
