<HEAD>Mother Teresa Tells U.N. Abortion Is Greatest Threat To Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Mother Teresa ...,' to CORRECT Mother
Teresa's title. PICKS up 4th graf, `The small ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY49</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> on Wednesday gave her best wishes to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> conference on disarmament and gave delegates a new issue to ponder by saying `` abortion has become the greatest destroyer of peace.'' `` I think the world has never needed so much tender love as today,'' she told reporters after she met Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> for a courtesy call. <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>, 77, works with and is the founder of the international <ORGANIZATION> Missionaries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Charity </ORGANIZATION>, a religious order in <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION>. She received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979 for her work to ease the suffering of dying slum dwellers, and is known there as the `` saint of the gutters.'' The small, frail-looking woman, wearing a white cotton shawl and blue-trimmed robe, spoke fiercely against `` the evil of abortion, of destroying children, of neglecting children.'' `` We're fighting abortion by adoption, and we have saved thousands of children from being destroyed, because as you know abortion has become the greatest destroyer of peace because it destroys the child, the gift of God. And it destroys the conscience of the mother, it is actually a double killing.'' When asked if she discussed with <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> population control programs, she said she had not. Many anti-abortion activists have criticized the programs, saying them promote abortion as a possible option. `` I think we talked of other things, that we did n't say,'' she replied. Another reporter asked her why the concept of non-violence does not seem to work in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Mohandas </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> lived for 21 years and where Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize winner, carries on the tradition of peaceful civil disobedience today. <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> said `` non-violence begins at home,'' adding, `` Our government in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and the government of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> have given us full permission to go to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. And we have a mixture of all nationalities, and I am going to take take with me different nationalities, different colors, and bring there with me the joy of loving.'' She said she was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to try to open a center to care for children infected with AIDS.
