<HEAD>Bush Gets Much-Ballyhooed Drought Briefing; Says Rain Needed to
End It</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: stands for PM-Farm Scene</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the end, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s appearance at the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for a drought briefing was outshone by a career federal meteorologist's description of the trouble spots and how they could worsen Reporters who had been herded into a room to look at the vice president, then herded out, ended up only with a written statement in which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared that rain is needed to end the drought plaguing large portions of the country. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, accompanied by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and a White House entourage, met Wednesday for about half an hour in the office of <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>. For a while, the placid atmosphere of the old <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> administration building was charged by the swarming of security forces assigned to protect the vice president, who is expected to be the Republican presidential nominee. The main elevators were stopped, and employees were routed far around the sensitized area where <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was to enter and walk within the building. The department's flock of public affairs specialists scurried and fluttered about. It was an exciting time for almost everyone _ except for reporters looking for news. Reporters, photographers and television technicians were herded into a conference room, or a holding pen, where they were required to put all tape recorders and cameras on the floor and then move outside to a hallway. Dozens of <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> security people hovered close while a large German Shepherd was taken into the abandoned holding area to sniff the equipment for bombs or weapons. None was found. After more waiting, the two dozen or so news people were allowed to walk up one flight to <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s outer office. The group was allowed to enter for a `` photo opportunity'' at which the subjects are often asked questions over the clicks and whirrs of cameras. But <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s chief meteorologist, was explaining a set of yellow-and-red charts to his audience, including <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, who were seated on a couch, and <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> and others in the official party. No questions were shouted by reporters while <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> talked. After a few minutes, all news people were sternly ordered out of <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s office. Those who tried to tarry in the area were finally herded downstairs again and lodged behind a yellow tape that represented a security boundary. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> then zipped out <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s front door without enduring a single question from reporters about drought or anything else. In his wake, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> left a single-page statement noting that if relief does n't come soon, the corn crop could be in jeopardy. `` Without rain there is the potential for this to be a catastrophe,'' he said, echoing <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s congressional testimony of the day before. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said farmers in 21 states are receiving some form of emergency relief, `` but sad to say, nothing will take the place of rainfall, and we have to be concerned about the plight of the nation's farmers.'' <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> filled in the gaps later, gathering up his charts and leading reporters back into the conference room where he summarized his presentation to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>. <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> said the West is severely lacking in moisture from reduced snowpack during the winter, which resulted in `` well-below-normal'' reservoir levels in much of the region, including <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. Another major problem area is in the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, notably in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION>, he said. And dry areas still persist in the Southeast, which has not yet fully recovered from the 1986 drought. `` The best areas in terms of moisture are the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, up into the central <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> ... in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> said. Just in the last two weeks, the drought has expanded into the eastern Corn Belt states of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, and `` this is a major concern for us,'' he said. Without substantial rains soon, <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> said the Corn Belt drought has a `` potential for deterioration'' of crops. However, he said, `` it simply is too early in the growing season to try to define what that potential is.''
