<HEAD>Security Threat Posed By Drug Trafficking At Nuclear Lab, Probers
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug trafficking still poses a security threat at a top-secret nuclear weapons laboratory in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> where a 1986 undercover drug investigation was abruptly terminated under pressure from the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> investigators say. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., said `` a drug problem continues to exist, a security problem continues to exist'' at the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, where highly sensitive research on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Star Wars missile defense system is conducted According to staff investigators for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee chaired by <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>: _ In April 1987, a <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION> electronics technician with a high-level security clearance was caught with several hundred dollars' worth of illicit drugs The employee, who was working on a classified computer system, admitted trading drugs for sex with a female co-worker. _ In June 1987, a security guard responsible for protecting the laboratory's super-sensitive plutonium facility was arrested for drug possession He was accused of bringing drugs and paraphernalia into his security bunker while on duty and being armed with an automatic weapon. _ Also last summer, another employee with top security clearance who worked in the nuclear chemistry department resigned after he was accused of selling thousands of dollars' worth of cocaine to workers in sensitive areas of the laboratory _ Energy Department and <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION> officials are currently investigating allegations of drug use by `` a professional laboratory employee with access to extremely sensitive classified information. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said these disclosures, following the shutdown of the drug investigation code-named `` Operation Snowstorm'' in September 1986, raise `` serious questions about the integrity of security at our nation's most sensitive nuclear weapons and research facilities.'' Energy Undersecretary <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> said officials decided to terminate the investigation `` because it had run for eight months and was apparently not uncovering new productive leads.'' <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> said Operation Snowstorm had served its purpose in putting <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON> employees on notice that drug use would not be tolerated. He denied <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>'s charge that the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had tried to conceal the aborted investigation from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel. At the end of a day-long hearing Wednesday, <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said he was ordering an audit by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, to determine the extent of drug-related thefts of computers and other government property at <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>. `` If they are stealing government property, why would n't they steal government secrets, which are more valuable?'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> asked. Energy Department officials responded that they were conducting their own investigation of the theft problem and were `` aggressively pursuing'' questions of whether the laboratory's security clearances had been compromised by drug trafficking The DOE was accused Wednesday of halting the nine-month drug investigation prematurely, leaving undercover agents unable to pursue leads on 127 <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> employees who were suspected drug dealers or users. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Orsa-DiJamco </PERSON>, a special agent of the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, testified that pressure from DOE and laboratory officials to hasten the arrest of an alleged drug trafficking ringleader at <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>, prevented her agency from identifying the drug suppliers in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., a subcommittee member, suggested that officials who terminated the drug investigation were fearful of adverse publicity `` It seems to me that this Operation Snowstorm should be called ` Operation Snow Job','' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said. `` It appears that <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> was less interested in cooperating with the DEA than in heeding the concerns of one of its contractors,'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said. He was referring to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, which has a government contract to operate the Livermore facility. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, who managed the undercover investigation, testified that many of the drug pushers among <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON>'s 8,500 employees held top-secret `` Q'' security clearances. He said the illicit drugs they were selling included cocaine, marijuana, methamphetamine and barbiturates. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, current chief of safeguards and security at <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>, as telling staff investigators that if Operation Snowstorm had been allowed to continue, `` we would have to arrest 20 percent of the