<HEAD>Surgical Implantation of False Teeth Becoming More Common</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dental science has developed new techniques and new materials for the surgical implantation of false teeth, but there still is no definitive study on the effectiveness of the procedure, a panel of experts says. A panel of dental experts, meeting at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, released a statement Wednesday in which they said more than 300,000 Americans annually will be receiving surgically implanted false teeth by 1992 and that the number of dentists performing such procedures has increased by 10 times since 1983. But the panel said scientific and statistically precise studies are needed to define the effectiveness of permanently implanted false teeth. The panel said the cost for surgically-installed false teeth is about $ 300 to $ 1,000 per implant and that patients can receive from one to eight implants. <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> conference on dental implants, said the surgical installation of teeth can no longer be considered experimental. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said the development of new materials and new techniques have led to wider acceptance of implantation by dentists and that the demand for permanent false teeth is increasing among Americans. He said as people tend to live longer, more and more patients are finding that they can not use removable false teeth and are choosing to have permanently-implanted artificial teeth. There are several systems for implanting false teeth in living tissue, but they all basically involve surgically cutting into the bone that normally supports teeth and installing a manmade peg or post to support the false teeth, or to anchor a bridge of false teeth. The <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> panel said that because scientific studies have not been made on methods of implanting false teeth, `` it is not possible to make judgments on the comparative merits of different implant systems.'' Several studies, however, show that dental implants are effective for five to 10 years, the panel's report said. However, the report said that little information is available to evaluate such factors as patient satisfaction, appearance, comfort and the effect of implants on speech and chewing. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said the panel also determined that the risks of surgically implanting false teeth include the `` inadvertent'' penetration of a sinus cavity by a dentist drilling in bone to create a socket for the implant. He said other problems include damage to facial nerves and infections that could threaten existing, natural teeth.
