<FIRST>r a PM-Drought-Almanac     06-16 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought-Almanac,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Old Farmer's Almanac' Reader Complains About Missed Forecast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Iowa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After watching his half-acre of grass wither and dry this spring, <PERSON> Witham </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> wrote a letter to the `` Old Farmer's Almanac.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a regular reader of the almanac, asked whether the 196-year-old publication's forecasters, having missed the Midwest's drought, could at least predict the dry spell's end He received a pretty dry answer from <PERSON> Judson </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, editor of the almanac. `` We did n't predict that it was coming and we ca n't predict when it will end,'' <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who lives in suburban Terrace Park. The almanac claims to be 80 percent accurate, but <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> acknowledged that it does n't predict weather for spring and summer too well. This year, it predicted that it would be warmer and wetter than normal in the Greater <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Heavy rain was predicted for June 14 to 17. The almanac usually gathers statistics for its predictions six to 18 months in advance. The predictions are based on such information as changes in sun spots, the size of polar ice caps, and the location of warm water currents. `` Our 1989 edition will be published in November. It is really hard to nail down the weather for spring and summer that far in advance because so many things happen,'' <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said. `` They have been a little off before, but never this far,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` They said we would be about half an inch off, but not a drought like this.''
