<HEAD>Ousted Statesman Was Israel's Spokesman For Four Decades</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senior <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislator <PERSON> Abba </PERSON> <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>, a founding father of the Jewish state and its leading spokesman for years, has been ousted from <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> politics after a generation in its vanguard. The 73-year-old <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>, a former deputy prime minister and foreign minister, failed in his bid Wednesday to win a slot on the party slate for the November elections to the Israeli Parliament. Under the Israeli system, each party makes a list of people to fill the seats it wins in the 120-member <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION>. The number of seats assigned to a party depends on its total vote. After the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> vote, <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> wrote to party leader and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>: `` For a generation I carried -LRB- the party's -RRB- flag and stated its case throughout the country and the world, and many listened to me. `` It's clear I can not keep carrying the flag as I did in the past because the party leadership took away my right to do so.'' <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> said he would now dedicate his time to writing books and participating in a television series on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s history. The tall, portly <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> is known for his sophisticated oratory, and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s first prime minister, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Gurion </PERSON>, once described him as `` the voice of the Hebrew nation.'' In his 40-year political career, <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> also served as <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Referring to his appeal abroad, <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> once said: `` I could have been elected prime minister if people abroad could vote in <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> elections.'' In domestic party politics, <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> never played a central role, partially because his upper-class mannerisms and love of academia set him apart from many of his colleagues. Since 1984, <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> has served as chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a position of influence but with little direct power. <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> was born Feb. 2, 1915, in <LOCATION> Capetown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and his family moved to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> when he was a child. He attended <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION>, where he received first class honors in classics, Hebrew, and Arabic and Persian During World War II, he joined the British army. When the war ended, he joined the <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the forerunner of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, and was sent to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to help fight for a Jewish state. His skill as a speaker was instrumental in persuading the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to pass the Nov. 29, 1947 Palestine partition resolution that granted the Jews a homeland. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was declared a state a year later. <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>'s ouster Wednesday was in part an apparent payback for his criticism of party leaders for the <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> spy case. <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON>, a 33-year-old American Jew, was sentenced to life in prison in March 1987 for selling classified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military documents to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> made waves in the party last year when a <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION> investigating committee he headed blamed <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> and Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, a party member, for not supervising those involved in the <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> operation. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> was prime minister when <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> was working for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.
