<HEAD>Communists To Participate in Single-Candidate Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> departed from its previous radical stance and said it will participate in a presidential election in which the only candidate will be nominated by the military. The Communists were until now the only major opposition group refusing to participate. They had called for `` all forms of struggle,'' including violence, to put an end to the military regime of President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. The Party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that the new position was prompted by `` a new social-political picture in the country'' resulting from the opposition's `` social mobilization and intense political battle.'' But <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leader, said the Communists still will remain excluded from a group of 14 moderate opposition parties united for the vote. According to the 1980 military-drafted Constitution, the election will take place at an unspecified date later this year or early 1989. Citizens will only be able to vote `` yes'' or `` no'' on a candidate to be nominated by the commanders of the three armed services and the head of the national police. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, 72, who has ruled since a 1973 coup, is considered the most likely candidate. Four Communist leaders said at a news conference that they still think the government will try to win the plebiscite fraudulently and called for labor unrest and street demonstrations. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanfuentes </PERSON>, a party leader, said, `` The victory of the ` no' in the plebiscite should mean an immediate end to the dictatorship and its fascist legislation. He said it should lead to a `` transitional democratic government'' to call an early competitive presidential election. The moderate opposition says a `` no'' victory should be followed by negotiations with the military to ensure a peaceful and orderly transition to full democracy. But the government insists that whatever the vote upcome, the Constitution will remain unchanged. That means if the military-picked candidate is rejected, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> would remain in office for an extra year, until 1990, when an open election would be called.
