<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ito-Yokado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a major Japanese supermarket operator, has suspended sales of South African products because of the country's apartheid policy, a company official said today. `` The decision not to deal in South African products was made in view of the growing criticism in and outside the company'' of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s policy of racial segregation, said supermarket spokesman <PERSON> Yasuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Takaha </PERSON>. Sales of canned yellow peaches and canned fruit cocktail imported through a Japanese trading company were suspended at the company's 133 shops across the country in April. <PERSON> Takaha </PERSON> said the decision was made during a company meeting in March, but the supermarket chose not to make a formal announcement. He said the products have been replaced with similar items from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
