<SECOND>PM-China-Foreign Media,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Attacks Foreign Reports On Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese police today accused the foreign media of `` sheer fabrications'' in reporting a student sit-in. It was the second attack in a week on foreign accounts of student unrest. The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingrong </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, as saying foreign journalists reported students were arrested or beaten by police at sit-in Friday on academic issues. `` Such stories in some foreign media are sheer fabrications,'' <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> as saying. He confirmed that police broke up the protest outside <LOCATION> Zhongnanhai </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, a walled compound that houses party headquarters and residences for top leaders. The students were from <LOCATION> Changchun </LOCATION> in northeast <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Jilin </LOCATION> province. But in a telephone interview, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> refused to give details of how the protest was broken up. No Western reporters saw the brief sit-in. The French news agency <ORGANIZATION> Agence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France-Presse </ORGANIZATION> quoted a witness as saying police led away about 60 protesters, and said police later confirmed the students were taken away. But AFP said it did not report any police beatings of the students, and the target of <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>'s criticism was not immediately clear. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> accused the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> radio of falsely reporting a student was arrested in a separate sit-in June 8. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> denied the charge, and said it only reported that one person was led away by police. That sit-in involved about a dozen <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students who were trying to hold a pro-democracy protest in central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square. Hundreds of students had rallied on campus and planned a march to the square, but police cordoned it off and no march was held. The protest Friday involved students who attended an unaccredited `` special training course'' in <LOCATION> Changchun </LOCATION> and wanted government accreditation for their diplomas, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said. It quoted <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> as saying police stopped the sit-in because `` the students violated the rules for maintaining social order by interfering in the work of the government.'' The incident prompted a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> announcement Tuesday calling for a crackdown on unauthorized schools and training classes that lack official accreditation. A growing number of such classes have been set up privately and by work units in recent years, generally to teach English and technical subjects, because of a shortage of places in accredited schools. But their certificates or degrees are not recognized by would-be employers. Officials have made it clear they will not tolerate a repeat of the massive student protests of the winter of 1986-87, when thousands of students in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and other major cities marched through the streets to demand democracy and freedom. Those protests ended with a crackdown on Western-style liberalism and the ouster by conservatives of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> for failing to halt the protests quickly enough.
</TEXT>
