<HEAD>New President Challenges The Generals Who Ensured His Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore dropped word. Picks up 3rd graf,
`Manigat on ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ President <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> has rejected the transfers of several high-ranking army officers, publicly challenging for the first time the powerful military command that ensured his election. The apparent power struggle began when Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>, head of the three-man junta that ran <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> until <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>'s election in January, ordered the transfers or retirements. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> on Wednesday overruled the orders, claiming they were unconstitutional since he had not been consulted. On Wednesday night, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement pledging loyalty to <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> and delaying the transfer orders. `` It has been decided after a meeting with ... the president and the minister of defense to temporarily put off the above mentioned steps,'' said the statement, broadcast on the private <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haiti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inter </ORGANIZATION>. `` The transfer and retirement of certain high-ranking officers and other officers decided Tuesday morning by the commander-in-chief'' had been rescinded to `` avoid a major crisis,'' said the statement from the national palace read on local radio stations. It was unclear whether <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> had prevailed. `` The situation is grave,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Either the general submits to <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>'s ultimatum, or there will be a stand-off between the government and the army There is fear of a clash.'' One of the officers <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> tried to reassign is Col. <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, who heads the widely-feared <ORGANIZATION> Dessalines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Battalion </ORGANIZATION> and was indicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges in March. <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inter </LOCATION>, quoting an unidentified military source, said <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> relieved of his command of the 700-man battalion and named assistant chief of staff, a largely administrative position. Soldiers under <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s command have been blamed for widespread violence against voters that forced the cancellation of last November's independently adminstrated general elections and left more than 30 people dead. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>, the army's candidate in the Jan. 17 junta-run elections, has always claimed that he could govern independent of the army, which has controlled <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> during most of its 184-year history. A government spokeswoman said Wednesday that everyone was waiting to see what would happen. `` This is certainly a moment of crisis,'' said <PERSON> Anaise </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavenet </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the Ministry of Information. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> scheduled a news conference for this morning. The army's statement, signed by General Secretary of the General Staff Col. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> also said the high command reaffirmed its `` unreserved loyalty to the government of the state within the framework of constitutional and legal provisions.'' <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> was head of the three-man junta that ruled <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> for two years after dictator <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> fled into exile in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in February 1986. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>, a former political science professor, was elected in army-supervised balloting that was boycotted by the opposition that foreign observers said was fraught with fraud. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> cut off most of its aid to <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> after the aborted November balloting. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> was indicted in March by a grand jury in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on charges of conspiring to import 220 pounds of cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in December 1986. He has denied the charges. Last week, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Latortue </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>, that his government is ready to open an investigation into <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s alleged drug connection as soon as it officially receives the evidence from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lite </PERSON> said details of the charges were delivered to Haitian authorities last week. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>, a Social Democrat considered right-of-center and staunchly anti-communist, has done little to alleviate <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s most pressing problems. <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, which a population of 6 million, is the poorest country in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>. It shares the island of <LOCATION> Hispaniola </LOCATION> with the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>.
