<SECOND>PM-Canada-Espionage,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Told That U.S. Secrets Intended For Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Canadian who lived for a time in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has been charged with espionage for allegedly gathering secrets about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> submarine-monitoring operations for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON>, 25, a native of <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>, was charged with three counts of espionage under <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s Official Secrets Act during an appearance in St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s provincial court on Wednesday. Officials have not said whether any information was actually passed to the Soviets. <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON> was ordered held without bail until June 28. He did not have to enter a plea. The suspect said nothing when reporters shouted out questions as he left the courthouse. <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON> was accused of gathering classified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military documents about the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s submarine-tracking base in the <LOCATION> Argentia </LOCATION> naval base during 1987 and 1988. The documents were intended for a foreign power, `` namely the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics,'' the charges said. <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON> was arrested last Saturday in St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s following a 2 -LCB- - year investigation by the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mounted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Argentia </LOCATION> base, on <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>'s foggy south coast, keeps an eye on Soviet submarines by monitoring a network of underwater listening devices in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The base is jointly operated by up to 400 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel and 70 Canadians. The base commander, Capt. <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON>, said Tuesday that a member of the base staff cooperated with <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> security agents in investigating <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> would not say whether <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON> approached the base member to seek classified documents or whether he was given doctored documents to pass to the Soviets. <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON>'s mother came from <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>. His father was a Hungarian who emigrated to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> after the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> cracked down on an anti-Soviet uprising in 1956. After his mother committed suicide <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> for a while as a child. Later he returned to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. In 1983, he moved back to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> before again moving back to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ratkai </PERSON> was the fourth person charged under <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s Official Secrets Act since 1950. Only one of the four has been convicted. That was in January 1986, when former <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mounted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> officer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> pleaded guilty to having passed secrets to the Soviets in 1955. He was sentenced to 18 months in jail.
