<HEAD>Journalist Advocates Sweeping Democratic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent journalist has proposed radically altering Soviet politics so the people elect their chief executive by secret ballot and power is transferred from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to the government. <PERSON> Fyodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> calls for the changes in this week's edition of the literary newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Literaturnaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION>. He says the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s parliament, the Supreme Soviet, should be given broad powers, including the right to allocate the budget and impeach the president. The body now merely ratifies the Communist leadership's decisions. The main thesis of <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> adviser and prominent Soviet political thinker, is that the government should be strengthened to the detriment of the party, which now holds a monopoly on political power. `` <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> had some elements of democracy before, but never had liberal traditions ... the freedom of an individual from interference by the state,'' <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> wrote. `` <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> never had any notion about basic human rights.'' The far-reaching article in the weekly newspaper of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> is one of the most radical critiques of the system yet to appear under the auspices of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program of liberalization <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> expands on points included in proposals to be discussed at an extraordinariy <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference that begins June 28. He says the country's leader should be elected `` by direct and secret ballot by all the people'' rather than in a meeting of the Politburo of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> suggests a candidate should first attain the post of party general secretary, now the highest Soviet office, then run for president. He does not say if more than one candidate should be allowed to run for each office. The writer also calls for the creation of the post of vice president. Supporters of the <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> reforms say their efforts are hampered by conservative officials in the party and government who stand to lose power and privilege. Conservatives blocked <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> and other outspoken reformers from being included among the 5,000 delegates to the party conference. The conference can debate and set party policy, but is not expected to make leadership changes. <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> is vice presdident of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and a regular contributor to <ORGANIZATION> Literaturnaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION>. He first gained prominence as an adviser to <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, who was ousted as Soviet leader in 1964 by a group which included <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who lead the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> until his death in 1982.
</TEXT>
