graf, `West German ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bands of English, Dutch and West German rowdies brawled after a European Soccer Championship match, but the city was quiet today after thousands of riot police massed in its center. Authorities said massive security efforts had thwarted serious violent clashes. In all, 371 people were arrested during two days that ended Wednesday. Of them, 18 were English fans, police said. Most of those arrested were released after spending several hours in jail. Sporadic fistfights erupted in various parts of the city on Wednesday after the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>' 3-1 victory over <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s national team Soccer fans mobbed the streets and <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION>'s main train station But by midnight, the station and surrounding streets were nearly clear of fans. Most had boarded outbound trains. Streets in the city's Old Section were also quiet, police said. More than 2,300 police were deployed in <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION> to prevent a recurrence of the rampant vandalism and running battles that erupted among rowdies in the city Tuesday night. `` It was n't as bad as we had feared,'' said police spokesman <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodax </PERSON>, adding that most of the violence was initiated by West German fans. `` The English were not the problem,'' <PERSON> Rodax </PERSON> said. West German television late Wednesday showed a pistol confiscated from one of the rowdies, but did not identify its owner. On Wednesday night, West German, Dutch and English soccer fans got into a street brawl near the train station. Riot police rushed to the scene, broke up the fight and arrested about 20 people, observers said. West German and English rowdies also had minor scuffles inside the train station itself as English fans waited for trains to take them out of the city. Many of the English were headed to <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are to meet for a match on Saturday. About 22,000 Dutch and about 8,500 English fans jammed into <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION> for the game on Wednesday. Their arrival followed a night of vandalism and fighting pitting West German fans against English soccer buffs. Police said in that round of violence 130 people were arrested, 90 of them English and 40 West Germans. English club teams were barred from European Cup tournaments after a rampage by English fans that left 39 people dead at a European Cup final in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> three years ago. <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Millichip </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the latest trouble could destroy the last faint hope English clubs have of being readmitted to European competition, and that he feared it might also force the international team into exile. British Sports Minister <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, who was on a fact-finding mission in <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION> for Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to look into the clashes, also strongly denounced the violence. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, also speaking to the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said of the British troublemakers: `` They are worse than animals, because I know of no animals which would behave in this manner.''
