<HEAD>Striking Scriptwriters File Unfair Labor Practice Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Striking scriptwriters have filed unfair labor practice charges against 13 production companies but have scheduled another meeting with producers in an effort to end their 4-month-old walkout. The charges were filed with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday, said <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON>. They accuse the companies of bargaining in bad faith by refusing to provide information on writers as requested by the guild last month, Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said. The union had requested the names, addresses, dates of employment and rates of pay for persons providing guild-covered writing services since March 7, Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said in a statement. The companies include <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> for its `` I Man'' production; Capital Cities @ <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for `` General Hospital,'' <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Square </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION>, for `` The Late Show,'' and <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> for the shows, `` McGyver,'' `` Star Trek, the Next Generation,'' `` Webster'' and `` The Naked Gun.'' The statement was issued late Wednesday, and the companies could not be reached for immediate comment. Representatives of the guild and the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, were scheduled to meet again this afternoon in a bargaining session that management said could `` conclude negotiations.'' Although the guild agreed to the meeting, Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said `` the producers are trying to stampede us into a settlement.'' Sources have said only one issue _ foreign residual payments _ remains. Top negotiators for the guild and the producers' alliance have been meeting informally since the parties' last formal session ended Saturday. On Wednesday, the producers called `` for a meeting of the bargaining committees to conclude negotiations.'' `` Spelled out, that means we are going to give them a formal proposal, based on the intensive meetings we had last week,'' said <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an alliance spokesman. The latest effort to end the strike comes on the eve of the television production season. Also looming is this week's scheduled start of talks between producers and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> unions. The stage craft workers' and drivers' contracts expire July 31. A guild source who spoke on condition of anonymity said `` major issues remain unresolved, and we do n't anticipate -LRB- today's -RRB- discussions to result in an imminent end to the strike.'' Sources have said the guild has accepted a producer's formula based on sales success for syndicated one-hour television shows. The previous formula had a fixed revenue. Producers have claimed the market for such sales has softened. But because the guild has accepted a management proposal in one-hour shows, sources said, union negotiators want a substantial increase for foreign residuals, an area that has been booming for several years for studios and distributors but has not been negotiated for 18 years. The guild has cited reports from <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION> magazine that estimated a $ 4.9 billion trade surplus for the nationwide entertainment industry in 1986, with an estimated surplus of $ 5.5 billion for 1987, second only to the aerospace industry.
