<HEAD>Mercenary Witness Should Be Jailed, Magistrate Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal magistrate says a former mercenary should be jailed for refusing to cooperate in a $ 24 million lawsuit against an alleged guns-for-drugs smuggling conspiracy to aid the Contras. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> refused to answer questions or turn over documents Wednesday in the civil case filed against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government officials, <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> leaders and <ORGANIZATION> Medellin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cartel </ORGANIZATION> drug traffickers by two journalists and the liberal <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` It has to do with principle,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Turnoff </PERSON>. `` My past would have been in vain.'' But the magistrate said <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s position had no legal basis and ordered him held in civil contempt until he answered the questions during depositions. <PERSON> Turnoff </PERSON> said he would make his recommendation to the presiding judge in the case, Chief U.S. District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, who is on vacation until next week. The suit was filed by <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Honey </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Avirgan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Avirgan </PERSON> was injured in a 1984 bombing in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> that he blames on the alleged conspirators. The damage and racketeering suit charges that members of a right-wing terror network tracing back to 1959 illegally participated in assassination plots, gun running and drug trafficking. Hall, who will remain free at least until King returns to the bench, said he has been told he can be jailed indefinitely for refusing to hand over the documents, and for up to six months for not answering questions. `` I'm prepared to go to jail as long as the case takes,'' he said. Hall is not considered a major witness in the case, but the plaintiffs want to know who paid and directed <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> while he aided the Contras inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. In 1986, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> was caught by the Sandinista government, which called him mentally unstable and later kicked him out of the country. Hall has acknowledged receiving funds from anticommunist militant and former Maj. Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>, his boss in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and one of 29 defendants in the suit. The case is set for trial June 27. However, he repeatedly refused to disclose where other funds came from or who trained and directed him in the use of explosives. Asked whom he was protecting, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> replied `` <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON> and above,'' indicating <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government officials. But he added his information, while politically embarrassing, did not involve illegal acts. Hall, who lives in <LOCATION> Redington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shores </LOCATION>, also said he has connections with Iran-Contra figure <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, an assistant to <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and a defendant in the suit. He said <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> promised him a presidential pardon for his activities in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, also attended the hearing, and bitterly attacked the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and the suit. `` This is a completely baseless lawsuit ... that has consumed hundreds of thousands of dollars, indeed millions of dollars of the defendants' money,'' he told Turnoff. Along with <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON> and <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, defendants in the suit include <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Shackley </PERSON>, former deputy director of operations for the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> Medellin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cartel </ORGANIZATION> leaders <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Escobar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON>; Iran-Contra figures <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, and others. The suit was filed in May 1986, six months before the Iran-Contra affair became public.
