<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two vials of blood found on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> shore earlier this month contained the AIDS antibody, the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said, but it stressed that the samples posed virtually no risk to swimmers. `` There has n't been any evidence of AIDS contamination with such samples,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, acting health commissioner, said Wednesday. The samples, which have been turned over to the attorney general's office for further investigation, were discovered June 3 or 4, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said at a news conference. One vial was found on <LOCATION> Ortley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and the other on the north side of <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, both in <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said officials did n't know how long they had been there. Beach patrols discovered five glass tubes, each about 5 inches long and less than an inch in diameter, containing coagulated blood, said <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>. Only two were found to have evidence of the AIDS antibody, he said. Presence of the AIDS antibody means the blood came from individuals who carry the AIDS virus and will probably develop the fatal disease, said <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the body's ability to defend itself against disease. `` We do not have a threat of AIDS or AIDS contamination from these samples,'' said <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>. The vials were found at about the same time as some syringes. Health officials could not determine where the items came from, except that they probably originated from a clinic or hospital. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> is temporarily replacing Commissioner Dr. <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coye </PERSON>, who is in <LOCATION>