<TEXT>
 Indian peacekeeping troops cordoned off a Tamil town in eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> today and began rounding up suspected rebels, area residents and diplomatic sources said. In <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, meanwhile, a newspaper reported that the main Tamil rebel group in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> has agreed in principle to surrender most of its arms in exchange for the rehabilitation of its fighters. Residents of <LOCATION> Batticola </LOCATION>, 135 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, said by telephone that Indian troops had surrounded the adjacent town of <LOCATION> Kallady </LOCATION> at about dawn today and had rounded up hundreds of Tamils for questioning. A spokeswoman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy, in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> said only that `` Indian troops are continuing their search for Tamil Tiger arms and fighters.'' She spoke on condition of anonymity. The state-run Daily News today quoted Indian sources as saying Indian troops captured 21 Tamil rebels Wednesday, including four guerrilla leaders. It said the rebels were arrested during `` white flag protests'' in the northern and eastern provinces, where Tamils predominate. Hundreds of Tamil homes were decked with white flags Wednesday to underscore a demand that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> begin negotiations with the rebels. In July, President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> signed an Indian-sponsored peace accord aimed at ending the Tamils' guerrilla war. But the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, the largest of the rebel groups, rejected the pact and continued fighting for a separate homeland. The English-language Indian Express today quoted unidentified Tamil leaders in the southern Indian city of <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> as saying an agreement was in the works between the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> and the Indian government. The Express said the two sides still were negotiating the period of time over which the rebels would surrender their arms and their role in restoring peace after five years of guerrilla warfare. The story did not specify exactly what is meant by rehabilitation but the word is generally used to mean helping the combatants shift from soldiering to more socially useful occupations. The paper said the agreement could be announced as early as Friday, when Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> visits <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION>. An Indian official in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that the report was speculative, but that <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> officials had been talking with the Tamil rebels. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved in the Sri Lankan war because it is the dominant power in the region and because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the separatist rebels' cause. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has sent at least 50,000 troops to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> to police the cease-fire called for in the July agreement, and this force has inflicted a series of defeats on the rebels in recent weeks. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. They claim discrimination by the Sinhalese Buddhists, who form 75 percent of the population and control the government and military.
