<HEAD>IRA Bomb Kills Six Soldiers, Injures 10 Civilians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with IRA statement; quotes from
witnesses, details. No pickup. Adds byline</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBURN, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> vowed today to wage `` unceasing war'' against <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> after a guerrilla bomb blew up at a festive foot race packed with people, killing six soldiers and wounding 10 civilians. The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Belfast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility for Wednesday night's bombing _ the guerrilla group's deadliest attack in seven months _ in a statement today to news media in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas slipped into the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> town of <LOCATION> Lisburn </LOCATION>, headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, and wired a bomb containing seven pounds of explosives to an unmarked army van, the statement said. The blue van exploded as six soldiers rode away in it after taking part in half-marathon of 13 miles that had attracted 4,250 competitors to <LOCATION> Lisburn </LOCATION>, seven miles southwest of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>. All six soldiers were killed, bringing this year's death toll from the province's sectarian violence to 38, eight this week alone. Mayor <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bleakes </PERSON> said the town was in `` shock and disbelief that any human being could do this to other human beings.'' None of the civilians, including an 80-year-old man and a 2-year-old boy, suffered serious injuries, police said. <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>, 28, who lives nearby, said the town `` was packed with people ... They were running about screaming. There were children and families. They were terrified.'' The death toll was the highest since an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> bombing at a war memorial ceremony in <LOCATION> Enniskillen </LOCATION> on Nov. 8. The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> said that bomb was meant to kill soldiers but accidentally massacred 11 Protestant civilians. The explosion occurred as the van moved through the town center, which was thronged with runners and spectators leaving the charity run. <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sands </PERSON>, 19, who was two cars behind the van, said he saw smoke, then heard a loud explosion `` and I saw two bodies lying in the middle of the road. One of them had no legs, and one of them was burning. It as badly mutilated. It seems they were blown from the van. There was panic and people were running everywhere.'' Although police said they received no warning before the blast, the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> said: `` Every care was exercised by our volunteers to ensure the minimum risk to the local population. The statement said the British presence in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> oppressed the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> people, adding: `` Until that presence is removed and the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> people as a unit can exercise our right to national self-determination, the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> will continue to wage unceasing war against the British Crown Forces and the British colonial presence.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s representative in the province, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> Secretary <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, toured the bomb scene today and told reporters later the attack revealed the `` vileness of terrorism which we have to face.'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said, however, that the security forces had not taken adequate security precautions to prevent the bombing. British soldiers and police are the main targets of the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> in its nearly 20-year war to oust the British from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republic. Police on today cordoned the area where the bomb went off. Townspeople gathered in clusters by ribbon barrier, gazing in silence at the van's gutted hulk. <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>'s Irish News, the province's main <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, said the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> had opened `` another blood-stained chapter in their perverted history ... The result of their savagery will only be to harden hearts and block progress towards an eventual solution.'' It was the army's worst blow since a 1982 bombing in a pub near <LOCATION> Londonderry </LOCATION> killed 11 soldiers and six civilians. An <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> offshoot, the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, claimed responsibility for that attack.
