 <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON>'s got a copyright on his confession and his organization is not taking it lightly that the <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> is promoting a production by using the minister's public admission of sin The radio commercial began airing today, opera officials said. It promotes the opera company's June 30 and July 2 performances of <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON> <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON>'s 1956 opera `` Susannah,'' in which an isolated young woman is seduced by a hypocritical, backwoods <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> preacher. In the commercial, the voice of <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> is heard to say: `` I do not plan in any way to whitewash my sin. I have no one but myself to blame.'' <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON>, a Louisiana-based television preacher, made the statement during a February speech to his congregation. He never specified the sin, but he was reported to have met several times with a prostitute at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> motel to watch her perform sexual acts. He has not denied those reports. `` We're looking into this to see if there's a violation of our copyrights,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Treeby </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> attorney who is a board member of the <ORGANIZATION> Jimmy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swaggart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are not going to comment further, just examine it from a legal standpoint. They do n't have the right to use material that we've copyrighted.'' He said the ministries have copyrighted the <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> confession. A 10-second television spot produced for the opera company re-enacts a scene from the opera in which <PERSON> Susannah </PERSON>, with her back to the camera, bathes nude in a creek, while an announcer says, `` <PERSON> Susannah </PERSON> takes it off, and the elders ca n't bear it.'' <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Beggs </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> marketing director, said the hint of sexual scandal was a natural in marketing the opera. `` This is so topical it's unbelievable, with <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Beggs </PERSON> said. `` It was sort of a connection everybody was drawing.'' The company hopes the advertisements will amuse and not offend, she said. `` We certainly did n't do it with any malicious intent. We just want to bring opera into range of focus of people's experiences,'' Ms. <PERSON> Beggs </PERSON> said. The radio advertisement, which was produced by <PERSON> Lawler </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> Advertising, used the clip from <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON>'s Feb. 21 public confession, then followed it with the voice of announcer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephenson </PERSON> saying: `` Lustful evangelists have gotten a lot of publicity lately. But if you want to see the most lustful evangelist of all, come watch the Rev. <PERSON> Olin </PERSON> <PERSON> Blitch </PERSON> try to convert the beautiful but innocent <PERSON> Susannah </PERSON> to a life of sin and degradation in <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON> <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON>'s all-American opera ` <PERSON> Susannah </PERSON>' ... probably the only great opera ever written that takes place in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>.''
