^By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLAHABAD, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One person was killed and several others were injured today during a parliamentary election that will test the power of Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s main challenger. Election officials later postponed voting at one polling station after allegations that loyalists of <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> tried to rig ballots. The contest for a seat in the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> pitted former Defense Minister V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a Gandhi ally-turned-foe, against singer and film writer <PERSON> Sunil </PERSON> <PERSON> Shastri </PERSON>, of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The battle between <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, 56, and <PERSON> Shastri </PERSON>, 38, has been watched closely as a measure of how <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> would do in a national contest against <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. The polling booth in the <LOCATION> Satpura </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Allahabad </LOCATION> did not open today because of irregularities, election officials said. Balloting was rescheduled for Friday. Officials gave no details. But <PERSON> Chander </PERSON> <PERSON> Amrit </PERSON>, a member of <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morcha </ORGANIZATION> political group, said 15 armed men had raided the Satpura polling booth and marked 800 ballots, most of them for the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate. One of <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s supporters was shot and injured in a clash in the village of <LOCATION> Naini </LOCATION>, 10 miles south of <LOCATION> Allahabad </LOCATION>, election authorities said. He was identified as <PERSON> Narendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Pal </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a member of the state assembly. He is not related to the candidate. In neighboring <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> state, one person was killed and several injured in clashes among factions at three villages, the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. No details were available. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, running as an independent with the backing of most of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s major opposition parties, was among the first to cast his vote in <LOCATION> Allahabad </LOCATION>, 360 miles southeast of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. `` I voted for myself,'' he said. `` Who else is there?'' <PERSON> Shastri </PERSON> was not eligible to vote because he is registered in his home city of <LOCATION> Gorakhpur </LOCATION>, 120 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Allahabad </LOCATION>. More than 6.5 million voters in eight states were eligible to vote in off-year elections for seven <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and 11 state assembly seats. Lines formed outside the voting centers long before they opened at 7:30 a.m. Polls were to close at 4:30 p.m., and final results were expected late Friday or Saturday. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> broke with the prime minister last year over the government's hesitation to investigate alleged kickbacks in defense contracts. Opposition parties and the press have alleged that government officials and <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> cronies received kickbacks to facilitate the purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> artillery guns from <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and West German submarines. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and his party have denied the charges. The <ORGANIZATION> Allahabad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> seat became vacant when film star <PERSON> Agitabh </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachchan </PERSON>, a close friend of <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, was forced to resign because of allegations his brother may have been a conduit for kickbacks. The <PERSON> Bachchan </PERSON> brothers have denied any wrongdoing. <PERSON> Shastri </PERSON> is the son of popular late Prime Minister <PERSON> Lal </PERSON> <PERSON> Bahadur </PERSON> <PERSON> Shastri </PERSON>. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shastri </PERSON> are just two of the 68 candidates for the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> seat, but only one other candidate, <ORGANIZATION> Kanshi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ram </ORGANIZATION>, is considered a serious contender. Ram has championed the causes of the lower castes.
