<HEAD>New Jersey Mayor Becomes President Of U.S. Mayors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The top priority of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> will be to convince the presidential candidates that cities need help, especially in the fight against drugs, the organization's new president said. Mayor <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, was installed Wednesday as the 45th president of the organization during the closing session of its annual meeting. <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>, who succeeds Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in the two-year post, said Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may have erred in being the only presidential nominee to snub an invitation to address the gathering. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spoke to the mayors on Sunday and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> appeared on Tuesday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said a scheduling conflict prevented him from coming to <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, but he sent a detailed letter addressing the needs of cities, <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said. `` If I were <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, I would want to be here, and not having been here, I would want to talk to as many mayors as possible,'' said <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, a Democrat. Of the problems facing cities, the most serious is the use of illicit drugs and the crime it spawns, <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said during a news conference. `` Number one is drugs. The problem of crack is overwhelming us,'' <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said. `` Almost all of our crime is drug-related,'' in <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, he said. `` We simply do n't have the resources to fight this.'' <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said the conference sent a telegram to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday asking for an amendment that would allow federal anti-crime funds to be sent directly to cities for use in the war on drugs. `` We have n't acted as though we are at war, and we must if we are to conquer that which is conquering us,'' he said. After drugs, cities need federal help for mass transit, housing and job training, said <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>. Mayor <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, whose city will host next year's annual meeting, said aid to cities has dropped sharply in recent years. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said Urban Development Action Grants have been reduced from a high of about $ 750 million in 1980 to $ 216 million last year. However, the mayors did n't blame the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` I fault the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>. Mayors attending the conference hailed <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION> as a creative urban leader and articulate spokesman for the nation's cities. <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> was elected mayor of <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION> in 1959 after serving on the city commission. He was defeated in 1966, but reclaimed the office in 1970 and has held it since then.
