<HEAD>Operating Rates at Factories Rose to 82.9 Percent in May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Operating rates at American factories, mines and utilities rose in May to 82.9 percent, the highest level in more than eight years, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the 0.2 percentage point rise from the April level put operating rates at their highest levels since March 1980, when the rate was 83.7 percent. It was the sixth increase in eight months. Operating rates rose by 0.3 percentage points in April, after dropping 0.1 percent in February and remaining unchanged in March. The May advance was led by gains in the production of autos and parts, primary metals such as steel, and in fabricated metal products. It was the third consecutive steep monthly rise at motor vehicle and parts plants, where operating rates were 83.9 percent, compared with 76.8 percent in February. Analysts had expected the modest rise in overall operating rates after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday that production levels had increased 0.4 percent in May. Rising operating rates, if unchecked, are considered by analysts to represent a threat of inflation. The concern is that prices will rise if manufacturers have difficulty meeting demand. The May level of 82.9 percent was 3 percentage points higher than the 79.9 percent rate a year ago, but analysts generally do not consider the overall operating rate to be inflationary until it reaches 85 percent. Rising capacity levels have been attributed to the surge in exports caused by the devaluation of the dollar. But, so far consumer demand in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> appears to have been restrained enough to allow manufacturers in most industries to comfortably meet both domestic and foreign demand. In a speech in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> earlier this week, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said despite strained capacity in steel and certain chemicals, statistics on industrial delivery times do not indicate that inflationary bottlenecks are developing. Delivery times for production materials have moved up only moderately since late 1985 and have stabilized, at least temporarily, during the past five months, he said. The operating rate for manufacturing plants jumped to 83.1 percent in May, up from 82.9 percent a month earlier. Production of durable goods, `` big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years, rose by 0.6 percentage points to 81.6 percent, while the rate for non-durable goods declined by 0.4 percentage points to 85.3 percent. The mining industry, which includes oil and gas drilling, operated at 81.3 percent of capacity, down from 81.8 percent in April. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> utilities operated at an 80.9 percent rate in May, up from 80.4 percent.
