<FIRST>r a PM-SentencingGuidelines     06-16 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sentencing Guidelines,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Florida Federal Judges Strike Down U.S. Sentencing
Guidelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A decision by federal judges in southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to discard federal sentencing guidelines as unconstitutional has been hailed by defense lawyers as bringing humanity back to the courtroom. `` The guidelines were barbaric,'' said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubin </PERSON>, an area director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION>. `` They turned the judges into automatons.'' Defense attorneys had argued the guidelines did not give judges enough discretion in sentencing. Wednesday's 85-page opinion resulted from a rare `` en banc'' hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>'s 16 federal judges, held April 21. `` It's a very thorough and well-reasoned decision,'' said <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> lawyer who spearheaded the arguments against the guidelines. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Roettger </PERSON>, whose courtroom is in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, said he did n't think the change would result in widely different sentences. `` We'll just sentence on the old policy, that's all,'' <PERSON> Roettger </PERSON> said. `` We have been sentencing as we have been for decades. All we're doing is continuing that.'' The guidelines were established by the seven-member <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Sentencing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, set up by the 1984 Comprehensive Crime Control Act, and applied to any offense comitted after Nov. 1, 1987. Written by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON>, the 12-4 opinion finds the guidelines unconstitutional primarily because of the composition of the sentencing commission. Because the commission includes three federal judges, the separation of powers outlined in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution is violated, the judges said. Fixing punishments belongs to the legislative branch of government and can not be established by judges, the opinion said. `` This collaborative rule-making effort between the judicial and the executive branches of government cast too long a shadow over the independence and impartiality of the entire federal judiciary,'' <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON> wrote. `` We conclude that the act is unconstitutional, and until we receive contrary guidance from a higher authority, the guidelines will not be applied in this district.'' Under the decision, those who are awaiting sentencing for convictions or guilty pleas will be dealt with under the old guidelines. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorie </PERSON>, the chief criminal prosecutor in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney's Office, said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will ask that the guidelines remain in force while the decision is appealed. Similar hearings have been held around the country with conflicting opinions on the generally stricter sentencing guidelines included in the 1984 Comprehensive Crime Control Act. On Monday the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> agreed to step into the dispute, and a decision by the high court is expected by early next year, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Steer </PERSON>, general counsel to the sentencing commission in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The guidelines allow sentencing judges to take into account the nature of the crime, the grade of the offense, the amount of harm caused, the community's view of the crime and the sentence's deterrent value
</TEXT>
