 June 11 The Lafayette -LRB- Ind. -RRB- Journal and Courier on the drought: Nothing is as humbling as coming face to face with the fact that despite all of our technology, we remain at the mercy of the natural elements. All forms of natural disasters remind us of this: hurricanes, earthquakes, tornadoes and flood. As we look around the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, we see unfolding yet another of nature's leveling influences. What started as a troublesome dry spell in May has met or surpassed the pessimism of those who early on predicted the worst drought since the Dust Bowl days. ... As we wait and pray for rain, let's not focus only on the bad that the drought produces but the good as well. There is the breaking down of barriers between segments of the community. There is the inward reflection on an individual basis that promotes personal growth. While we all await the miracle of rain, let's remain in tune with the other miracles that continue to occur each day. The tough times will be over before we know it.
