<HEAD>Conservation Chic: Eateries Serve Water on Request Only</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is one in an ongoing series of stories about the effects
of the 1988 drought on the nation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Call it conservation chic: The latest trend in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> cusine is the waterless meal. There's more than civic spirit at work, however. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, an ordinance that took effect at the end of April requires restaurants to serve water on request only. But even outside city limits, many restaurateurs are voluntarily turning off the tap. `` You think about it because of the fires,'' said <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Averna </PERSON>, manager of Splash, a bistro in the seaside celebrity community of <LOCATION> Malibu </LOCATION>, where drought also brings the threat of devastating brush fires. Posh celebrity hangout <ORGANIZATION> Spago </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> is voluntarily dry, as are the <LOCATION> Brown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Chasen </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, an old favorite of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The conservation effort gets a boost this week, as the region's biggest water supplier mails out 200,000 cards to more than 2,000 restaurants to post on tables, outlining the water-on-demand policy The cards bear a picture of a water glass, one-quarter full, and the caption, `` What, no water?'' On the back is an explanation that for each serving of water, it takes three to four times that amount to wash the glass. That's a small but important bit of conservation, with rain and snow runoff in the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, source of much of the state's water, at one-half or less of normal levels, said Metropolitan Water District spokesman <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Skrove </PERSON> The <ORGANIZATION> MWD </ORGANIZATION>, wholesale supplier to water districts serving 14 million people throughout <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, paid the $ 13,000 for printing and mailing the restaurant cards, <PERSON> Skrove </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Restaurant Association supplied the mailing list and is urging members to comply, said <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyker </PERSON>, executive vice president. The benefits of pulling water glasses off the tables, <PERSON> Kyker </PERSON> tells members, are twofold. Not only do they save water and set an example, they also save money by washing fewer dishes. `` It's your obligation to do your role,'' <PERSON> Kyker </PERSON> tells restaurateurs, `` and besides that, it'll save you money.'' The initial response has been good. Diners do n't usually complain once they find they can get water by asking, said Ms. <PERSON> Averna </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> McCague </PERSON>, general manager at the <LOCATION> Brown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION>. But conservation chic is n't for everyone. Stylish Le Dome in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> would n't dream of asking its patrons to sacrifice. Manager <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritz </PERSON> puts it simply but firmly: `` We always serve water, sir.''
