<HEAD>Jury Deliberates In Mecham Criminal Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The jury ...,' to UPDATE with deliberations
under way today.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> said he had a `` clear conscience'' as he awaited a jury's verdict on criminal charges that he concealed a $ 350,000 campaign loan. The jury deliberated for 3 hours and 45 minutes after receiving the case Wednesday, then resumed work today. `` I'll feel better when it's here -LRB- the verdict -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, 64, told reporters as the jury was dismissed for the night. But he added he expected to sleep well because `` I have a clear conscience.'' The former governor again insisted that he and his co-defendant, his brother <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>, were innocent of any crime. But prosecutor <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> <PERSON> Lotstein </PERSON> told the jury in Wednesday's final portion of the closing arguments that the Mechams' `` cloak of innocence has been stripped away thread by thread by thread; <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> stand naked before you now ... because the evidence is overwhelming of their guilt. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, a Republican, took office in January 1987 and was removed April 4 when the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted him of two unrelated impeachment charges. He also was impeached in connection with the loan, but the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> decided not to hear that charge for fear of prejudicing his criminal trial. The Mechams face felony charges of concealing the $ 350,000 loan on financial disclosure reports required by the state. The loan from developer <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> did not appear on <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s personal or campaign finance statements. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, told reporters `` there was absolutely no evidence of intent'' to conceal the loan. The defense said the loan was properly reported as part of a $ 465,000 lump sum that was listed as a campaign contribution from <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, and that the failure to itemize the loan was an innocent mistake by his brother, <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, who was his campaign treasurer. <PERSON> Lotstein </PERSON> disputed a defense claim that the loan was common knowledge because one former top <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> aide said she knew about it. `` To claim that the loan was not a secret from the public because some insiders knew about it would be like claiming that the secret plan for the <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> invasion in World War II was public knowledge because the general that planned it knew about it,'' the prosecutor said. <PERSON> Lotstein </PERSON> contended that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> lied when he told reporters Oct. 30 that he did not owe any loan to <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON>, but that his campaign did, and that he did not intend to repay it. <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> called him shortly afterward, assured <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> he would be repaid, and said his attorney had told him to make the public statement. The defense said <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> had no motive to hide the loan because the report on which it appeared was not filed until a month after the Nov. 4, 1986, election. But <PERSON> Lotstein </PERSON> said a disclosure of the loan early in <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s new administration would have destroyed his image of being anti-special interest. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents and faced from almost nine to 22 years in prison if convicted of all charges. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> faced three similar counts and up to 9 -LCB- years in prison if convicted of all charges.
