<HEAD>Researcher: Sudden Unexpected Death Among Hmong May Be Linked To
Diet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 5 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED STY Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mystery disease that kills seemingly healthy SoutheastCH
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Asian men in their sleep is primarily caused by a</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 diet high in vitamin-deficient white rice, a researcher suggested Thursday. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Munger </PERSON>, a post-doctoral fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>'s division of epidemiology, said his studies show that stress is not the leading cause of Sudden Unexpected Death Syndrome, as some experts have said. <PERSON> Munger </PERSON>, 34, presented his findings Thursday to a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Epidemiologic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, Br humans and monkeys both received the virus from a common ancestor. Monkeys and humans are descendants of primates who lived 20 million to 30 million years ago. The report on African green monkeys by <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON>'s team was published in Nature, a British scientific journal, earlier this month. <PERSON> Carel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulder </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> biologist, in a separate commentary in Nature, said the findings mean `` the human viruses can not have originated from African monkeys in recent times, as had been predicted by many people.'' <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON> says many diseases that afflict humans came from animals, so it was not unreasonable to theorize that AIDS did as well. His complete genetic sequencing of the green monkey virus determined that the simian and human viruses were different. The sequencing involved checking by hand 9,000 base pairs of nucleic acids _ the building blocks of genes. His laboratory has not completed sequencing of the mandrill virus yet, but hybridization, another test, shows it is different from human viruses and the African green monkey virus, <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON> said. `` SIV -LRB- Simian Immunodeficiency Virus -RRB- mandrill is really we think an authentic mandrill virus, not from another species,'' <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON> said. The most intriguing aspect of the two simian viruses is that neither produces illness in the animals that host them. Examining why the simian virus does not produce illness could lead `` to a strategy for producing a vaccine'' to prevent AIDS in humans, <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON> said. Because the African green monkey virus has been fully genetically analyzed, it can be compared with the human virus. <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON>'s laboratory has found that the human virus has an `` R'' gene, which is missing in the simian virus. He said his laboratory staff has already begun `` constructing a recombinant clone of the African green monkey cirus with an ` R' gene We are going to test it to try to induce AIDS.'' <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON> said, `` At this moment, nobody knows the function of this gene. If we prove the ` R' gene is responsible for pathogenicity that is very important. We can have the weapon to attack the human virus. But that is only my dream.'' Meanwhile, work is continuing on the full genetic sequencing of the mandrill virus. The virus was found in two mandrills living in the primate center's forested enclosure. Both were born in the wild and captured and brought to the <LOCATION> Franceville </LOCATION> center, a $ 30 million facility built with <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>'s oil earnings to study infertility. In recent years in it has focused on AIDS research. In April, other scientists at the center claimed to have found two chimpanzees with an AIDS virus. If confirmed, it will be the first time chimpanzees have been found with the disease. As chimpanzees are a closer relative of humans than monkeys, this could be another important step for AIDs research.
</TEXT>
