<SECOND>AM-BRF--Whale Beached,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Pygmy Killer Whale Beached, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLE OF PALMS, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pygmy killer whale beached itself and died at the Isle of Palms of wounds it apparently suffered from sharks, authorities say. The 7-foot-long whale, a type rarely seen, was spotted Wednesday. It beached itself twice but was helped back into the water by swimmers, then pulled back ashore because police feared it would attract sharks to the crowded beach, said police Cpl. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>. The whale died before a veterinarian arrived, officials said. The dead whale was examined by <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, curator of natural science at the <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Mount </PERSON>, a research analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consortium </ORGANIZATION>. It was the only second stranding of a pygmy killer whale on record in the state, with the first two years ago, <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> said. The wounds on the whale's back were probably caused by sharks, he said.
</TEXT>
