<SECOND>AM-India-Drought, Bjt,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought Brings India Back To World Food Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a decade after <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> succeeded in growing enough food to feed itself, drought has forced the world's second most populous nation back to the international food markets. The purchases have been small _ a million metric tons of wheat from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 500,000 metric tons of rice from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> _ and are solely to replenish buffer stocks. But they underscore the limits of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s `` green revolution'' of the early 1970s and how reliant on the weather it remains. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s ability to feed itself also is linked to curbing a population that has reached 800 million and is growing at a rate of 2.2 percent a year. The food problems began last summer when the monsoon failed and a drought moved north into prime farming regions, leading to a winter rice harvest about 10 million tons less than that of the previous year. When the rains did come, another wheat crop was in the fields. That harvest was slightly larger than that of the year before, `` but they needed a fantastic crop to make up for the kharif -LRB- winter rice -RRB- failure,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity. The government has used its food reserves to make up for the shortfall. Reserves have shrunk from 25 million metric tons in July 1987 to about 9.43 million tons, news and other reports said. A metric ton weighs 2,205 pounds and is equivalent to about 1.1 short tons. `` <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> handled the drought well,'' said the diplomat, an agricultural specialist. `` We've had no reports of deaths.'' The government's problem is getting enough of the wheat now being harvested. Farmers, private traders and flour millers have been working to keep the wheat crop off the market to take advantage of the shrinking national reserves and drive up prices. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> recently quoted <ORGANIZATION> Sukh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ram </ORGANIZATION>, minister of state for food and supply, as warning middlemen about hoarding. Hope is focused on the life-bestowing monsoon due to hit <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> in late June. Western officials expect <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to buy more wheat and rice this year, and the strength of the monsoon will determine how much must be purchased. Problems remain even if the weather cooperates and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s grain production continues its modest increase. The green revolution extended only to wheat and rice, and production lags in other areas, according to Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Asrinivasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Sastry </PERSON>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> bought 100,000 metric tons of corn from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> this year and was given 100,000 tons by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Corn imports could total 500,000 tons by the end of the year, the Western diplomat said. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> also remains the world's largest importer of edible oils _ 120,000 tons this year _ and also imports soybeans, lentils, butter oil, non-fat dry milk and small amounts of sugar and cotton. Western officials have criticized <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s agriculture extension service, saying it is not getting necessary information to the farmers. But <PERSON> Sastry </PERSON> said it takes time to disseminate information. About 85 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s wheat-growing land is now irrigated, but the diplomat believes more must be done. <PERSON> Sastry </PERSON> said his ministry is working to increase irrigation, improve dry land farming and increase production in states where water is no problem. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s initial green revolution allowed it to grow as much food as the people could buy, but 200 million people _ 25 percent of the population _ do n't have the money to buy enough food and are malnourished. <PERSON> Sastry </PERSON> said increases in rice and wheat production have leveled off in recent years but said he was not worried about population growth outstripping the country's ability to feed itself. `` But if you want to make a significant step up in production ... There will have to be another green revolution,'' he said.
</TEXT>
