<FIRST>u p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0601 06-16 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,790</SECOND>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERT new grafs 9-11 with Hollings comments bgng ``Hollings
said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> today urged the government to use caution in involving the military in its war on drugs and said that option should be used primarily as a backup. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> testified before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> about prevention and treatment of drug abuse, and in the session senators lavished him with praise for his outspoken leadership on the subject. In answer to a question from Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, about current sentiment in some quarters for legalization of drugs, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> replied, `` That would be a mistake. It would be surrender to the No. 1 threat to our national security. We would not think of legalization of smog because there's a lot of it. It's dangerous.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, commenting on the current effort to use the military in drug interdiction, said, `` We must be careful, however, to avoid involving the military in any police actions against citizens or arrests.'' He said strengthening the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and Customs border patrol should be the first priority in interdiction. `` We should not lead with our military forces in drugs or any other aspect of foreign policy. But the military can play a greater and useful role in backing up these efforts and providing intelligence assistance,'' he said. Before the hearing, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> jokingly pinned a large `` <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> 88'' badge on <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>'s lapel. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, one of the conservative movement's guiding lights, wore the button through the hearing, but joked that `` I thought you were worried sick about the effect it would have on you'' to have such a conservative wearing the badge. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> later met with Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, the only senator who has said he will give <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> his delegate vote at the convention. <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> said he supports <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> because he won <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and he said more Democrats should follow his example `` for the good of the party.'' <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had changed since 1984, when both of them ran for president. `` I would think <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> frightened the bejesus out of them four years ago. I remember him standing up and saying his time has come! ` I want it all,''' <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> said. `` This time he's run a winning campaign. He has n't frightened anyone. He's charmed them in all of those different debates and in his own right has leveled off.'' On Wednesday, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he met with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, who has been interviewing potential running mates to join the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor on the Democratic presidential ticket. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told a news conference he has not yet decided whether he would want the post, only that he has earned `` serious consideration.'' He made the comments after a meeting with the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>, whose members urged him to seek the post and said they will try to meet with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and lobby him to choose <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would not discuss his meeting with <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> but said it was `` a very meaningful preliminary discussion.'' In a Wednesday evening interview on <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> elaborated: `` We simply discussed today the process, discussed the guidelines, we talked about the requirements. After all, we need to know what the rules are, what the standards will be.'' He said he is talking to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> not only about the vice presidency, but about his budget concerns and his proposal to pay for social spending by freezing military spending and hiking taxes on the rich and corporations. He said earlier in the day that his budget priorities are his `` most critical'' concern now that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and he agree on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> policy. `` The most critical becomes this budget, a commitment to invest in people, a commitment to reinvest in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said following a meeting with leaders of civil rights groups. He said he is prepared to go to the convention floor if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> balks. `` Of course, that's the proper mechanism and it's the thing to do,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> when asked if he might wage a floor fight. Asked what would happen if he loses the fight, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> took a philosophical approach: `` Sometimes you win, sometimes you lose. ... If you lose you will at least have left your imprint.'' On the vice presidency issue, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has said previously that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will be considered, but not that he will get any special consideration by being runner up. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> made clear he would like the offer to be made to him although he has declined to say that in so many words publicly, instead stating that it is <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' option.
