<HEAD>Eban Says Party Made Mistake In Ousting Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elder statesman <PERSON> Abba </PERSON> <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> said Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> made a mistake when it pushed him off its slate for the November elections to make room for political newcomers deemed more attractive to voters. <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>, 73, fell victim a new selection system in which for the first time the rank-and-file, not party bosses, chose the slate for the elections to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s parliament, the <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION>. Half the candidates elected Wednesday were political newcomers, and Labor's general secretary, <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Baram </PERSON>, called the outcome a `` revolution'' and `` feast for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s democracy.'' `` It's clearly a disappointment,'' <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` During the years I have accumulated valuable knowledge and experience. I told party members I'm ready to offer this, but if you do n't want it, I wo n't.'' During his 40-year political career, <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> served as deputy prime minister, foreign minister and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>'s ouster was a `` real tragedy, not for him, but for the country. `` I've never known anyone else who I thought had made a greater contribution to his country,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Political analyst <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Galnoor </PERSON> said <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> might have retained his position had the party bosses formed the slate, but the new selection process showed he `` does n't have a following in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' `` Eban is not connected to any influential groups. He's just a bright guy with a terrific sense of humor. Unfortunately, these things are not very admired in Israeli politics,'' said <PERSON> Galnoor </PERSON>, a political scientist at <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Party members did not choose <PERSON> Eban </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s ranked list of candidates for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 120-member <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION>. The number of parliament seats assigned to a party depends on its total vote in the elections. Based on previous election results, Labor candidates in the top 40 to 45 slots are expected to be re-elected. Eleven slots, including the top seven reserved for party leaders, were filled by appointment, not popular vote. Twenty-one of the remaining 34 slots considered `` safe'' were given to newcomers. Four of the newcomers were Sephardic Jews from North African nations, a group that has traditionally voted for Labor's political rival, the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc. <PERSON> Galnoor </PERSON> said the selection might improve <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s chances in the election, but also said such gains could be offset if Labor does n't deliver a clear message on how it will solve the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict Polls have indicated that the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> might lose the election to <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> because many voters have moved to the right in response to the 6-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> leaders say <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will never withdraw from the occupied territories. Labor advocates the return of some land in exchange for peace, but opposes formation of a Palestinian state or the dismantling of Jewish settlements.
