<HEAD>Hundreds Stay Away From Work To Commemorate 1976 Soweto Riots</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd pvs, ``Another suspected...' to
UPDATE with report that guerrillas planned offensive; picks up 5th
pvs: Many factories...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of thousands of blacks stayed away from work today to commemorate the 1976 <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> riots. An explosion killed one man, firebombs wounded three others and a commuter railway was bombed. Police reported the deaths of 11 suspected <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas in the past week, including the man killed today by explosives he was carrying near <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. The man was not identified. Another suspected guerrilla died in an accidental blast Tuesday, and nine were killed by police in two shootouts near the <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> border in the past week, Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said. The state-run South African <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said police were tipped off that Mozambique-based guerrillas would try to enter <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> to stage `` massive acts of terrorism.'' In each case, it said, police stopped vehicles at roadblocks and riddled them with bullets after someone inside opened fire. Many factories shut down, and the largest daily newspaper for blacks, The Sowetan, did not publish. Workers at three diamond mines went on strike to demand that June 16 be designated a paid holiday. The unrest came on the 12th anniversary of a police attack on marching schoolchildren in the black township of <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. Ten people, including two children, died that June 16. The confrontation prompted a nationwide rampage in which hundreds were killed. Commemorative church services were held in many black townships. Security forces reportedly fired tear gas and bird shot because of stone-throwing that occurred as blacks left a church service in <LOCATION> Lamontville </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>. At <LOCATION> Langa </LOCATION>, a black township outside <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, a commuter rail line was bombed at midday. Police headquarters said two officers on patrol flagged down a train approaching the wrecked section of track, averting a possible derailment. Trains coming from <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> reportedly were stoned. Firebombs were thrown at three buses and two delivery vans in other townships, causing serious injuries to three blacks. The main power line between the black township of <ORGANIZATION> KwaMashu </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> was sabotaged during the night, stopping rail traffic for several hours. Later, a train on the route was derailed and commuters had to be transferred to buses. The nation's largest ports were operating normally, but in the eastern <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> province half the workers were absent at <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and there was a total boycott at Port Elizabeth docks. Mining company officials said only 24,500 of 540,000 black employees at major mines were absent. The De Beers mining company said black workers disrupted operations at three mines with a strike to demand that June 16 be designated a paid holiday. It is illegal under national emergency regulations to call for or participate in boycotts or illegal strikes, but many blacks have become accustomed to observing June 16 as a holiday. In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, there are no public holidays commemorating events of specific significance to the 26 million black majority. Many stores and shops in downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> were closed, and only a handful of buses and taxi-vans were operating in the city. Trains arriving from <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> and other nearby black townships were nearly empty. The streets of <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> were almost deserted. About 100 people were scattered along the main road trying to hitch rides. Most of the township's 2.5 million residents appeared to have slept late. The normally teeming main bus station was vacant. About 15 people gathered this morning in Avalon Cemetery at the grave of <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Pieterson </PERSON>, a 13-year-old boy shot by police during the student march in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> in 1976. <PERSON> Pieterson </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Margot </PERSON>, 17, and his nephew, <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Tabane </PERSON>, 6, put flowers on the grave, which bears a marker saying: `` Deeply mourned by his parents, sisters, and a nation that remembers.'' <PERSON> Popi </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>, 29, a young girl who was hurt in the 1976 shootings, came to the graveside service in a wheelchair. The <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> students had been protesting the use of Afrikaans, the language of descendants of Dutch settlers, in their schools. The shooting touched off a nationwide rampage in which, by official count, 575 blacks were killed. The following month, the government announced that blacks could choose the language of instruction in their schools. The anniversary has almost always been marked by violence, particularly confrontations between black crowds and police trying to halt observances. Last year, 11 people died despite a call by anti-apartheid groups for a quiet observances. Slogans were painted on the walls of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, saying, `` <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, Free Us,'' `` South Africa Bleeds,'' and `` <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Will </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Liberate </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' The slogans were painted in yellow, green and black, the colors of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement.
