is 1987 romantic comedy `` Forgotten Melody For A Flute,'' which was screened for the Israeli audience. The movie is about a Soviet bureaucrat who is married to a woman he does n't love but whose influential father promises to help his career. The hero must decide whether to remain married or run off with a poor nurse he loves. `` At last Soviet lovers have sex,'' said one immigrant viewer, referring to a scene in which the adulterous couple is shown naked in bed. Others praised the film for making fun of Soviet censorship and influence peddling.
