for numerous cases of torture and brutality. Radical students accuse <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>; President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, a fellow general who succeeded him; and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of responsibility for military repression of a 1980 civil uprising in the southern city of <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>. Nearly 200 people were killed, according to government figures. Minor clashes were reported Thursday in <LOCATION> Taejon </LOCATION>, another southern city, between police and students denouncing the blockade of a march to the border with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Much larger battles occurred Jun 10 when police stopped thousands of radicals from marching to the border for meetings with North Korean students on reunifying the peninsula, which was divided in 1945. In another development, Chief Justice <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Yong-chun </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday he would resign in response to calls by junior magistrates for judicial reform. On Wednesday, 85 judges issued a statement saying the judiciary is seen as subservient to the government and has not benefited from recent democratic changes. It was the first such collective action by judges in the nation's history. Another 194 judges joined in a supporting statement Thursday and support for the demand is expected to continue growing among the 940 magistrates in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
