<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved a $ 44.1 billion money bill for farm programs and food aid Thursday with fewer complaints this year from urban lawmakers that payment programs have gotten out of hand. `` Everyone's pointing to agriculture like we're the ones who are causing the deficit, like we're all causing all this international debt,'' <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said. He said agriculture represented only a small part of the estimated $ 176 billion budget deficit for the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1. `` They stumble over that much at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>,'' the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat said. Farm payment programs, which include price supports, income supports and conservation payments, peaked at $ 26 billion in 1986. Those programs now are down to an estimated $ 17 billion in fiscal 1988. The drop in overall farm payments has muted somewhat the chorus of complaints that met 1985 legislation designed to alleviate painful problems in the farm economy. But while farm payments have gone down as the farm economy has recovered, a number of critics of `` excesses'' in the farm programs say there still is much to complain about. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 343-54 to approve the money bill amid calls from farm-bloc lawmakers for aid to growers and livestock producers squeezed financially by a drought across broad areas of the country. The bill earmarked no drought aid, however, and most lawmakers said they were inclined to go along with administration suggestions that it would be best to wait until the full extent of the problem becomes clear. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been saying an inch or so of rain once a week for the rest of the growing season would rescue <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> corn and soybeans, although wheat in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION> is in far worse condition. The bill calls for outlays of $ 44.1 billion for the fiscal 1989 for programs ranging from farm payments to food stamps. That is $ 2.5 billion less than requested by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and $ 12 billion below last year's amount. It also is $ 3 billion below an agricultural appropriations bill currently being drawn up in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. It contains $ 16.3 billion for food and nutrition programs, $ 12.4 billion for rural development and $ 6.8 billion to replace losses of the government-owned <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates federal payment programs for farmers. Farm program spending has dropped sharply over the last year as exports expanded and the farm economy shook off the doldrums of the early 1980s. Thus a $ 14.3 billion decrease in funds to cover losses of the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> represents the bill's major savings. Critics, however, said it is optimistic to expect a sale of government-held stocks will yield $ 3 billion to help cover additional losses and hold down costs. `` It appears to me there are lots of mirrors on the ceiling and lots of smoke coming from the cloakroom,'' Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, R-Pa., said Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunderson </PERSON>, R-Wis., said it most likely would be necessary to come back for a supplemental appropriation later The House debated for two hours a plan by Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, to bar further <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> loans to farmers already in default. But farm forces defeated, 310-88, a parliamentary maneuver designed to bring up his proposal for a vote. `` Everybody knows that you do n't lend money to people who never paid you back on you're previous loans,'' <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON> said. `` Everybody but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Farm state lawmakers were quick to take up <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>'s challenge. `` This gentleman who comes here from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and suggests that the farmers are trying to pull the wool over the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> just has n't been there to share the problems,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Durbin </PERSON>, D-Ill. The Targeted Export Assistance program, established in 1985 as a subsidy for overseas advertising and promotion of food exports exports, came under renewed criticism from Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION> `` Even if the program were extremely well run, maybe we ought not to be funding it,'' he said. He pointed to millions of dollars paid out to private companies for advertising campaigns abroad. <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> cited a report from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> that found program mismanagement.
