<HEAD>Peace Corps Expanding Operations, Director Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> is sending volunteers to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> for the first time in 21 years and will begin a new program in the <LOCATION> Comoros </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, agency director <PERSON> Loret </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruppe </PERSON> said Thursday. A <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> assessment team will also go to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> this summer, to plan for the first set of volunteers for that country, Mrs. <PERSON> Ruppe </PERSON> told a luncheon audience at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. The three new programs will bring to nearly 70 the number of countries welcoming the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, and Mrs. <PERSON> Ruppe </PERSON> said the grass-roots agency hopes to grow even bigger. `` Those cynics who wonder if the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> is still around should know that the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president have not only endorsed, but mandated, a five-year growth plan for the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> to double in size to 10,000 volunteers by 1992,'' she said. The agency, whose last program in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> ended in 1967, is sending eight volunteers to <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lahore </LOCATION> this fall to train high school teachers. The emphasis will be on training English teachers, but education courses for biology, chemistry and physics instructors also will be given. Nine volunteers will be assigned to the <LOCATION> Comoros </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, an Islamic nation 250 miles off the coast of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. They will arrive in July for language and cultural training and begin working in September, Mrs. <PERSON> Ruppe </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> program is scheduled to begin sometime next year. Since Chinese Foreign Minister <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xueqian </PERSON>'s announcement in March that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would welcome the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, the agency has received 300 public queries from Americans declaring their eagerness to participate in the Chinese program, said agency spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanigan </PERSON>. `` That's a fairly good number of people expressing an interest in going to a particular country,'' <PERSON> Flanigan </PERSON> said. The Peace Corps never guarantees a volunteer's choice of country, but <PERSON> Flanigan </PERSON> said the agency was bouyed by the interest shown in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. At the time of Wu's announcement, officials said an English-teaching program would be the most likely plan and that the initial complement would be about 50 volunteers. The assessment team will discuss the location of the first group. `` It's very much their call,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Ruppe </PERSON> said of the Chinese. The Peace Corps was created during the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> administration to spread skills to the grass roots of developing countries and broaden the horizons of young Americans. Despite conservative hostility to the agency at the outset of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, it has grown in the past seven years. The <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> gets 200,000 queries a year from potential volunteers, of whom 17,000 fill out applications and 2,600 are accepted. Currently, the agency is particularly interested in people with skills as teacher trainers and agriculture experts, Mrs. <PERSON> Ruppe </PERSON> said. In its expansion plans, the agency will try to increase the size of some of its contingents and try to get more nations to accept volunteers. During its heyday, the agency's biggest program was in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, where up to 1,600 volunteers served. The biggest one is now in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, where there are 300 Peace Corps people. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> would be a fertile ground for new programs, Mrs. <PERSON> Ruppe </PERSON> said. On that continent, only <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> accept volunteers, she said.
