<HEAD>Pentagon Resumes Testing Star Wars Chemical Laser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, recovering from an accident in January, has successfully resumed its testing of a chemical laser that one day could become a key part of any Star Wars anti-missile defense system, officials said Thursday. The latest test of the so-called Alpha laser was conducted Wednesday night behind closed doors at a contractor's laboratory in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Capistrano </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. It marked the final check-out of all the laser components and support equipment and was considered a complete success, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weapons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Kirtland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, N.M. The test replicated all the heat and pressure effects that will exist when a laser beam is produced in the new system, but by design no `` lasing'' was attempted on Wednesday, said <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>. The next and final stage of the testing program _ producing a high-powered laser beam through a chemical reaction _ will probably begin this fall, the spokesman added. The test conducted Wednesday evening had been scheduled several months ago but was put off indefinitely while engineers repaired damage caused during a brief, accidental fire on Jan. 7. The fire at the <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> laboratory resulted from an operating mistake by a worker. Little direct damage was done, but the fire left contaminated the main vacuum chamber needed to simulate firing the laser in outer space, and thus halted all testing. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Weapons Laboratory completed a milestone test of its Alpha laser on Wednesday,'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said in a statement. `` The laser successfully completed a hot flow test with heat released from the cavity. This test verified that all supporting assemblies were operating properly and that <PERSON> Alpha </PERSON> was ready to begin receiving the optical components necessary for full lasing tests.'' The experiment `` was as close as we can get to lasing without actually doing it,'' the spokesman added. The Alpha laser, described by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> as `` the most mature of the -LRB- Star Wars -RRB- directed-energy technologies,'' has been under study for almost a decade. The device is constructed primarily of aluminum, making it relatively light and compact, and draws its energy from the combustion of the gases hydrogen and fluorine. It is thought to generate roughly 2 million watts of power. Last October, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> awarded a contract to <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marietta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, asking it to assess the possibility of conducting experiments in space with Alpha. In the meantime, however, <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> _ which built the device _ began preparing for the first ground tests in the laboratory.
