ION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> starts hundreds of investigations that are carried out over a long period of time. The White House is not aware of most, if not all of, those investigations,'' he said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said `` there always comes a time when any investigation, when it's presented to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for criminal action or whether it's presented to a grand jury for possible indictment, it becomes known to the civilian authority, whether it's the president or the head of the agency or the bureau or whatever. `` I'm sure that in this case, it was simply their judgment that this was the right time to make it known to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the president was `` satisfied that the bureau has acted with the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> quickly and effectively and pursued this investigation.''
