<HEAD>Lawmakers Propose Tightening OSHA Regulations In Wake Of Apartment
Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers who say the <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adminstration </ORGANIZATION> has taken little action to prevent construction accidents such as last year's collapse of a <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> apartment complex that killed 28 workers on Thursday proposed tightening federal laws regulating construction. The legislation would stiffen <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> fines, tighten accident reporting requirements, mandate a professional engineer to oversee construction projects, make negligent employers liable to stiff prison terms and give the agency authority to shut down a work site to investigate an accident. <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> lawmakers drafted the measure following <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearings examining the April 23, 1987, collapse of <LOCATION> L'Ambiance </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION>, a half-built apartment complex in <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. L'Ambiance Plaza was the worst construction accident in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> history `` It has been more than a year since <PERSON> L'Ambiance </PERSON> collapsed,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Shays </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., the chief <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spnosor `` Tragically, we have seen little movement to change any of the factors that contributed to the accident.'' <PERSON> Shays </PERSON> said he hoped the bill would `` arm <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> with the proper tools to help fulfill its mandate to protect worker health and safety.'' Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., the chief sponsor in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, said the country `` must not tolerate any more <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> or L'Ambiance Plazas or any of the thousands of other accidents that claim lives and futures and could be avoided if industry and government act swiftly and responsibly. L'Ambiance Plaza was the nation's worst construction accident since a cooling tower under construction in <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, collapsed in 1978, killing 51. The Shays-Weicker bill: _ Requires an onsite engineer or architect to oversee construction projects. _ Increases maximum <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> construction fines from $ 10,000 per violation to $ 25,000. _ Increases maximum criminal penalties for first-time `` willful violations'' from six months in prison and $ 10,000 in fines to 10 years in prison and $ 250,000 in fines. Repeat offenders would be subject to 20 years in prison and $ 500,000 in fines. _ Gives <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials the authority to close down a work site to investigate an accident. _ Mandates employers to report accidents and for <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials to inspect within 24 hours when there are at least three workers hospitalized, one `` life-threatening'' injury or fatality or a collapse, partial collapse or near collapse of a building. Under current <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> regulations, contractors are required to report an accident only if a worker is killed or at least five are seriously injured, and there is no mandate for <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> inspections.
