<HEAD>Task Force: Make Careful Vice Presidential Choices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Presidential candidates should thoroughly evaluate their running mates and not make hasty decisions for the occupant of the office a heartbeak away from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, political experts said Thursday. `` The speed with which vice presidential candidates are selected can still create serious problems,'' according to a report prepared by a task force that included former top aides to Presidents <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. The report, commissioned by the 20th Century Fund, a non-profit research organization, said the position of vice president, long the butt of jokes, is critical because it is so close to the Oval Office. To ensure the best person gets the nod, presidential candidates could use a mix of tools: questionnaires, interviews, polls and informal inquiries. In the end, however, politics plays a big role in the selection. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, respectively the expected 1988 Democratic and Republican presidential nominees, have not revealed their choice of running mate, but the issue is attracting widespread attention. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>, a former aide to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, recalled that Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., was a compromise vice presidential candidate in 1976 Although <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> maintains <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was an asset, others viewed <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> as `` not a good candidate.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> lost the election to <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. `` All too often you end up making the decision at 2 a.m.,'' <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Heclo </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, criticized the selection process. He said vice presidential candidates <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> in 1964; <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON> in 1972; <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> in 1968 and <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON> in 1984 were not `` shining successes of finding what the Founding Fathers used to call the continental character.'' <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON>, the only one of those candidates elected, was forced out of office in a corruption scandal. On balance, the experts said the vice presidency is a healthy if imperfect institution in which the incumbent can play a role advising the president on a range of issues and representing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> abroad. But <PERSON> Helco </PERSON> and two other panel members, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s former aide, and <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuss </PERSON>, former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, suggested the vice presidency does more harm than good and should be abolished. `` All you are trying to do is create some stand-by equipment,'' said <PERSON> Heclo </PERSON>, who argued that a special election could be held to choose a successor to a disabled president. <PERSON> Reuss </PERSON> criticized the `` imperial nature'' of the vice presidency, which comes with a mansion, a seal and its own aircraft, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Two. The vice president also has a large staff. `` The modern vice presidency that has developed with little forethought over the past 30 years is proving a more disruptive than constructive feature of our political system,'' the dissenters said.
