<HEAD>Tastes Great, Less Filling, Big Trouble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Call them big, call them hefty _ hey, call'em huge _ but do n't say the Fat Boys, those high-calorie rappers, drink <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> Lite </PERSON> beer. The three beefy bandmates charged in a federal lawsuit this week that the <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> intimated just that in one of its Lite commercials _ the one where an immense <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> `` Rapping Fats'' <PERSON> Piscopo </PERSON> raps that the `` less-filling'' brew `` tastes great.'' The suit says <PERSON> Piscopo </PERSON>'s obese appearance and rapping have left a bad taste in the <ORGANIZATION> Fat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>' mouths _ one that the comic, the beer company and its ad agency should pay $ 5 million to remove. `` In their efforts to promote the sale of alcohol, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> intentionally selected and exploited the likenesses and performing musical styles of the Fat Boys,'' the suit filed Monday charged. The portly plaintiffs are <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> -LRB- better known as `` Prince Markie Dee'' -RRB-, <PERSON> Damon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wimbley </PERSON> -LRB- aka `` Kool Rock Ski'' -RRB- and <PERSON> Darren </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> -LRB- `` The Human Beat Box'' -RRB-, along with the group's record company and music publisher. They're asking for $ 5 million in damages and withdrawal of the commercial. They allege the ad, which features <PERSON> Piscopo </PERSON> rolling around on a huge bogus belly while rapping with three heavyweight partners, takes advantage of their platinum-selling record success and infringes on the Fat Boys trademark. That's right. The Fat Boys received Registration No. 1,351,054 from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Patent and <ORGANIZATION> Trademark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> for their name on July 23, 1985. `` The weight of the members _ their actual physical size _ combined with other elements of music, costume and performance style constitutes an identifiable and unique characteristic of the group,'' the lawsuit said. It also alleges the commercial's music, particularly the vocal percussion of one rotund performer behind <PERSON> Piscopo </PERSON>, `` contains a melody copied from -LRB- and -RRB- derived from'' the Fat Boys' music. A spokesman for the comedian, <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, had no immediate comment on the suit. The ad agency, <ORGANIZATION> Backer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Spielvogel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, declined comment; a <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> spokesman was not in the company's <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> headquarters to react to the suit.
