<HEAD>Drought Takes Toll on Nation's Rivers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A drought parching much of the country dropped water levels in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> rivers, making the waterways unnavigable Thursday and meaning `` major-league'' losses for the inland shipping industry. A seven-mile stretch of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, remained closed to all traffic while a dredge deepened a shallow channel. Dozens of towboats and barges were stranded. Meanwhile, nearly 700 barges in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> were tied up north and south of the <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, bridge because the river had dropped to the lowest levels since authorities began keeping records in 1872. `` Everybody is concerned,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkop </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The group comprises industry, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> officials who monitor river conditions. `` We've experienced tough river conditions and closures before, but nothing this bad,'' said <PERSON> Brinkop </PERSON>. He said the industry is losing `` major-league dollars'' because of the traffic stoppage. Towboat crews stranded on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> rivers spent their time painting, watching television, doing light maintenance and even fishing while each towboat owner loses about $ 10,000 daily. <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Shumann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, said a 300-foot stretch of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> had water levels of about eight feet _ the lowest mark there since January 1969. For safe passage, he said barges need at least 8.11 feet of water. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paducah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, closed the river. It was to reopen Thursday night, but underground cables and debris forced a delay until Friday afternoon. In the past two weeks, more than a dozen barges have gone aground near the <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> area, said Guard spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Buri </PERSON>. The dredge <ORGANIZATION> Elco </ORGANIZATION> was summoned to dig a 2,100-foot channel 11 feet deep by 250 feet wide, he said. Low water in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> has created bottlenecks in places like <LOCATION> Vaucluse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Landing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, about three miles north of the <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, bridge. An <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> patrol </ORGANIZATION> boat has been escorting barges with light loads one-by-one, and prospects for ending the bottleneck north of <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> brightened Thursday. Spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Logue </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> marked a previously unknown secondary channel at <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>. He said it appeared smaller towboats would be able to use it. `` Since we found the secondary channel, it looks like the small tows will be able to go ahead and pass,'' <PERSON> Logue </PERSON> said. `` The larger tows will have to wait.'' Authorities said it would take at least a day and possibly two to dredge a channel 16-feet to 20-feet deep that could handle larger barges. On board the stranded towboats, crews made the best of it. `` There's plenty of work, there's always something to do,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Southern </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Paducah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, a first mate on the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON> on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. `` Some people are even trying to fish.'' Idle barges also worried shippers like <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Crafton </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Henderson </LOCATION>, Ky. He depends on barges to deliver his petroleum products. `` Our last shipment was delayed about a day,'' he said. `` The river conditions concern me. Like everyone else, I'm hoping for some rainfall.''
