<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday to approve full funding of science, space and technology programs despite efforts to balance the federal budget. In a letter to key lawmakers, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the bipartisan budget agreement reached by the administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in November was designed to `` put the federal government firmly on the path toward elimination of the budget deficit.'' `` Achievement of that critically important objective requires those in office to make difficult choices among competing priorities,'' he said. `` We have considered the full range of federal programs and their competing demands on scarce taxpayers' dollars and have concluded that full funding of science, space and technology programs must remain a top priority.'' `` I urge the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to provide full funding and support for these programs,'' the president said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s letter was addressed to Sens. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., and <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, and Reps. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boland </PERSON>, D-Mass., and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, the chairmen and ranking minority members, respectively, of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appropriations subcommittees that will review science and technology
