<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You ca n't get a ticket for running a red light in <LOCATION> Carroll </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. There are none. The county's last traffic signal was turned off this month when Avenue Elementary School closed. There are fewer than 19,000 residents over 600 square miles in the county in the northwest <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Missisippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Savanna </LOCATION>, with 4,500 residents, had the last traffic light. `` It was green all the time unless somebody pushed the button on it,'' Comptroller <PERSON> Corrine </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. The signal was installed near the school to control traffic when children and school employees crossed the street, Superintendent <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierson </PERSON> said. The county will be free of red lights through at least 1989, but a traffic signal will be erected in <LOCATION> Savanna </LOCATION> when a bridge construction project is finished.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> says it was in the stars that he should be honored as the 50 millionth person to ride the city's public transportation system. His horoscope predicted he had a chance to win a contest. `` Do you realize what the odds are _ 50 million to one?'' <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` I should be so lucky when I play the lottery.'' On Tuesday morning, after a dispatcher alerted drivers that the 50 millionth rider was about to board a bus, drivers handed out a registration form to the next passenger to get on or off their bus. <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON>'s form was drawn from the 36 returned. Before the drawing Wednesday, <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said his wife, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, telephoned him at work and read the horoscope for Virgo: `` Lunar position accents popularity, ability to persuade, valid chance to win contest.'' `` I got the biggest bang out of that,'' <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said. `` I said, ` Well, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and I, we read them.' I do n't really take it too seriously.'' <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON>, 61, will receive a two-night vacation for four in <LOCATION> Pigeon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, a resort area near <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Smoky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, a free bus pass for a year and other prizes.
