super delegates'' in whose states and districts he won the popular vote. Super delegates are Democrats who will have votes at the convention by virtue of their elected or party leadership positions. Later <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters that the Democratic leadership, `` while accepting my investment in the party to make it strong, has not been as reciprocal as it ought to be.'' `` The people have spoken and now leadership should catch up with the people,'' he said. `` If in fact I have injected nothing in the party, I should expect no return. If I invest I should reasonably expect return,'' he told reporters. `` So I appreciate the accolades that I am the voter registration champion for the party, that I have led the drive to return the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> back to the Democrats, that I have won states that no one said I could win.'' However, he added, `` If I have done all of that, I simply say let's be fair.'' He was praised earlier Thursday by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, before whom he testified on drug abuse prevention and treatment. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who has made the drug issue a centerpiece of his presidential campaign, told the committee that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces should not be used as the primary interdiction force, but rather should be used for backing up other agencies and providing intelligence. `` We must be careful, however, to avoid involving the military in any police actions agianst citizens or arrests,'' he said. `` We should not lead with our military forces in drugs or any other aspect of foreign policy.'' <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., and the other senators thanked <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for his years as an outspoken leader against drugs and for his work with young people Later <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> joined <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> at a rally outside the Capitol denouncing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as a terrorist state. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> urged support for anti-apartheid legislation.
