ure in the Switzerland-sized jurisdiction. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Vanjo </PERSON> was relieved `` in connection with a transfer under the jurisdiction'' of the Moscow-based <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the party's policy-making body. The Committee could assign him to a job in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> or elsewhere in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. His replacement, <PERSON> Vaelaes </PERSON>, 57, served earlier as a secretary of the Estonian party. In a separate biographical note, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> indicated the choice of <LOCATION> Vaelaes </LOCATION> was not unanimous, saying he received `` the majority of the votes'' from <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Such decisions are usually unanimous. <PERSON> Vaelaes </PERSON> began his political career in <LOCATION> Tartu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, where he was elected head of the city's <LOCATION> Komsomol </LOCATION> _ young Communist league _ after graduating from <ORGANIZATION> Tartu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. He went on to lead the party organization in <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s capital, for 10 years, and then was elected a party secretary for the republic-wide party apparatus He joined the diplomatic corps in 1980, and served as Soviet ambassador to <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tobago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.
