<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSLaws     06-16 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Laws,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laws Preserving AIDS Confidentiality Limited, Professor Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Laws protecting confidentiality for AIDS patients are less effective than those aimed at preventing discrimination in areas such as jobs and housing, a law professor writes in a leading medical publication. When it comes to AIDS infection, legal protection of medical confidence is often an illusion, said Professor <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickens </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. `` While some laws appear to require and provide secrecy of medical data, others compel disclosures,'' he wrote in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> He cited examples in non-AIDS cases in which courts have ruled that public policies favoring confidentiality must yield when it is necessary to prevent danger to others. `` The protection privilege ends where the public peril begins,'' he said, quoting a <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision concerning the appropriateness of warning a person believed to be in danger of attack from a mental health patient. In general, high legal principles exist to justify the breaking of some medical confidences, regardless of laws to preserve those confidences, <PERSON> Dickens </PERSON> wrote. An example, he said, would be a spouse's right to know if her mate is infected with the AIDS virus, because the information pertains to a risk to her life, he wrote. If potential victims ca n't be identified, disclosing the names of people with AIDS-related conditions to health authorities might be legally justifiable even if it is n't specifically required by law, according to the article. Currently, all 50 states require that diagnoses of AIDS be reported to health authorities, he said. Some states require the names of people diagnosed with the disease be reported. A number of states mandate reporting of every laboratory test that indicates infection is present, <PERSON> Dickens </PERSON> said. AIDS, a fatal and incurable viral illness, is believed to be passed mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during birth. The disease has struck more than 64,000 people in this country since 1979 and killed more than 36,000 of them, according to the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. Laboratory tests for AIDS infection do not indicate whether a person has the disease, but only if the virus that causes it has entered his system. It can be years between infection and the appearance of symptoms. <PERSON> Dickens </PERSON> said that rather than beefing up laws protecting confidentiality, it makes more sense to reinforce laws prohibiting discrimination against people with AIDS, with related conditions or people suspected of being infected. He praised a proposal in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> aimed mainly at curbing discrimination in areas such as housing, employment, education, insurance and access to medical care. The measure, an amendment to the federal <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Act </ORGANIZATION>, does not omit guidelines to protect confidentiality, but couples them with anti-discrimination provisions, he wrote. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Graff </PERSON>, legal director for <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advocates </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, agreed. `` Our position has been is that it is important to have confidentiality and anti-discrimination laws working in tandem to protect individuals,'' he said by telephone Thursday. `` And we know that this works.''
</TEXT>
