<HEAD>Supreme Court Ruling Postpones Murder Trials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 First-degree murder trials are on hold until the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> can decide if the <LOCATION> Duval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury is legal. Defense attorneys claim the jury has too many members, making it easier for prosecutors to win an indictment. The high court granted a stay in a murder trial scheduled to begin next week, causing the postponement of all trials in which the defendants were indicted. Chief Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said Wednesday the ruling means none of the 17 first-degree murder cases in <LOCATION> Duval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> will be able to go to trial. But <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said the current grand jury will keep indicting people for first-degree murder, which carries a penalty of life in prison or death in the electric chair. The high court ruling came Tuesday in the case of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> man already convicted and sentenced to death in one slaying, and to go on trial Monday on a second first-degree murder charge. His attorneys, Assistant Public Defenders <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuinness </PERSON>, argued the case should be postponed until the grand jury issue is resolved. They claim <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> laws require a maximum of 18 grand jurors be impaneled at one time. <LOCATION> Duval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s grand jury has 23 members. They claim because it only takes 12 members to vote for an indictment, it is easier to get 12 of 23 jurors than 12 of 18. Prosecutors, however, claim the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> gives larger counties the right to impanel up to 23 jurors and their position was upheld by Chief Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Santora </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. The public defenders appealed to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said it could be three months before the justices rule. If the high court rules that <LOCATION> Duval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> was incorrect, <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said a new grand jury can be impaneled and the defendants re-indicted. The only possibility of serious problems, he said, would be if the high court voided past convictions. The county has been using 23 grand jurors since 1970.
