<HEAD>Hanover High Students Break Leapfrogging Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Amid the empty Gatorade bottles, flattened tubes of sun block and stacks of fetid sweat socks, 14 <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> students leapfrogged their way into the record books Thursday. Actually, the pace was more like a few steps of jogging, then a leap. And the 14 _ who were at it on the soccer field in two-hour shifts, round-the-clock since Friday afternoon _ were n't exactly bounding with energy. But according to the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>, that qualifies as leapfrogging, and at 11:30 a.m. the students `` frogged'' past 662 miles, breaking the record set by a fraternity at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonz </PERSON>, both seniors, made the record leap. `` People ask which hurts more _ the bending or the leaping,'' said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, 17, between swigs of Gatorade. `` It's the jogging in between.'' The students, who planned to continue leaping until they reach 888 miles _ estimated to happen sometime Saturday morning _ are raising money for the <ORGANIZATION> Norris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth-Hitchcock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. So far, passers-by have donated $ 2,000, and the students are n't sure how much they will raise in pledges The students formed four-person teams to frog in shifts of two hours on, four off. In between, they cheer each other on, eat, sleep, spray each other down with hoses, soak aching ankles in coolers of ice and take final exams. `` I studied this morning at seven o'clock with flash cards,'' while leaping, said <PERSON> Brendan </PERSON> <PERSON> Creagh </PERSON>, 18. <PERSON> Creagh </PERSON> said the students are averaging 19 leaping miles a day, most of it in temperatures in the 90s during the first heat wave of the summer. A cluster of tents in one corner of the field, called `` Frogville,'' is home to the leapers, and candles in paper bags mark the path around the field at night. In one tent are some instruments and a stereo, upon which the students played the theme from the film `` Chariots of Fire'' as they broke the record. Despite the excitement, most of the leapers are looking forward to the end. `` I have not done it before and I will not do it again,'' <PERSON> North </PERSON> said.
