<HEAD>Pentagon Changing Policy On Coverage Of Persian Gulf Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Pentagon has decided to stop forming `` pools'' of reporters to cover <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> operations in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> and instead will try to accommodate requests from news organizations on an individual basis to board <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships. The change in policy, announced Thursday in a brief statement, does not change the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s commitment `` to keeping the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people informed about the activities of military personnel serving in the gulf,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. Rather, the department is now going to try `` to accommodate the many requests received from news organizations asking for the opportunity to send representatives to ships in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>,'' the statement added. `` We're ending the pool,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary for public affairs. `` We will come up with a procedure that works for everyone. This is as much a result of requests from various news organizations as it is at our inception.'' The Pentagon has operated a `` regional press pool'' in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> for almost a year now, helping the news media to cover the efforts of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to protect reflagged <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> oil tankers plying the waterway. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> is a key ally of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the Iran-Iraq war and won permission from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration last year to re-register its ships under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag after they became special targets of Iranian forces. Under the press pool procedure, a small group of reporters representing the major wire services, broadcast networks, news magazines and daily newspapers was formed periodically and sent to sea with <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warships escorting tankers. The dispatches filed by the pool reporters were then sent through military channels and released to all news outlets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The pool system is commonly used by the press when there are more reporters asking to cover an event than there are spaces available. A pool reporter is expected to share with all other reporters the information he gathers on the media's behalf. According to Thursday's statement, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has now decided that absent an emergency or the outbreak of fighting, there is no need to keep dispatching press pools to ensure coverage. Rather, efforts will now be made to accommodate individual reporters from organizations that have not been part of the pool. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Persian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pool </ORGANIZATION> will be discontinued on July 1 and in its place, unilateral embarkations will begin, with plans for a contingency pool as necessary,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The success of the regional pool was due to the cooperative efforts of news organizations and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> to solve the problems faced in working in a difficult environment. But the time has come to make this change.'' The procedures for setting up regional and national press pools were devised in the wake of the 1983 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, during which the Pentagon prohibited news coverage.
