<HEAD>North Dakota Farmer Says 1,000 Acres Of His Grain Lost To Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STERLING, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> looked across a 30-acre wheat field Thursday, at shafts of grain barely a foot tall and shriveling from the prolonged drought that has hit <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> harder than any other state. `` The best purpose for this right now is the cows,'' he said, digging into dirt that was bone dry three inches below the surface. `` What we are trying to do now is get enough grazing to get the cattle through the summer.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s farm, which has received less than an inch of precipitation since January, normally would be lush and green this time of year. Instead, his pastures are parched and his grain crops are wilted. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> figures the 1,000 acres of wheat, oats and barley that he planted this spring already have been wiped out. `` We are not even going to start the combine this year from what I can see.'' <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> farmers are selling off cattle, plowing under crops and filing crop insurance claims while the drought Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> characterizes as the worst since Dust Bowl days grips the state from border to border. The drought is expected to cost the state 40 percent of its farm income and seal the fate of many farmers who already were struggling financially. `` We did n't need this,'' said economist <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Leholm </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` The economy in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> was starting to rebound. We had crop prices that were starting to rise, not wildly, but mildly. Livestock prices were pretty decent,'' <PERSON> Leholm </PERSON> said. The drought could cost the state's economy at least $ 2.7 billion, a loss that could throw it into another tailspin, <PERSON> Leholm </PERSON> said. Direct crop losses on wheat, barley and oats will total about $ 500 million. Because market prices are higher, producers will also receive about $ 400 million less in federal deficiency payments, he said. `` We have got large sections of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> where they are estimating that 70 percent of the crop is already gone,'' <PERSON> Leholm </PERSON> said. The drought is more widespread than the last one in 1980, <PERSON> Leholm </PERSON> said. `` The last real wipe-out was in 1961,'' he said. If adequate rain does n't fall by mid-July, the threshhold for planting later forage crops, another 10 percent of the state's farmers could be put out of business, he said One crop insurer, Rain and <ORGANIZATION> Hail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, already has received about 500 crop damage claims from its 4,500 policy holders, said <PERSON> Eldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wollmann </PERSON>, a field supervisor. `` They are coming in at about 100 a day lately now. And that's only going to get worse,'' <PERSON> Wollmann </PERSON> said `` I would guess that there would be very few insured we have policies with that would not be filing some kind of claim.'' An estimated 40 percent of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s farmers carry crop insurance, which basically covers a farmer's cost of production, officials said. `` The way they are looking right now, if we get by paying $ 7 million to $ 8 million -LRB- in losses -RRB-, we will be lucky. It could be double that, easily,'' <PERSON> Wollmann </PERSON> said. For <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, his major struggle right now is trying to find feed for his 160 head of cattle, a herd his family has been building for 20 years. Already, he's sold off 32 cows and some calves for lack of feed. `` I am sure, if things do n't change, there will be some more going.'' His alfalfa fields are brown, except for low spots that might yield some bales of hay if it rains, he said. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> intends to maintain at least 100 cows, which could force him to ship the cows elsewhere, perhaps <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, for feeding this winter, he said. Weather forecasts are so depressing <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> has quit listening to them. What he would have heard Thursday was a prediction of temperatures in the 90s and high winds. `` You watch the sky and hope. That's about it,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said.
