<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Blacks took a self-proclaimed national holiday Thursday, boycotting jobs and praying at churches to commemorate the 1976 <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> riots that set off months of violence. Two bombings were reported in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> and police said a guerrilla blew himself up accidentally. The first bomb wrecked part of a commuter rail line in the city's black township of <PERSON> Langa </PERSON> and the second went off in the lobby of a civic center during a meeting of the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, causing damage but no injuries. Reports said some trains from <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> were stoned and passengers had to lie on the floor. Firebombs were thrown at buses and delivery vans in other townships, causing serious injuries to three blacks. Police said the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the main guerrilla movement fighting white domination, had planned a major offensive to coincide with the anniversary but was at least partially thwarted. Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said 11 suspected guerrillas had been killed in the past week. One was killed Thursday near <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> by explosives he was carrying, another blew himself up Tuesday and nine, including three women, were killed by police in two shootouts near the <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> border, <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said. The state-run South African <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said police were tipped off that guerrillas based in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> would try to enter <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> for `` massive acts of terrorism'' Thursday. In each of the two shootouts, it said, police stopped vehicles at roadblocks and riddled them with bullets after someone inside opened fire. The African National <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement from its headquarters in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> paying homage to blacks killed in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> 12 years ago and pledging to `` escalate our political and military offensive.'' Many blacks have regarded June 16 as a holiday since 1976, when nationwide rioting broke out after police fired on a student march in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s main black township. At least 575 blacks were killed in the ensuing months, when the anti-apartheid movement acquired a new militancy. No official holidays mark events of specific significance to the 26-million black majority, but several black unions have negotiated with employers to have June 16 as a day off. Many factories closed Thursday, and the largest daily newspaper for blacks, The Sowetan, did not publish. Workers at three diamond mines struck to demand that their employer, <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Beers </PERSON>, join other companies in making the day a paid holiday. Commemorative church services were held in several black townships. Reports said security forces fired tear gas and bird shot because of stone-throwing that occurred as blacks left a church service in <LOCATION> Lamontville </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>. About 15 people gathered at <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>'s Avalon Cemetery at the grave of <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Pieterson </PERSON>, a 13-year-old shot by police during the march in 1976. <PERSON> Pieterson </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Margot </PERSON>, 17, and his nephew, <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Tabane </PERSON>, 6, put flowers on the grave, which bears a marker saying: `` Deeply mourned by his parents, sisters, and a nation that remembers.'' <PERSON> Popi </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>, 29, wounded in the 1976 shootings, came to the service in a wheelchair. Later, 1,500 people attended a service at <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>'s largest <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. At one point, two white men in civilian clothes were chased by members of the crowd who thought they were policemen and grabbed cameras they were carrying. The crowd dispersed hastily after the service with many policemen looking on. The <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> students 12 years ago had been protesting a range of grievances, particularly the use of Afrikaans in their schools. In July 1976, the government announced that black schools could choose their language of instruction but activists say most other demands, generally related to giving black communities more control over their schools, have not been met. Mining executives said 24,500 of 540,000 black employees at major mines were absent Thursday. The biggest stayaway was at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kinross </ORGANIZATION> gold mine, where 86 percent of black workers were absent. <ORGANIZATION> Kinross </ORGANIZATION> was the site of the nation's worst gold mine disaster when 177 men, all but five of them black, died in a fire in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which carries hundreds of thousands of black commuters from their townships, reported a 90-95 percent stayaway in the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> area, 50-80 percent in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> and about 30 percent in <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>. Many stores in downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> because black employees were absent.
