<HEAD>NBC-Journal Poll Finds 15-Point Dukakis Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential contender <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held a 15-point lead over Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll released Thursday, largely on the strength of overwhelming support for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> among women. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was supported by 49 percent of the registered voters in the poll, to 34 percent for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reported. Among men the split was 46-40 for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, but among women his margin was 52-28. The national survey of 2,014 adults was conducted June 9-12. Its result was similar to that of a Gallup poll, conducted June 10-12, that found a 14-point <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> lead. Two other polls early in June put his lead in single digits; others in May had <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' lead as great as 16 points. The `` gender gap'' facing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also appeared in an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll last month, which suggested he trailed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> narrowly among men but by a 2-1 margin among women. In another measure, the <ORGANIZATION> NBC-Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll Thursday found that only 38 percent of women said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cares about people like them. In another important measure of voter sentiment, poll respondents said by a 2-1 margin that it is time for the nation to change direction rather than to follow the course set by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. And while 49 percent approved of the job <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has been doing as president, 39 percent disapproved. Respondents disapproved, 48 percent to 41 percent, of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's handling of the nation's illegal drug problem _ an issue in which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has taken a prominent role. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was rated higher than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on handling the nation's economic problems, reducing the federal deficit and dealing with drugs <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was rated higher on defense and foreign policy. The margin of sampling error in the telephone survey was three percentage points.
