<HEAD>Former Governor Still An Outsider</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s tumultuous ride as governor of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> ruined his business and landed him in two courts. But it left him the same man as when he started: a political outsider railing at the system that refused to work in his favor. Eighteen months ago the outspoken Republican was at the top, a prosperous automobile dealer who had finally won the chance to govern his state after five tries for the office. Now the governorship and the auto business are gone, one lost when he was convicted by the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in an impeachment trial, the other sold because business was lagging under the weight of bad publicity. Now another critical chapter has been closed: <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>, were acquitted Thursday of criminal charges related to the alleged concealment of a campaign loan. The 64-year-old ex-governor had faced six felony counts and up to 22 years in prison on charges of hiding a $ 350,000 campaign loan on personal and campaign financial reports required by the state. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faced three similar counts and up to 9 -LCB- years in prison. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> insisted throughout his trial that the charges were based on `` smoke and mirrors,'' but he had stopped short of predicting that the <ORGANIZATION> Maricopa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury would find him innocent. Although he said for months he wanted nothing more than to get the facts out regarding the loan from attorney <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON>, neither <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> nor his brother took the stand during seven days of testimony. It was an uncommon spell of official silence for the combative <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, who testified in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> impeachment court and who never shrunk from speaking his mind as governor. As <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s chief executive he angered many constituents by canceling a Martin Luther King holiday on grounds it was illegally created and by saying he did n't believe the slain civil rights leader deserved a holiday. He was criticized for defending a book's use of the word `` pickaninny'' for blacks. Other statements deeply offended Jews, homosexuals, women and Japanese-Americans. But <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> never backed away from his comments, and he remained defiant even after the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted him April 4 on impeachment charges of misusing money from a state protocol fund and trying to thwart an investigation of a death threat. A son of Mormon farmers, a fighter pilot in World War II, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> put himself through college by selling cars in the rural town of <LOCATION> Ajo </LOCATION>. In 1950 he moved his <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> dealership to <LOCATION> Glendale </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> suburb. He published his own newspaper in the 1960s as an alternative to the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> press. He also developed a virtual hobby of running for public office. He won his first race in 1960, gaining a two-year term in the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. But he lost a 1962 bid for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and ran unsuccessfully for governor four times, including a near-miss in the 1978 election against Democrat <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>. Fortune finally turned in <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s favor in 1986, when he shocked the political establishment by winning the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> primary and the three-way general election race. Even after taking over as governor, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> saw himself as an outsider attacked by an establishment of legislative leaders, the news media and Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON>, a fellow Republican. In <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s eyes, those forces conspired to force him out of office and into criminal court. But even before the jury returned its verdict, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> declared he had been vindicated by the testimony. It `` has been totally revealed to the world that there was no conspiracy -LRB- to hide the loan -RRB-,'' the former governor said when the defense had rested its case. Although <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> often appeared haggard during his legal ordeal, at other times he seemed anything but a broken man as he joked with the reporters he has blamed for helping bring him down. In any case, he insisted all along that nothing would destroy his peace of mind. He often quoted <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, saying he would be happy if he eventually won out but if he did n't, `` 10 angels swearing I was right wo n't make any difference.''
