<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior official in the Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> blamed nationalists influenced by the Armenian Orthodox Church for protests in a territorial dispute, a Hungarian newspaper said Thursday. In what it called an exclusive interview with <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> state prosecutor <PERSON> Ilias </PERSON> <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hirlap </ORGANIZATION> quoted him as saying the disputed <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region `` has never belonged to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'' and `` any return is out of the question.'' The parliaments, or Supreme Soviets, of the two southern republics held separate votes this week. <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>'s decided not to give up <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and the Armenian parliament backed demands by protesters that the mountainous region to be incorporated into <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. About 80 percent of <PERSON> Ngorno-Karabakh </PERSON>'s 160,000 people are ethnic Armenians. It was assigned to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in 1923 but Armenians consider it part of their ancestral homeland. `` You can only return what has been taken from you, legally or illegally,'' <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` <LOCATION> Karabakh </LOCATION> has never been part of Armenian territory.'' <PERSON> Magyar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirlap </PERSON> did not say when it obtained the interview with <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON>, which it said was conducted in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Unrest over the fate of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> began in February with mass street protests in the Armenian capital, <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, and strikes and protests in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. Violence folowed in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, where 32 people were killed in ethnic rioting in the port city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, most of them ethnic Armenians. Soviet authorities said a policeman was killed in further unrest in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> last week. The Soviet Communist party daily Pravda reported last Friday that a general strike had virtually shut down industry and agriculture in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> for three weeks. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hirlap </ORGANIZATION> report, <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> said: `` What is happening in <LOCATION> Karabakh </LOCATION> was well organized in advance ... by Armenian nationalists ... and under the influence of <LOCATION> Echmiadzin </LOCATION>,'' center of the Armenian Orthodox Church. `` The whole ideology originated in <LOCATION> Echmiadzin </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> said, referring to the religious center outside <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>. Despite his accusations associating <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s church with the unrest, <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> said the conflict should not be seen as a religious clash between Armenian Christians and the predominantly Moslem people of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. `` There is an attempt to give a religious color to the conflict, saying Christians do not want to live under Moslem sovereignty,'' <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> said. `` To put it mildly, this is a malicious approach to the question _ there is no religious basis to this conflict.''
