<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Search Warrant Outlines Theory of Government Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A search warrant obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and made public Thursday reveals the background and the theory of the government's investigation into possible corruption involving the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and private contractors. The following are excerpts from that search warrant, which was issued by a federal judge in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> in response to the <ORGANIZATION> Justioce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> request to search an office at <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest defense contractor: `` <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> resigned from his position as Assistant Secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> for Research, Engineering and Systems in April, 1987. In April, 1987, <ORGANIZATION> PAISLEY </ORGANIZATION> opened his own private consulting business in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> area. As a consultant to defense contractors, <ORGANIZATION> PAISLEY </ORGANIZATION> provided advise -LRB- sic -RRB- to corporations and contractors who do business with varous agencies within the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>. One of his consulting contracts is with <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>. A large portion of his dealings with <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> are with or go through <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunn </PERSON>, a vice-president in marketing. `` DOD awards approximately 150 billion dollars worth of contracts every year. <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION>, through its constituent agencies, makes decisions in areas for the acquisition and award of contracts to further the national defense. At various stages, decisions are made in <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> and the military departments concerning the development of defense materials, equipment and services and the allocation of funds appropriated to <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> for the national defense. `` Information and data used to develop and implement the acquisition strategies are often closely held by <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> and its military departments and are of value and interest to companies seeking contracts from DOD. A company with such advance information can prepare more advantageously for procurements which are likely to be upcoming. Moreover, if a company learns of the Government's plans, the company can evaluate the plans and try to influence the decision makers to make modifications which would favor the particular company As such, a company may want to influence a decision about the size of a particular procurement, the specifications for the items being procured, the prerequisites which a company must meet in order to be eligible for the award of the procurement, or the weighing which the Government will use in evaluating different aspects of all competitors' proposals. `` Once <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> decides to seek a particular procurement, a majority of the contracts are awarded following a competitive bidding process. <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> has contracting officers who oversee the bidding process and are assigned within the various military services -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. The process begins with an advertisement for a new contract which is followed by companies receiving a document called a Request for Proposal -LRB- RFP -RRB- which details contract specifications and other contractual requirements. `` A time limit is set for the recipients to respond with their offers. Generally the price submitted by a company is critical to the company's winning a contract because the Government usually awards the contracts to the lowest bidder which is technically qualified to complete the contract. Once the initial offers have been submitted, the Government analyzes the offers for both technical expertise and price. The government determines a competitive range based upon the technical and pricing factors. If it is determined that at least two of the companies' offers are within the competitive range the competitive process is continued for those companies. `` The government holds discussions with each company and tells it where its offer is weak technically. The companies are then asked to submit their Best and Final Offers -LRB- BAFO -RRB-. The BAFO provides them with the opportunity to adjust their offers with respect to the price and the portions that were technically weak. However, if the Government determines that only one company's offer is within the competitive range, the Government can award the contract without a BAFO stage. `` Information about a company's competitors' offers and the Government's evaluation of those offers is never disclosed to a company prior to the award of the contract. Therefore, a company which has access to that information prior to the time when <ORGANIZATION> BAFO </ORGANIZATION>'s must be submitted can benefit greatly The information can assist the company in deciding how to modify its own offer. `` The information can also help a company learn that it has no chance of winning a contract. Then the company can decide to either drop out of the bidding or to seek to influence the Government to withdraw the <ORGANIZATION> RFP </ORGANIZATION> and change it in a way to be more favorable to the company. `` In addition, companies can obtain an edge if they obtain information about the Government's intentions which have not been disclosed prior to or during the bidding process. For instance, the Government may not have disclosed the amount of funds it has budgeted for a procurement or its estimates of how many options it will exercise under a contract containing options. Such information can help a company in drafting its proposal. `` The scheme involves the illegal disclosure of information and the exertion of influence with respect to <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> contracts. The information disclosed is often provided by Government employees receiving bribes or gratuities. The disclosed information has been of the type that can provide a company with an unfair advantage over its competitors and @ or the government. A substantial portion of the disclosed information is classified or confidential. `` As a defense contractor consultant, <ORGANIZATION> PAISLEY </ORGANIZATION> relies upon Government officials to provide <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> contract information which is not available to the contracting public. <PERSON> PAISLEY </PERSON> then provides this information, for a fee or as part of his `` consulting contract'' to <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>, who is a <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> contractor. <PERSON> PAISLEY </PERSON> has provided <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> THOMAS </PERSON> <PERSON> GUNN </PERSON> substantial information obtained from Government officials which has been classified and @ or confidential or not available to the contracting public. This information has included the following: `` 1 -RRB- information regarding <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> proposed sale of its F-18 fighter airplane to the Swiss government, including internal information of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> regarding the Super Hornet configuration; a proposed letter to <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> regarding the F-18; information regarding <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> and Final Offers -LRB- BAFO -RRB- on the Swiss contract; inside information pertaining to <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> F-16 proposal; `` 2 -RRB- information regarding a co-development plan with the French government regarding an updated F-18 -LRB- called FA-18 -RRB- including an internal <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> study; `` 3 -RRB- information regarding the sale of F-18s to <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> including, names of individuals with ability to influence the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Government to approve the sale of F-18s to <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and; `` 4 -RRB- information relating to sale of F-18s to <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- EFA -RRB- nations, including a telex from an <ORGANIZATION> EFA </ORGANIZATION> nation Embassy -LRB- <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> -RRB- dated axpproximately February 3, 1988, notes on Keb briefing on the Hornet 2000; documents on the APG 65 Radar; and letters from the Germans on the APG 65 Radar; and letters from the Germans on the radar for the F-18; `` 5 -RRB- the summer of 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> study; `` 6 -RRB- early 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analysis </ORGANIZATION> study regarding the 500 MG Helicopter -LRB- Killer Egg -RRB- and the future helicoper needs of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>; `` 7 -RRB- information relating to the Advanced Tactical Aircraft program, including BAFO information.''
