<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Campaign Across South</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 2 pvs to UPDATE with 2nd poll; SUBS 21st graf pvs
to UPDATE with Dukakis campaign comment; ADDS 3 grafs with
NBC-Journal poll</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> laid the foundation Thursday for their general election battle in the South, with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> trumpeting a tough anti-drug stand in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> seeking to unify his party in a region that was once its stronghold. A new poll said the two men are locked in a tight contest there. And another survey out Thursday gave <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> a double-digit lead nationwide. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> started a regional campaign swing with a stop in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> to pick up the endorsement of former Democratic presidential rival <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is going to carry our party to victory in November. He is going to win in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, in the North, in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, and he is going to win right here in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor he criticized during the primary season. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' `` image in the South and all over the country is very different than many people thought it was going to be when this campaign began. I think he moves beyond the old labels,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' remaining rival, testified before a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee on drug abuse and basked in the praise of a senator he competed against in the 1984 presidential campaign. `` I would think <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> frightened the bejesus out of them four years ago,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. `` I remember him standing up and saying his time has come! ... This time he's run a winning campaign. He has n't frightened anyone. He's charmed them in all of those different debates. <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, the only senator to back <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has locked up the nomination, but he said his vote at the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> convention would be based on <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>' support of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` He won my home state; he certainly has earned my vote,'' <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> met with 33 <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senators as he pressed for more unpledged `` super delegates'' to the July Democratic convention to support him. He said the party leadership `` while accepting my investment in the party to make it strong, has not been as reciprocal as it ought to be.'' `` If I invest, I should reasonably expect return,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters. `` So I appreciate the accolades that I am the voter registration champion for the party, that I have led the drive to return the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> back to the Democrats ... If I have done all of that, I simply say let's be fair.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> welcomed <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s support and said he looked to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to join the bandwagon. `` I would hope <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will be a part of this campaign and as early as possible,'' the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> added his backing to the idea of a special outside counsel to probe charges against <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who will preside over the Democratic convention next month. He said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had welcomed the idea, and he called that a stance that `` contrasts rather sharply with the kind of stonewalling we've had from the administration on case after case after case.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> distinguished his support for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> from his call for the resignation of Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. `` That's after repeated evidence of insensitivity, a lack of awareness of what we mean when we talk about high standards,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` If you're attorney general of this country and you've stumbled as often as he has and made as many mistakes as he has and provided as weak leadership as he has, you ought to leave office.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, with his budget cramped by federal spending limits, went only as far south as <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice president declared drugs `` the ultimate fatal attraction.'' He also renewed his call for companies to put anti-drug programs in place before they can receive federal contracts. `` The point is that stopping drugs in the workplace is not just a profit and loss issue, it's a matter of protecting the health and safety of workers,'' the all-but-certain Republican presidential nominee told the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jaycees </ORGANIZATION> annual meeting. `` It's no less important than <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> regulations on the conditions of machinery.'' `` The federal government should not dictate what kind of drug-free program a company should have, but it should require any federal contractor to have one in place,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also demanded `` Where's the price tag?'' for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s advocacy of increased spending on non-nuclear forces, which the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor called a Conventional Defense Initiative, to replace President <PERSON> Reagan </P