<HEAD>Heroin Candies Called ``New Trend'' in Drug Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Candies made from enough heroin to kill a child are the latest way smugglers are trying to bring the drug into <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, customs officials said Thursday. Twenty pounds of the fake candies, each containing the equivalent of nearly $ 550 worth of heroin, have been discovered in the luggage of smugglers arriving from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in the past three weeks, the officials said. The total value was put at $ 1.34 million. The officials said they were alerting customs officials in other countries, of the danger. `` Somewhere in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> there is a factory compressing, glazing and wrapping heroin to look exactly like sweets,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Curr </PERSON>, assistant chief investigations officer. `` If they are stolen by kids or otherwise get into their hands, just one sweet will kill a child,'' he said. `` Even touching it by unwrapping the cellophane will leave a rash as the heroin is absorbed into the skin.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, chief press officer at national customs headquarters in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, said heroin disguised as candy was seized before at a British border but called it `` a relatively new trend in smuggling techniques.'' He said smugglers usually baked the drug until it was black and looked like licorice, then wrapped it in real candy wrappers. The fake candy was found in two confiscations involving five passengers coming in from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which is known as a drug source, <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> said.
