<HEAD>FDA OKs Expanded Use Of Experimental Drug For Parkinson's Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday authorized expanded use of an experimental drug for Parkinson's Disease, a development that could benefit 30,000 Americans with severe forms of the ailment The drug, selegilene, can be distributed under the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s relatively new category called `` treatment IND'' in which promising experimental therapies can be prescribed for desperately ill patients before completion of the more extensive review required for full-fledged new drug approval Selegilene is the fifth drug to win such a designation under the new regulations adopted last year. The `` IND'' in the definition stands for `` investigational new drug.'' Distribution is to be administered by the drug sponsor, <ORGANIZATION> Somerset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Danville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, which has an application pending for full approval to market the drug under the trade name Eldepryl. Physicians treating patients with severe <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON>'s who have had difficulty with standard treatment can contact the company for detailed information about the drug's distribution, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. The most widely used treatment for Parkinson's involves use of the drug levodopa. However, that drug's effectiveness often gradually decreases with long-term use and it needs to be given in larger amounts that can produce increasingly severe side effects such as nausea, involuntary bodily movements, flushing and palpitations, said an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> announcement. Parkinson's Disease is a serious, degenerative disorder of the central nervous system that can affect people 40 and over. It is believed to be caused by reduced levels of a naturally produced substance in the brain called dopamine. Selegilene surpresses some of the enzymes in the body that inactivate dopamine.
