<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak Economy,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Passes Limited Economic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament has passed reforms that give state enterprises more say in production, make them self-financing and could reduce the economic bureaucracy by 30 percent, the government said Thursday. The limited package passed in a special three-day session is patterned after Soviet reforms that prescribe self-management and self-financing for state enterprises and cooperatives while taking away some or all state subsidies. <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, said state companies will be directly subordinate to ministries and that eliminating middle-level bureaus could bring a reduction of up to 30 percent in the economic bureaucracy. The reforms, which take effect next Jan. 1, were passed after a yearlong debate. During the rest of this year, companies that account for 30 percent of industrial production will be involved in an experiment that gives them greater control of production decisions. Czechoslovak officials gave few details on plans for economic reform, which they approach with caution. Decentralization of management will not go as far as in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and will not take full effect until 1991. Premier <PERSON> Lubomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Strougal </PERSON> acknowledged in May that the economy had not improved under his government. He said the number of committees and bureaus between enterprises and ministries will be reduced and the direct responsibilities of ministers increased. The once-efficient economy is plagued by low productivity, a poor industrial structure, unbalanced supply and demand, and growth of unsold inventory. <PERSON> Jaroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Matejka </PERSON>, an architect of the reforms, told a news conference last month only 48 percent of companies had applied for the new status that brings more independence. He said some feared being put out of business. Managers will be elected by secret ballot in the plant, according to the new law, but the government retains the right to nominate candidates for the jobs. New trade legislation will allow companies to make contracts of cooperation with others inside the Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Comecon </ORGANIZATION> trading group without first seeking government permission, <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said. Some enterprises will be allowed to deal directly with Western companies, bypassing foreign trade offices that now act as middlemen. A new law on cooperative enterprises, which employ 1.5 million people, affects those in both agricultural and housing and could increase their efficiency, the agency reported. Housing cooperatives alleviate the chronic housing shortage in a country where thousands of people have waited years years for new apartments. Agriculture subsidies now cost $ 3 billion a year. <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Toman </PERSON>, the agriculture minister, raised the possibility of people being allowed to buy land. `` There is a situation ... when the new law allows transfer of land not suitable for socialist large-scale production ... to other ... socialist and social organizations and individuals,'' <PERSON> Toman </PERSON> told the daily <PERSON> Lidova </PERSON> <PERSON> Demokracie </PERSON>. He gave no details.
