<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee approved prohibitions Thursday on oil and gas drilling for another year in federal waters off <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The bans were contained in the $ 9.7 billion appropriations bill for the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and related agencies that the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> sent to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. Earlier in the day, <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> announced a delay of at least six months in the planned lease offering for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> waters to try negotiations with affected <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> governors. The sale originally had been scheduled for next February. <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> also split the offering for <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> waters into two parts, with the 44-million-acre non-controversial section to be offered in November as scheduled. An offering on other gulf waters will be delayed at least six months while two federal-state task forces conduct additional studies on oil spill trajectories and the effects of any spills on the southwest <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> coast. Last week, <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> similarly delayed the offering of leases off northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> until next October. The committee's provisions, if upheld by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, will apply until Sept. 30, 1989. There have been several previous bars to drilling enacted similarly as riders to appropriations bills, and most of the argument Thursday covered ground familiar to the member