Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>, and the 400-meter provision was chosen to conform to provisions of a 12-year Canadian moratorium in adjacent waters adopted earlier this year. The action closes about 3.5 million acres to drilling and leaves about 2 million acres available for offering in a February auction. Opposing the committee proposals, <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said there might be no bids if promising shallow-water areas were ruled off limits off <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Speer </PERSON>, staff attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and long-time opponent of offshore drilling, said after the vote: `` This is a major victory. This takes the pressure off and will allow the next administration to take a look at the offshore program.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said the action if upheld `` would mean the abandonment of any meaningful effort to find new supplies of oil and natural gas offshore, and is a severe blow to the nation's future energy security. ... The record of oil company offshore operations clearly shows that oil and gas is being extracted without harm to the environment, to economic activity, tourism, fishing or wildlife.''
