<HEAD>FAA Curtails Proposal For Small Plane Tracking Device</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``Under the ...''
to UPDATE
   with comment by FAA Administrator McArtor and include current
requirements; Picks up 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``The move ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, flooded with tens of thousands of complaints from private pilots, on Thursday curtailed its proposed requirements for altitude tracking devices on small planes. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> announced a final regulation which calls for private pilots to have the altitude equipment when flying within 30 miles of 27 of the country's busiest airports and in restricted airspace around 109 additional airports. Three months ago the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said it was considering a much broader regulation that would have banned private pilots from airspace within 40 miles of 254 airports unless they had the equipment that tells air traffic controllers a plane's altitude. Under the new rule, small planes also will be prohibited from flying at or above 10,000 feet without the altitude encoding equipment. Originally the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> had suggested requiring the equipment on small planes flying as low as 6,000 feet. The final regulation falls short of what the airlines had wanted and closer to what the private pilots of small planes had sought. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said the regulation should reduce the danger of an aerial collision involving a small aircraft. He called it `` a major positive impact on safety.'' Currently the altitude encoding transponders are required on small planes only if they fly inside controlled airspace around the 27 busiest airports. The new requirements will be phased in beginning in July 1989. The move to broaden requirements for altitude-reporting equipment stemmed from the 1986 aerial collision over <LOCATION> Cerritos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, in which a small plane without such equipment collided with a Mexican airliner killing all aboard the two aircraft. The airlines and commercial pilots have argued that small, private planes should have the altitude encoding equipment whenever they fly in airspace used by commercial jetliners. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had called on the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> to broaden its requirement for the so-called Mode-C radar signal transponders on private planes. But when the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> suggested in February that it might require the equipment at 254 airports, it unleashed a flurry of protests. According to estimates by the <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, more than 80,000 letters were sent to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> complaining about the proposal. The private pilot group argued that the additional signals from the increased number of transponders would overwhelm the air traffic controllers _ a claim disputed by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> _ and that the additional requirements were being proposed for airspace near airports that are not heavily used by commercial jetliners. Pilots also complained about the estimated $ 600 to $ 2,000 cost for the altitude encoding transponder. Commercial jets as well as most sophisticated private planes that fly in and out of the busiest airports already have the equipment. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> long has required any aircraft flying within so-called terminal control areas _ rings of airspace of varying size around the 27 busiest airports _ to have the altitude encoding equipment. The rule announced Thursday would require the equipment for flights within 30 miles of the 27 airports beginning in July 1989. At 109 additional airports, which have less restrictive airspace, private planes must have the equipment when flying within that restricted area or up to 10,000 feet beginning Dec. 30, 1990. Other airports may be designated as requiring small planes to have the Mode-C equipment within 10 miles, but the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said only two airports so far have been singled out. Small planes flying within 10 miles of <LOCATION> Billings </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, must have the equipment beginning in 1991.
