<TEXT>
 That hum of air conditioners pulled power demand to peak levels as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Englanders </LOCATION> kept fighting the heat Thursday, while cooler weather prevailed for parts of the Plains and thunderstorms hit numerous regions of the nation. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pool </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of 95 utilities which coordinates electrical power for the region, recorded a record demand Thursday and another utility, <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, had record power demand for the second time in two days for the 40 communities it serves around <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Some <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> workers called the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> to see if a state law allowed them to go home once the temperatures reached a certain high. The icy answer: No. Readings were into the low to mid-90s from the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> valleys through central parts of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. Record high temperatures for the date were set in <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, 91; and <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, 93. Temperatures were more comfortable from the northern Plains into the upper Great Lakes. Readings were in the 70s across much of the region with temperatures in the 50s and 60s across northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The low for the nation Thursday morning was 35 at <LOCATION> Alamosa </LOCATION>, Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55 degrees at <LO