sing. Police denied permission for an anti-war group, <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Non-Violent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION>, to march down <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> where the leaders will meet. `` Demonstrators could occupy the attention of police and allow terrorists to act,'' <PERSON> Nadeau </PERSON> said. He said police also worry about random attacks by `` unstable persons'' like <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who shot and wounded <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1981. Despite its setting in a city of 3.4 million people, the summit will take place in a security cocoon. `` At no time will the delegates be on public view,'' said <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> Police Chief Jack Marks. Local resident <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKenzie </PERSON> called it ironic that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> walked the streets of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, a place he once dubbed an `` evil empire,'' but <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> is not considered safe enough for him to emerge from his armored limousine.
