<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was found innocent Thursday of concealing a $ 350,000 campaign loan, a partial vindication for the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> governor impeached and removed from office in 59 years. Minutes after the clerk had read the jury's last `` not guilty'' finding on the six counts against <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> and his brother <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>, the judge declared the trial over and <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s supporters cheered. `` Justice can occur in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> when you get to the people and outside the politicians,'' the 64-year-old former governor told reporters outside the court. `` We're happy, we're happy. You're always apprehensive but not really surprised. He said he would hold a news conference Friday morning. As the final verdict was read, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> smiled broadly and hugged his attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, then turned and embraced his wife, <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION>. Then he crossed to the jurors and began shaking their hands. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> asked Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> whether <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> could make a statement, but the judge refused, saying `` This is a court of law, Mr. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> had acknowledged he did not itemize the $ 350,000 loan from developer and attorney <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> on either his personal or campaign financial statements. The defense said the failure was an innocent mistake, partly due to <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>'s inexperience as a bookkeeper. However, the prosecution insisted that the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> badly needed the <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> loan to keep his campaign afloat, then hid it to avoid spoiling his theme of being `` beholden to no one.'' The jury had deliberated 6 -LCB- hours after receiving the case Wednesday following seven days of testimony. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> could have been sentenced to 22 years in prison if convicted on all six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents. His 67-year-old brother faced a maximum 9 -LCB- years on three counts. Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> said after the verdict that he had offered to let <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> plead guilty to a misdemeanor before the trial began, but <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> turned him down. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was impeached by the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and removed from office on April 4 when the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted him of misusing money from a state protocol fund and trying to thwart an investigation of a death threat. He had also faced an impeachment trial on the loan concealment charge, but the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> decided not to consider the matter to avoid prejudicing the criminal trial. The former auto dealer had run for governor four times unsuccessfully before he won a three-way race in November 1986. Gov. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> secretary of state who took over <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s post after he was removed by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, said in a prepared statement that she hoped her predecessor `` and his entire family can resume their lives as private citizens.'' `` The end of this trial signals a hastening of a healing process which has begun and that the citizens of this great state so richly deserve,'' she said. Outside the courtroom, prosecutor <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> <PERSON> Lotstein </PERSON> said that he had `` we had an obligation to present this case'' and that he had `` no quarrel with the decision.'' `` We believe we presented a responsible case that had to be presented. We obviously felt we had a good case.,'' <PERSON> Lotstein </PERSON> added `` A lot of the people in this community feel that he has suffered enough, and perhaps that was a factor.'' <PERSON> Lotstein </PERSON> said he felt the key issue was whether either <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> or <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> `` had the intent to break the law when they filled out the disclosure forms'' and that the jury obviously did n't feel they had such intent. Judge <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, addressing the jurors before dismissing them, told them that `` this case was zealously litigated by both sides, very well done job by both sides.'' `` I think that your verdict has shown that there can be a fair verdict, a fair trial for all parties in this system,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> added. `` I think you're a credit to this system and I think that this system can do the job even under intense and high publicity situations.'' When testimony ended Friday, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> told reporters the prosecution had not proven its case, which he said was based on `` smoke and mirrors.'' Neither defendant took the stand. Former top <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Edith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> testified for the defense that the loan was `` common knowledge'' among <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s inner circle. However, former <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> insiders <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mac </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON> testified that they did n't learn about the loan until October 1987 when it was revealed by the media. Bur the prosecution said it was immaterial whether <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s closest aides knew about the <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> loan The main point, prosecutor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cudahy </PERSON> said, was that the loan was not listed on the public disclosure forms required by the state. A state accountant, <PERSON> Leroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, insisted that the failure to list the loan could not have been simply a bookkeeping mistake by <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>. `` This one transaction stands out above all other transactions,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` It's the largest single transaction by far. The receipt is recorded a month after the fact. The name on the receipt is <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, not <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON>.'' The jury's makeup was an issue before selection began, when <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> acknowledged in April that he asked a group of backers to `` remain quiet'' about their support of him if asked to serve on the jury. The former governor contended he was only joking, however. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> became engulfed in controversy just one week after taking office in January 1987, when he canceled a Martin Luther King holiday for some state workers on grounds it was created illegally. He said King did n't deserve a state holiday, and later caused another storm of criticism by defending the use of the word `` pickaninny'' in a book. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> also made remarks that angered women, Jews, homosexuals and Japanese-Americans. The former governor also was accused of making a series of substandard appointments to top state positions. Before <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, the last governor impeached and removed from office was <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> in 1929.
