<SECOND>AM-Welfare Overhaul, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0808-a0814-a0819,1,070</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Welfare Overhaul Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Combines Urgent series; INSERTS 2 grafs with Moynihan reax
after 4th graf bgng, `Sen. Daniel;' SUBS 7th graf pvs bgng, `Voting
no,' to UPDATE with those not voting; INSERTS 1 graf after 10th
graf pvs bgng, `Governors of,' to UPDATE with Moynihan saying more
stringent workfare requirements would affect only 6-7 percent of
the welfare caseload; $440,000 is cq in 25th graf bgng, `Money to'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday passed a far-reaching welfare bill designed to help people break out of poverty through jobs, backing it almost unanimously after acceding to White House demands for more stringent work requirements. The vote on the Family Security Act was 93-3. The five-year, $ 2.8 billion measure requires stepped-up child support collections and creation of a comprehensive education, training and jobs program. Long-term welfare recipients or those likely to become long-term, such as teen-age mothers, would receive particular attention. Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who wrote the bill and fashioned a broad coalition of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> supporters, said it would make fundamental improvements in a system that has not changed in 53 years. For <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, who was a presidential advisor and a professor before joining the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the lopsided vote capped decades of studying and seeking welfare reform. `` This is the most important legislation of its kind and the first legislation of its kind since the welfare system was established in the 1930s,'' he exulted. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> said that under the current system, `` One child in four in this country will be on welfare by age 18. That's where we were headed yesterday.'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION> called the <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> bill `` an opportunity ... to set an entirely new direction for the outdated and ineffective system we have today.'' And Senate Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., described it as `` the best hope'' for lifting people out of poverty and restoring their dignity Voting no on the bill were Sens. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>. Not voting were Sens <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Del.; <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>; Chic Hecht, R-Nev., and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, R-Idaho A bipartisan group of senators negotiated with <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> officials throughout the week following word last Friday that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto the <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> bill as it stood. The main obstacle as the bill neared passage late Thursday was a White House demand that some welfare recipients be required to participate for 16 hours a week in `` workfare,'' or community work projects, to work off their grants. Governors of both parties opposed the provision to phase in mandatory workfare participation by one adult in each two-parent welfare household. But <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> offered it as a floor amendment and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed it by voice vote after refusing 54-41 to kill it. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> said the provision would affect only 6 percent to 7 percent of the welfare caseload. Only nine states have statewide mandatory workfare programs. Some governors said it would be expensive, cumbersome and unnecessary in their states. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> said workfare is pointless for people who need retraining rather than work experience and in areas where the labor market is strong. Senators agreed to other White House requests as well, including a requirement that state job and training programs include 22 percent of eligible participants by 1994. The agreement added about $ 200 million to the five-year cost of the bill, bringing it up to $ 2.8 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> already has passed a more generous, $ 7 billion welfare plan. Negotiators for each chamber will reconcile differences in the two bills before a plan is sent to the White House. Whether <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> supports the final measure depends largely on the extent to which <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members are willing to go along with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> product. Aid to Families with Dependent Children, established in 1935 as part of the Social Security system, currently supports 3.7 million families which include some 7 million children. Originally conceived as a widow's benefit when women _ especially mothers _ did not work outside the home, the program now is dominated by divorced and unwed mothers at a time when the majority of new mothers are at work within a year of having a child. The centerpiece of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bills is a new jobs program under which states would have to offer a wide range of activities including job training and basic education as well as actual work. They would have to include as many people as they could afford, and half the money would have to be spent on people needing the most help. A 1987 study of current welfare-to-work programs found that they did not have nearly enough money, that they offered limited and superficial services, they lacked essential support services such as child care, put too much emphasis on job placement rates, funneled people into low-paying jobs that did n't get them entirely off welfare, excluded mothers of children under 6 and tended to help people who really did n't need it while ignoring tough cases. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bills attempt to correct most of these deficiencies. Each envisions a substantial federal financial commitment to the jobs program and describes or mandates activities to be offered. They improve child care benefits and guarantee child care for people in the program. Mothers with children under 3 would be exempt from the work-training requirement, and states could lower that to age 1. Both bills also require states to extend welfare benefits to poor two-parent families. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill only would require the benefits for six months in any 12-month period; 26 states already provide year-round coverage. A major difference in the two bills is that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> offers extra federal money to states that raise benefits to needy families, which in many cases have incomes well below half the federal poverty line. Money to cover additional spending under the <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> bill would come from making permanent a tax refund withholding program to recover federal debts, and eliminating the business food and entertainment tax deduction for people with incomes over $ 440,000. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved the meals and entertainment provision Thursday in place of a provision phasing out the dependent care tax credit for higher-income families. Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, sponsor of the substitute, said the original plan would have constituted a tax on child care and added, `` I'm against punishing women for their professional success.'' The <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> bill attracted opposition not only from conservatives seeking tighter work requirements but from mothers who said they should not be forced to work at all. A group called Wages for <ORGANIZATION> Housework </ORGANIZATION> complained that the measure was `` designed to get women off the welfare rolls, not out of poverty, and denigrates the work of all mothers.''
