<HEAD>New Zealand Shopowner Puts Cliche to a Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ever wonder what would happen if you really let a bull loose in a china shop? So did <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>. So much, in fact, that he put the cliche to a test in his own store on Thursday. Nothing happened. `` I'm pretty relieved,'' <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> admitted after fulfilling what he said was a lifelong ambition _ letting a 2,400-pound bull roam through his store for three hours. `` We managed to get him out of the shop before anything happened,'' <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said. Not that there were n't tense moments. <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said $ 60,000 worth of <LOCATION> china </LOCATION> was at stake during the romp by the bull, nicknamed `` The Colonel.'' <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said he attempted the feat at his shop in <LOCATION> Palmerston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Wellington </LOCATION>, after constantly being egged on by customers familiar with bull-in-a-china-shop cliche. While `` The Colonel'' shopped around, <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said, he got a call from a radio station in <LOCATION> Stoke-on-Trent </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, known as the home of bone china. Representatives of the Guinness Book of World Records as well as the international media also turned up to watch the stunt. <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> took some precautions. Before the event, he said, he insured his china at an undisclosed premium. Just in case.
