<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The family farm in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> must remain viable and subsidies can not be rolled back overnight, Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> told the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, the first West German head of government to address <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s legislature, acknowledged criticism of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s Common Agricultural Policy and the $ 300 billion global farm-subsidy war. He said he opposed permanent subsidies in principle but added: `` When developments have taken a long course over 20 years, you can not remedy the situation overnight ... the family farm must remain viable in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s future.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has proposed phasing out agricultural subsidies by the year 2000, and Canadian officials had hoped for a compromise at the seven-nation Economic Summit which starts Sunday in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said in welcoming <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> that summit nations `` must come to grips with the acute problem.'' But the 12-nation European Community has been reluctant to dismantle subsidies to small farmers because of the political outcry that would follow. In a wide-ranging, 55-minute address, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> likened the new U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement to <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> plans to create a unified market for goods by 1992. That uniform market of 320 million consumers will remain accessible to other countries, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said, and he counted on <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to ensure the same will be true of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> under free trade. `` We trust the assurances of our Canadian friends that <LOC