<HEAD>Blacks Insulted By Billboards Advertising Fade Cream</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A billboard advertising campaign for <ORGANIZATION> Porcelana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cream </ORGANIZATION> that features light-skinned black women as `` faded beauties'' shows a lack of sensitivity toward minorities, blacks said Thursday. `` I saw the billboards, and I could n't believe this thing was coming back again,'' said <PERSON> Sharmain </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, chief of staff for state Sen. <PERSON> Roxanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` I was definitely offended by it.'' The Porcelana billboards show the product name, a close-up photograph of two light-skinned black women and the words `` Faded Beauties of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>.'' One billboard, before it was covered by a new advertisement, was embellished with graffiti that changed `` faded beauties'' to read `` faded pride'' and the words `` Stop Racist Advertising'' were written across it. Fade creams are frequently advertised in black-oriented magazines for correcting uneven skin tones or diminishing scars and blemishes, but critics say the billboards imply lighter is better. Officials for the Los Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION> Dep </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes and distributes <PERSON> Porcelana </PERSON>, declined to comment on Thursday. <PERSON> Porcelana </PERSON> might not have meant to promote the cream as an overall skin lightener, but the possibility is the crux of the problem, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, executive editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, a tri-weekly that is one of the oldest black-owned papers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I do n't know if it's out and out blatant racism that makes for these kind of decisions, but there seems to be a certain lack of sensitivity that is born of out of some form of racist attitude,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` The issue is not so much that particular billboard,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` The issue is the treatment of black folks in advertising across the board.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> researcher who has studied the effects of minority-targeted advertising said The controversy might be an example of a company misjudging the message it sends to consumers, said <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a marketing professor at <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> who has studied the effects of minority-targeted advertising. `` Even if they did n't mean to offend, what you have to be concerned with is the decoded message _ what did it mean to the consumer,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` If that decoded message is leading to a negative perception, regardless of the intent of the advertiser, they should change -LRB- the advertisement.'' In an atmosphere of increased minority pride and activism, advertisers can find themselves in trouble if they fail to consider the sensitivity of their target group, he said. Black consumers wield well more than $ 200 billion of purchasing power, while Hispanic consumers have more than $ 100 billion, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` I think you're going to find more and more consumers who are going to use that purchasing power to reward those advertisers who are sensitive to their issues,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. Advertisers who aggravate minority consumers may find that consumers not only avoid a product, but may actively campaign against it, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said.
