<HEAD>Playing Bagpipes Can Damage Hearing, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 High noise levels from bagpipes can knock a Scotsman's hearing out of kilter _ and even cause permanent hearing loss, a neurologist and amateur bagpiper said Thursday. Dr. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rutland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, and audiologist <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartenstein </PERSON> measured noise levels produced by the bagpipes and reported their findings in a letter in the June issue of the Archives of Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgery. Indoor and outdoor levels at the player's left ear reached up to 105 decibels, they wrote. Noting that federal noise exposure maximums are 105 decibels for one hour and 115 decibels for 15 minutes, they said it would be fairly easy for pipers to meet or exceed these limits `` with steady, dedicated practice.'' Good quality foam ear plugs can sharply cut noise levels, they said. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON>, who said he had been playing the pipes about three years, became concerned when he found playing the pipes was almost a painful experience at first. He said he started wearing earplugs, but believes few pipers are aware of the risks of permanent hearing loss and few probably wear ear protection. He said the ear protection he wears reduces the sound level about 25 decibels and does not interfere with hearing and evaluating his own playing.
