 Rumors the Gran Cafe de Gijon in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> might be sold to a British bank rattled coffee cups far beyond the century-old literary landmark once frequented by the likes of <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> and <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> <PERSON> Capote </PERSON>. Legend has it that the actress <PERSON> Ava </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> once punched a photographer there. When the rumors spread recently of its possible sale, major publications rushed into print with what they called the inside story. Mayor <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Barranco </PERSON> pledged to preserve the cafe. Part-owner <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Brito </PERSON> spent a week denying it was for sale. `` We are not selling. It is impossible,'' <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> told reporters the day reports came out that an British multinational bank, not identified, had made a $ 5-million bid for the cafe that first opened its doors in 1888. Although it was before noon, the Gijon was already thick with cigar and cigarette smoke, and most of its marble-top tables were filled. The Gijon stands just off <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s traffic-clogged main thoroughfare, the <ORGANIZATION> Paseo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Castellana </ORGANIZATION>, as a reminder of quieter days when cafes stretched across the city and coffee time was a ritual. Although its glory days are past and <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> is much busier in an economic boom, the Gijon still attracts dozens of `` tertulias,'' groups of intellectuals, artists or retirees who meet once or twice a week for relaxed conversation with a cigar over coffee and brandy. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Brito </PERSON> said accepting the unidentified British bank's offer would have broken a pledge made to his grandmother, <PERSON> Encarnation </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, who bought the cafe from its original owners in 1913 `` Before my grandmother died, she made my father and my aunt promise not to sell. As long as my aunt is alive we would n't even consider it,'' said <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Brito </PERSON>, who owns the cafe with his four cousins. `` After that, who knows?'' he said. `` The younger generation all have professional careers. They want their free time. The cafe does n't allow that.'' Grandmother <PERSON> Encarnacion </PERSON> and her daughter, <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Aunt </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>, presided over the Gijon in the years after the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War, when struggling actors and writers were drawn to cafes because of their central heating and cheap admission _ the price of a tiny cup of coffee. By the time grateful artists showered <PERSON> Encarnacion </PERSON> with drawings and verse on her 100th birthday in 1968, most of them were eating better, and the Gijon was a grand old survivor, its fame cemented by the gradual demise of most competitors. `` The majority of the cafes were converted into bank branches, and the literary people took refuge here because there were n't many places left, `` said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, who began working at the Gijon in 1950. `` The coffee hour was a bit sacred,'' he said. `` People would talk about their projects, about bullfights. They generally avoided politics'' during <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s 36-year rule. <PERSON> Pilar </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nombrela </PERSON>, who has lived above the cafe for 20 years, said the Gijon in the late 1960s `` was a classic cafe.'' `` People would spend three hours over a cup of coffee and talk about art and literature. There were tables and tables of famous people. It was incredible.'' Today, the `` tertulias'' are fewer. At nights, the cafe is filled with young Spaniards who prefer gin-tonics to brandy. An armed guard stands inside the door to keep out heroin addicts who have occasionally robbed patrons at knife point. Gentifrication has set in the neighborhood around the cafe and real estate values have shot up like the skyscrapers along the <LOCATION> Castellana </LOCATION> as the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> economy marks an annual 5.2 percent growth rate. `` The cafe has changed a lot, just like the country has changed,'' the 63-year-old <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said. `` In those days, there were 20 cars circulating in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. Horse-drawn carriages were used a lot. People worked less and had more time.'' `` <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> was a city of cafes,'' he said. `` One writer called it an archipelago of tertulias.'' <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, an octogenarian who has met at the Gijon to chat with fellow <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> retirees for the last two decades, does not miss those times. `` The bureacrats used to spend all day in the cafes,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said, a few minutes before initiating a debate on the merits of legalizing hard drugs. `` When they finally got to the office, all they did was talk about what they had done in the cafe.''
