<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, June 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-AP on TV-Deaf and Blind</HEAD>
<HEAD>From `Titicut Follies' to Alabama Institute for Deaf and Blind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of the <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deaf </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Blind </PERSON> hopes a four-part documentary by filmmaker <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON> will inspire change to benefit the handicapped everywhere. `` I think it will sensitize many Americans to the uniqueness of the disabled, the frustrations and challenges of the deaf and blind,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, president of the institute. `` Over the longer term,'' he said, `` the film may make a major contribution in the professional perception of those who choose to work in these fields.'' The series, which has been seen only at film festivals and at theaters in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area, reaches a national audience for the first time tonight with the opening installment, `` Blind,'' on public television. <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON>'s stark look inside a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> mental hospital two decades ago helped transform the care of the nation's mentally ill. This look inside the institute at <LOCATION> Talladega </LOCATION> is part of a series of documentaries on American institutions. When he told a friend he wanted to do a film on the disabled as part of that series, <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON> explained in a telephone interview, he was told the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> institute was `` one of the best schools in the country.'' He filmed for about six weeks at the <ORGANIZATION> Talladega </ORGANIZATION> complex, which was founded in 1858 and has grown into a multi-purpose program that provides kindergarten through 12th-grade academics, competitive athletics, vocational training as well as special skills training for the deaf, blind and multi-handicapped of all ages. <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON> said he received `` complete cooperation'' from the institute and its staff as his camera recorded the anguishing difficulties and daily personal heroism of the handicapped and their teachers. `` I was impressed by the kindness and compassion,'' said <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON>. In 1967, <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON>'s film `` Titicut Follies'' reported graphically on the degrading living conditions and dehumanizing treatment of the mentally ill at a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> state hospital. The widely acclaimed film helped draw attention to what amounted to a national problem as litigation to reform mental health care spread to many states, including <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON> disagees with those who view his work as cause-oriented filming aiming only to expose one problem or another. `` I think that was a bum rap,'' said <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON>. `` I report on the experience I had in making the film.'' He said `` Titicut Follies'' turned out to be `` quite extreme.'' In contrast, he said, the experience at the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> institute was good. `` I report on what I find,'' he said. <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said he was not aware of the controversial nature of `` Titicut Follies'' when he opened the doors of the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> institute to <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON>. But even after learning about the filmmaker's previous work, he said, `` we felt comfortable that our program could withstand his scrutiny. <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON> and his crew seemed to become part of the normal environment. `` They were the most unassuming, unintrusive and unimposing people I've ever seen,'' he said. <PERSON> Wiseman </PERSON> `` recorded the human drama and the boredom of life itself,'' <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said. `` He did a great job of capturing what deafness and blindness are all about. We just happened to be the vehicle for him to use.''
</TEXT>
