<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Educator's Struggle to End Parish's Denial, Begin Christian Caring</BYLINE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cardinals meet this month to renew debate over what to teach Catholics about AIDS. But if the struggles of a trailblazing religious education director in an affluent <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> parish are any indication, the debate goes deeper than the much-publicized condom furor. AIDS is shaking ordinary parishioners' deepest religious convictions and raising a central question: is the church fundamentally about love or judgment?
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHBROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> _ nurse, hospital chaplain, mother of five and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> educator _ once wrote a verse about trying to teach her unusual gospel of AIDS in this affluent <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb. `` Behold, `` The empty chairs and `` the quickened pace to run. `` Away from me who waits to `` Reveal love over judgment, `` Knowledge over ignorance, `` Healing through reconciliation. `` AIDS ministers embrace an EXILED station. `` Behold, the empty chairs.'' For six years, Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> has been director of religious education at <LOCATION> Our </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lady </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, a church set on 11 acres of lush lawns and generous parking lots. To most in <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION>, AIDS is as vague and distant as a foreign war on the evening news. But in 1986, a friend of Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> revealed his homosexuality and began drinking heavily because he feared getting AIDS. Later, she heard from some parents that their children were trying `` alternative life-styles,'' including homosexuality. Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> came to believe that this conservative, sheltered parish could no longer ignore the disease. She spent 16 months writing an AIDS curriculum expressly for <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> parents, `` From Fr-AIDS to Faith: Let Us Talk About AIDS.'' Told in story form, blending gospel with realism about sex, drugs and AIDS, it was designed to help parents explain the disease to their children. For fourth - through sixth-graders, for example, there is a graphic discussion of bodily fluids, how AIDS is and is not spread, sex and marriage Suddenly this past school year, sleepy suburban <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION> found itself an improbable beacon of AIDS education. Her parish priest, Sunday school teachers and parents use words like `` pioneer,'' `` visionary,'' even `` prophet,'' to describe Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>, who argues that AIDS is a cataclysmic ethical and medical event that raises centuries-old questions over whether the essence of Roman Catholicism is love or judgment. Despite the outward adulation, however, her AIDS gospel has been largely ignored. She sent her curriculum to about 400 families in her parish, but only three accepted her offer for discussions. `` Our homophobia is making us deny that the disease belongs to all of us,'' she said. She got brief national attention when she spoke about her curriculum at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s convention in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in April She was subsequently invited to address other Chicago-area parishes, but attracted only tiny audiences. The problems she and fellow teachers have found within the church, in some ways as intractable as the HIV virus itself, are denial and indifference among parishioners and ambiguity and division in church policy. This month, she decided to leave her parish post to devote all her time to AIDS missionary work. The story of what happened when <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> tried to get AIDS discussed in <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION> tells much about the confusion and moral contradictions the disease presents for <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> educators everywhere. `` AIDS,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>, echoing the sentiments of many church members, `` is creating havoc for the Catholic church.'' In one sense, her parish was fertile ground for trailblazing. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> archdiocese, led by Cardinal <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON>, is comparatively liberal. Last December, when <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops issued a landmark statement on AIDS education that included mention of condoms, <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON> was a chief proponent. The statement drew fire from traditionalists led by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. The nation's 300 bishops have agreed to meet in <LOCATION> Collegeville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, June 24-27 to discuss the issue again. Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>, though often critical of what she considers the church's lack of realism about AIDS, never ran afoul of the archdiocese. Sister <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> archdiocese, and others in the hierarchy have praised her and her curriculum. Her pronouncements have sometimes challenged the bounds of acceptable dogma, as when she told a gathering of nuns, priests and lay religious teachers at the convention: `` If a kid tells me he's sexually active, I give condom information I'll tell him how to put it on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-AIDS-EmptyChairs Adv19-1stAdd   06-16 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AIDS-Empty Chairs, Adv 19-1st Add,0777</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NORTHBROOK: it on.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The heart of her AIDS message, however, is not condoms but the Good Samaritan parable, <PERSON> Luke </PERSON> 10:25 -37, directing Christians not to judge their suffering neighbors but to care for them `` Let God do the judging,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION> parishioners were getting mixed signals from their pastor. Father <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Herne </PERSON>, who has generally supported Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>' AIDS mission and who agrees the church should be compassionate, says it nevertheless should not shrink from calling a sin a sin. <PERSON> Herne </PERSON> wrote some verse of his own in a church bulletin: `` What used to be called chastity is now called neurotic inhibition ... What used to be called perversion is now called alternative lifestyle. What used to be called depravity is now called creative self-expression.'' `` She says God is love,'' <PERSON> Herne </PERSON> said of Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>. `` I say amen to that. But everything people do is not OK.'' <PERSON> Herne </PERSON> said he agreed with Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> that the church should soften its finger-wagging image and the perception it does not welcome homosexuals who contract AIDS `` We're not against homosexuals,'' said <PERSON> Herne </PERSON>. `` But we seem to be on the moral side, and less on the compassionate and understanding side.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>' work comes as <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> educators scramble to devise lessons about AIDS. The <ORGANIZATION> NCEA </ORGANIZATION> has until August to complete an AIDS curriculum for parochial schools to use in the new school year. It is likely to discuss, but not condone, condom use. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> archdiocese devised its own AIDS curriculum, which will be introduced this fall. Led by Sister <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, the archdiocese enlisted experts from <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and elsewhere to help train parochial teachers. Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> contends that <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> educators hold an untapped advantage over public schools in their ability to imbue AIDS lessons with religion. `` <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> tells us a story in <PERSON> Luke </PERSON> that helps us know how to treat persons who are sick, especially persons with AIDS,'' says her curriculum, referring to the Good Samaritan story and using language that would be beyond constitutional bounds in public schools. In talking to children in her parish she discovered it was these matters of the heart that puzzled them most. `` They would ask me, ` Why does the school nurse wear rubber gloves now?' or ` What if somebody falls down at school and bleeds. Can I still help them?''' But to most <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION> youngsters, AIDS remains remote. `` I told my kids, ` When you go to college next year, how are you going to know who you're with?''' said <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dondlinger </PERSON>, who teaches religious classes for teens at <LOCATION> Our </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lady </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> the </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>. `` But the trouble is, AIDS is not here. The kids have a real hard time connecting to it.'' Did Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> really expect to succeed? `` It was n't a matter of whether I believed parents would use it,'' she said. `` I wanted to give them the tools. I feel much better that parents do the teaching.'' At least as worrisome as the laity's denial of AIDS, said Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>, is the lack of thought toward moral and emotional preparation for parochial teachers being called upon to teach about AIDS. `` You're going to be giving a curriculum to a whole bunch of volunteer teachers who have n't thought out where they're coming from,'' she said. `` Not every educator should be doing this. If you do not have the heart for this, please be free enough not to do it. Students do n't want a one-shot filmstrip. `` Parents are hungry for a workable sexual theology. The hierarchy wants to do that, but they are writing from a male celibate perspective. That's not a criticism. That's a fact,'' she said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloan </PERSON>, who attended Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON>' AIDS lessons with his 10-year-old son, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, said he was glad of any help he could get in explaining AIDS and sexuality. `` It's good to have the Church involved in something like this,'' he said. `` I, like other parents, was hesitant to bring up AIDS with my kids,'' said another parent, <PERSON> Joey </PERSON> <PERSON> Buck </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> took a little pressure off us.'' How does Mrs. <PERSON> Clemens </PERSON> feel about the church as she prepares to leave her parish post? `` Love-hate. Sometimes it frustrates me,'' she said. `` The institution teaches me patience. It teaches me damage control. But I have hit an institutional wall not only in this parish, but in this church. `` On the AIDS issue, I needed the freedom to speak.''
</TEXT>
