<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The deficit in the broadest measure of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign trade widened in the first quarter to $ 39.75 billion as the first deficit in investment earnings in 30 years offset a sharp improvement in the merchandise trade balance, the government has reported. The quarterly imbalance in the country's current account balance surged 18.6 percent from the fourth quarter's $ 33.5 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. The current account is the most important trade statistic, because it covers not only merchandise trade but also trade in the services category, which reflects primarily the flow of investment earnings between countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales grew a lackluster 0.1 percent in May, the government said in a report analysts predicted should help ease fears of inflationary pressures in the economy. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said sales by retailers, which represent about one-third of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic activity, edged up a scant 0.1 percent in May to $ 131.9 billion, after a 0.4 percent drop in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A boom in the manufacture of business equipment and a pickup at auto plants helped boost <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial production by a moderate 0.4 percent in May, the government says. It was the eighth month in a row without a decline in an index measuring output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities, and a further sign of the resurgence of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturing. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday the May advance followed an April gain of 0.6 percent, revised slightly from a previous estimate of 0.7 percent. Overall industrial production now stands 6.1 percent higher than a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The working mother has made the transition from novelty to national norm, with more than half of new mothers remaining in the job market for the first time, the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. The labor force participation rate for new mothers climbed to 50.8 percent last year from 49.8 percent in 1986, marking the first time a majority of women reported they were working or actively seeking employment within a year of giving birth. Only 31 percent of new mothers were counted in the labor force in 1976, the first year the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> sought to calculate this rate.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> cattle farmers mowed roadside ditches for feed as the drought in the nation's midsection pushed prices skyward on commodity exchanges. About 750 barges were stranded on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> due to low water, and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> said twice as many could be stranded by the weekend. Rain fell in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, but the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it would n't be enough to make up for weeks of dry weather. Temperatures remained in the high 80s and 90s across much of the nation.
