<FIRST>r f PM-TradeDeficit Bjt   06-16 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade Deficit, Bjt,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Is Shrinking, Latest Statistic Notwithstanding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Economists say the nation's trade deficit is shrinking decisively, in spite of a government report indicating that the broadest measure of trade worsened in the first three months of the year. At first, Wednesday's negative report on the current account imbalance seemed to contradict the report of a day earlier that the merchandise trade deficit fell in April to its lowest point since December 1984. But economists said the bad news was old news. In truth, they said, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is well on the way to closing the gap between exports and imports. `` The trade deficit is on the mend in a fairly substantial way,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, director of economics for <ORGANIZATION> ASB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sparked a strong rally in the financial markets Tuesday when it announced that the April merchandise trade deficit shrank to $ 9.89 billion, far smaller than expectations. On Wednesday, the news seemed to sour when the department said the deficit in the broadest measure of trade, the current account, widened in the January-March period to $ 39.75 billion, up 18.6 percent from $ 33.5 billion in the last quarter of 1987. But financial markets shrugged off the negative report, which referred to trade news from early in the year that was superseded by the strong April results. Nevertheless, bewilderment over the seeming contradiction between the numbers was understandable, said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, senior economist of <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. `` It's confusing to economists. The rest of the people must be that much more confused,'' he said. The one dark spot in Wednesday's current account report was that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ran its first deficit in investment income in 30 years during the first quarter. The red ink in investment income was the result of foreigners' accumulations of huge holdings of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets in recent years For the first time, Americans had to pay out more in interest, dividends and rents to foreigners than they received on their holdings abroad. But the deficit on investment income did not disturb financial markets, because it was a predictable outcome of the persistent merchandise trade deficits. The investment income deficit is certain to get bigger in coming months because foreigners will continue adding to their holdings of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets as long as they run trade surpluses with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We're making progress on the trade front. But because we have such a large deficit, we're still piling up claims against us at a very rapid rate,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON>, executive vice president and chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The deterioration in the investment income account will not end until the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> starts running surpluses in merchandise trade. That is likely to happen around the middle of the 1990s, said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubarych </PERSON>, an economist at the consulting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kaufman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Carpenter of <ORGANIZATION> ASB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> thinks it could happen far sooner than that `` We will start having monthly surpluses within 12 to 15 months,'' he said.
</TEXT>
