<SECOND>PM-Ad Forecast,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecaster Expects 8.4 Percent Growth in Ad Spending This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Domestic advertising spending should rise 8.4 percent this year, its strongest showing in four years despite some unexpected weakness in local retail advertising, a widely followed ad forecaster says. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Coen </PERSON>, senior vice president for the ad agency <ORGANIZATION> McCann-Erickson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday that total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ad spending should rise to $ 118.8 billion. His forecast of 8.4 percent growth this year was slightly below his December prediction that spending would rise 9.0 percent in 1988, but it still exceeds rises of 7.4 percent in 1987, 7.8 percent in 1986 and 7.9 percent in 1985. `` The Olympics and the elections are helping to fuel a return to a higher growth rate for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ad spending in 1988 after a three-year drought,'' he told securities analysts at his semiannual briefing on ad spending trends. It would be the biggest gain since ad spending rose 15.8 percent in 1984, another year that also had the Olympics and presidential election. He said many large national marketers appear to have `` loosened their tight grip on budgets'' but are spending significantly more only `` when bargains or special considerations justify the increases.'' National advertising is expected to rise 9.4 percent to $ 66.35 billion, <PERSON> Coen </PERSON> said, while local ad spending will grow 7 percent to $ 52.47 billion. In the new forecast, <PERSON> Coen </PERSON> said national ad spending on television should rise 10 percent, the first double-digit rise in four years. The forecast includes a projection of an 11 percent rise in spending on the three major television networks. Network executives have complained in recent weeks that the national ad market has softened. Magazine ad revenue has risen 11 percent over the first four months of the year, but should slow and finish 8 percent ahead for the year, he said. The biggest adjustment in <LOCATION> Coen </LOCATION>'s forecast came in his estimates of newspaper ad spending. He said spending by local retailers, a major source of newspaper ad revenue, rose only 1 percent in the first quarter. He said the weather and worries about takeovers may have made some large retailers more cautious about spending. As a result, <PERSON> Coen </PERSON> said he scaled back his growth estimate for local ad spending in newspapers to 6 percent from 9 percent. Among the major ad categories, <PERSON> Coen </PERSON> said automakers boosted their spending on television and magazines by 18 percent in the first three months of the year, while makers of food, candy, soft drinks and cleaning products posted double-digit spending gains for the first time in several years. On the other hand, he said, cigarette advertising in magazines fell 6 percent in the quarter, and single-digit gains were posted by beer and airline companies. Outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Coen </PERSON> said he expects ad spending to grow 14 percent to $ 108.4 billion in 1988. That would mean worldwide ad spending would rise 10.9 percent to $ 227.2 billion. <PERSON> Coen </PERSON> said he tentatively expects <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ad spending to rise 7.5 percent to $ 127.7 billion in 1989. He said while the economy and profits are growing, many advertisers traditionally tighten ad budgets in a post-Olympic year.
