<HEAD>UAW Settles With General Dynamics Division, Averting Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with settlement, editing to conform.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bargainers for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Land Systems Division reached a three-year contract settlement late Wednesday night, averting a midnight strike at the defense contractor. The two sides put the finishing touches on a settlement covering 6,000 workers that includes a drug testing program UAW Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said would be mutually satisfying to the union and the company. Details of the tentative agreement were not immediately released, although <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said it included a substantial pay increase and a ratification bonus, along with improvements in health and safety provisions. `` Overall we were very happy,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> told a late night news conference. `` We dealt with the substance abuse matter. Our members will agree to that I'm quite sure.'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said the contract would be explained to the workers represented by the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> at the Land Systems Division, a tank-making operation that <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> bought from <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1982. The division has plants in the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> suburbs of <LOCATION> Sterling </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> and at <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. About 1,000 of the division's workers are on layoff. A ratification vote will take place in another seven to 10 days, the union said. The union had sought a 3 percent-per-year increase in the $ 13-an-hour base wage at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> and increased union representation to help workers with benefit questions, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said the company sought to reduce the number of job classifications, or strict definitions of individual jobs, and more flexibility in its use of workers. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said earlier that drug abuse was not a widespread problem in General Dynamics plants. General Dynamics and the union have a pilot Employee Assistance Program at the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION>. Like similar programs at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, the professionally administered program uses counseling and education to help workers with drug and other problems. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said the union wants the EAP expanded to other Land Systems Division plants. General Dynamics was required to accept <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> contract when it purchased the Land Systems Division, and a contract negotiated in 1985 closely resembled Big Three auto contracts. Talks on a new three-year contract began April 11, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said.
