<HEAD>UAW, General Dynamics Contract Contains Drug Testing Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tentative settlement reached between the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION>' Land Systems Division is one of the first major labor contracts to contain a drug-testing policy, a union official says. The settlement, covering 6,000 workers at Land Systems Division plants in the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> suburbs of <LOCATION> Sterling </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, and at <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, was announced less than 20 minutes before Wednesday's midnight strike deadline. `` We dealt with the substance abuse matter in a manner that is satisfactory to us. Our members will agree to that I'm quite sure,'' <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> told a news conference. `` All in all we are very happy.'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said the contract's approach, one of the first of its kind, `` deals with the rehabilitation aspects'' of drug abuse and will not mean that any workers will have to submit to random or mandatory drug testing. Earlier Wednesday, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said the union would not agree with the company's demand for random, mandatory drug testing. He said details of the program have to be worked out, then explained to workers along with the rest of the contract. He said members would vote within the next seven to 10 days. Company officials were equally as pleased with the agreement on drug testing. `` As we all know, it's a national problem,'' said <PERSON> Arch </PERSON> <PERSON> Rambeau </PERSON>, corporate vice president for human resources. `` It is involved in every community where we live. It's in every work place. We need to start with education and rehabilitation programs.'' General Dynamics and the union have a pilot drug program at the Warren plant, which uses counseling and education to help workers with drug problems. Other parts of the contract include a substantial pay increase over the three years of the contract, along with a ratification bonus and improved health and safety provisions, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. About 1,000 of the workers covered by the tentative agreement are on layoff, including 800 of the 2,700 Detroit-area workers. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rambeau </PERSON> declined to discuss specifics of how the contract will impact those workers, if at all, and also said they could not provide other specifics until union members are informed. <PERSON> Rambeau </PERSON>, however, said lump sum wage increases are included in the contract, as the company had wanted, but he would not elaborate. The union sought a 3 percent pay increase for the base wage of $ 13 an hour in each year of the pact. It also sought increased union representation to help workers with benefits questions, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
