<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-EconomicSummit     06-16 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Economic Summit,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delors Says Farm Policy Dispute Could Spoil Toronto Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A U.S.-European dispute over farm policy reform may `` spoil the atmosphere'' of next week's seven-nation economic summit, a senior <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> official said Thursday <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, chief executive of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, said a `` divergence of views'' remained between <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> over how to reduce government support for agriculture. `` This ... could well spoil the atmosphere'' of the summit that starts Sunday in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> told a news conference at <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> and other senior officials of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> executive <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will represent the 12-nation trade bloc at the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> meeting, which will be attended by the heads of government or state of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> said he expected no major new initiatives to emerge from the meeting. At last year's seven-nation economic summit President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> unveiled a proposal for phasing out government subsidies to farmers by the end of the century. The EEC has rejected the idea, saying it supports coordinated cuts in subsidies but that some government aid will always be necessary to properly manage farm markets. Last fall the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> proposed what it called `` short term'' measures aimed at easing immediate problems of overproduction of sugar, grain and other crops. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has criticized this approach. Farm reform is a central theme of the current <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of international trade liberalization negotiations being held under the auspices of the 93-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> also said discussions of key economic and trade issues at <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> would be made more difficult by the fact that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will soon leave office and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential election contest is heating up. `` This will make discussion of the outlook for the world economy in 1989 and 1990 a little bit more difficult,'' <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> said, adding that it also would hamper discussion of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> trade liberalization talks. <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> said he would be explaining to his summit partners the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s new protocol agreement with the Soviet-led economic bloc, the Council for Mutual Economic Assistance. The protocol, in which the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc group extends formal recognition to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> for the first time, is to be signed by leaders of both organizations on June 25.
