<HEAD>Weyerhaeuser Co. Rejects Union Contract Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has rejected a union contract proposal in the midst of a strike against three other <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> timber companies, according to a union official. A Weyerhaeuser counterproposal was inadequate, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Woodworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday. <PERSON> Hubbell </PERSON> said no further talks were scheduled with the <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, Wash.-based company, but negotiating subcommittees will meet in the next few days to discuss proposed changes in <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION>'s profit-sharing plan <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> has about 7,500 union employees. About 4,500 union workers have been on strike since June 6 against <ORGANIZATION> Willamette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Champion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> DAW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. The woodworkers' union and the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> called the strike after the companies rejected a contract accepted earlier by Eugene-based <ORGANIZATION> Bohemia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Bohemia </LOCATION> contract reportedly provides a 5 percent raise in the first year and 4 percent in each of the following three years of the contract. The Weyerhaeuser counterproposal calls for a 4 percent increase in base pay over four years, <PERSON> Hubbell </PERSON> said. The company also offered improvements in its profit-sharing plan. `` We're absolutely miles apart on base rates as it relates to the <LOCATION> Bohemia </LOCATION> settlement,'' <PERSON> Hubbell </PERSON> said. Company spokesman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Bjorklund </PERSON> declined to comment on details of Wednesday's negotiations, but described them as constructive. `` Both parties acknowledged the need for considerable discussion of detailed issues,'' he said.
