<HEAD>Stocks Up, Retail Sales, Industrial Production Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs on business inventories and sales; picks
up 2nd graf pvs, A late spurt ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Business inventories rose a moderate 0.5 percent in April as business sales slackened somewhat from March's torrid pace, the government said today. The build-up of inventories was about in line with expectations, and economists had expected sales to retreat after two strong months. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said inventories rose $ 3.6 billion to a seasonally adjusted $ 723.7 billion, while total business sales fell 0.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 478.8 billion. On Wednesday, stock prices edged to new post-October crash highs as the government reported increases in May retail sales and industrial production and a widened first-quarter deficit in the broadest measure of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign trade. A late spurt in buying on <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> pushed the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials up 6.93 points on Wednesday to 2,131.40, its second post-crash high in as many days. The blue-chip stock indicator climbed 25.07 points Tuesday. Before the market opened, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said retail sales rose 0.1 percent in May to $ 131.9 billion after a 0.4 percent drop in April. The sales gain was restrained by a 1.2 percent fall in automotive sales. Excluding autos, retail sales rose 0.5 percent in May. Sales of expensive durable goods expected to last three or more years were down 0.6 percent, while non-durable goods sales rose 0.5 percent. In another report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said industrial production rose 0.4 percent in May, the eighth consecutive increase in output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities. The May advance followed a revised 0.6 percent rise in April, initially estimated at 0.7 percent. With the latest growth, overall industrial production now stands 6.1 percent higher than it was a year ago. In the trade report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the deficit in the broadest measure of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign trade widened to $ 39.75 billion in the first quarter as the first deficit in investment earnings in 30 years offset a sharp improvement in the merchandise trade balance. The imbalance in the country's current account balance from January through March surged by 18.6 percent from a fourth quarter total of $ 33.5 billion. The current account is the most important of all the trade statistics because it covers not only merchandise trade but also trade in the services category, which reflects primarily the flow of investment earnings between countries. The report said the services category went from a fourth quarter surplus of $ 12 billion to a deficit of $ 655 million in the first quarter of this year, the first deficit in the investment category since 1958. The report on the current account came a day after another trade report showed the deficit in merchandise shipments narrowed to $ 9.89 billion in April, the smallest monthly deficit since December 1984. The current account figures showed a similar decline in the merchandise trade deficit. In the first quarter, it dropped 12.7 percent to $ 35.95 billion, the best improvement in five years. But the services deficit added $ 655 million to this figure and another $ 3.15 billion was added by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid payments and Social Security benefits paid to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> retirees living overseas.
</TEXT>
