<HEAD>Drought Brings Traffic To Crawl On Ole Man River</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 3rd pvs, bgng `Nobody knows...' with
Army Corps of Engineers spokesman saying they had discovered a
secondary channel that may let smaller tows pass. Pickup 4th graf,
`While tugboat...'; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Time runs slow on Ole Man River these days but the money's running out fast, as the 50 towboats in position to nudge 750 barges up the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> sit stranded in record-low water levels caused by drought. Officials fear that up to 1,500 barges could become stranded by the weekend, equaling `` a traffic jam of semi-trucks bumper to bumper from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Logue </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Vicksburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>. `` Nobody knows for a fact how long we will be here,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Burkett </PERSON>, a pilot with the towboat <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Detmar </PERSON>, Jr., stuck near this <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delta </LOCATION> town. `` Some of the boats have been here for three days _ at least three days.'' The low river levels have created bottlenecks in places such as <LOCATION> Vaucluse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Landing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, about three miles north of the <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, where the river is down to nine feet. Prospects of ending that bottleneck brightened today. `` Late yesterday afternoon, our navigation people were able to mark a secondary channel at <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> that we did n't know existed,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Logue </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, said today. `` Since we found the secondary channel, it looks like the small tows will be able to go ahead and pass. The larger tows will have to wait,'' he said. While tugboat owners are losing an estimated $ 10,000 a day in expenses, their crews are spending the time painting, performing light maintenance and even fishing. `` There's plenty of work, there's always something to do,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Southern </PERSON>, a first mate on the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON>, a northbound towboat pushing 30 barges north. The continuing drought throughout the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and Southeast has brought the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> to its lowest levels for this time of year since <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> chronicled life on the Big Muddy and officials began chronicling river levels in 1872. The low water has forced barges to operate only during daylight and to lighten their loads, said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, vice president of the American Waterways Operators in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` Low water _ since the days of <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> _ has been an occupational hazard, and they know how to deal with it. Things are somewhat restricted, but cargo is still moving,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said Wednesday. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barges carry such cargo as grain, petroleum, chemicals, iron and steel, he said. Barges with light loads wait here to be escorted one by one by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> channel patrol boat. In all, about 50 towboats were stranded Wednesday along with their charges, approximately 750 barges, officials said. The towboats, which displace more than 9 feet of water, were stranded in about 9 feet or less as they waited for the corps dredge <PERSON> Jadwin </PERSON> to arrive today to widen the channel. The <PERSON> Jadwin </PERSON> will take at least a day, and possibly two, to dredge the channel to a depth of 16-20 feet and allow the barges through, officials said. The drought has been good news for some, however. Waterways Marine, which takes orders by radio and delivers supplies to towboats passing by, has been doing a brisk business since the boats became stranded, said the company's general manager, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON>. In addition to food and housekeeping supplies, <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON> said, he is also selling a lot of fuel because many boats are keeping their engines running. Towboat owners are losing money because, in addition to food, fuel and salary expenses, they get paid per ton-mile, and every lost day is lost tonnage that could be delivered, <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON> said. The river gauge at <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, about 70 miles south of <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, read 2.5 feet Tuesday. The lowest level ever recorded was minus 7 feet in February 1940, when much of the upper river was frozen, said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, chief of water control management for the corps district. <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON> said some pilots are resorting to ingenious methods to try and get through what has become an increasingly narrow and shallow channel near <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>. One pilot radioed <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON> to ask if he could unload most of the fuel from his tanks to make his boat light enough to get through. <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON>, however, said he was n't able to help the pilot.
