<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Limit-Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened sharply higher today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, with corn prices for near-term delivery rocketing up the daily trading limit for the third consecutive day on dry-weather fears. The exchange expanded corn price limits from 10 cents to 15 cents a bushel on Wednesday _ the second day of limit gains _ in accordance with its rules. The higher limit will remain in effect at least through Monday. Most oat futures also opened up their daily limit of 10 cents a bushel. Some soybean contracts surged their 30-cents-a-bushel limit at the opening, but prices fell back on reports that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration would consider limiting soybean exports if the drought in the Grain Belt continues. `` That goes without saying _ they're going to have to reduce exports if we have a smaller crop,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Scattered showers brought relief to isolated sections of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> on Wednesday, and there is a chance of rain in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> this weekend. But the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday predicted below-normal rainfall for the region in the middle and latter portions of next week. In early trading, wheat was 2 -RCB- cents to 8 cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.91 a bushel; corn was 2 -LCB- cents to 15 cents higher with July at $ 2.94 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 10 cents higher with July at $ 2.89 \ a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to 24 cents higher with July at $ 9.44 a bushel Most cattle futures were lower while pork futures were mixed in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .50 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June at 69.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were 1.50 cents lower across the board with August at 70.27 cents a pound; hogs were .70 cent lower to .80 cent higher with June at 48.45 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .72 cent lower to 1.78 cents higher with July at 43.75 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures closed sharply lower on Wednesday.
