<HEAD>Dollar Declines, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar declined against the major currencies in European trading Thursday, mainly because of uncertainty over why the West German central bank was selling dollars. Gold prices were mixed. Foreign exchange dealers said the <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> sold about $ 210 million Wednesday and Thursday. They said there were rumors the bank will increase money market interest rates next week, making the West German currency more attractive. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading, British pounds were more expensive for buyers at $ 1.7900 dollars, up from $ 1.7848 late Wednesday. Other late rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.7505 West German marks, down from 1.7535; 1.4580 Swiss francs, down from 1.4675; 5.9005 French francs, down from 5.9137; 1.9650 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9690; 1,299.50 Italian lire, down from 1,300.62; and 1.2160 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2170. Earlier in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 125.98 Japanese yen, down from 126.32 late Wednesday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> late Thursday, the dollar traded at 125.65 yen and dealers said the dollar's fall against the German mark was the main reason for the decline. Gold bullion prices were mixed, moving higher in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and lower in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>. Traders said their market was nervous and prices fluctuated throughout the day in a narrow range, underpinned by rising commodity prices in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because of drought but weakened by lower oil prices. Gold closed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 452.80 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's late $ 452.60. The closing price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> was $ 452.50 bid, down from $ 453. After the gold market in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> was shut for a holiday Wednesday, gold closed there Thursday at $ 454.52, up from $ 452.58 Tuesday. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 7.21 a troy ounce, up from $ 7.14.
