<SECOND>AM-Tax Survey,0326</SECOND>
<NOTE>For Release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Americans Say New Tax Law Less Fair Than Old Statute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A majority of Americans questioned in a recent survey say the tax law that went into effect last year is less fair than the old statute, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The results of the poll indicate public opinion about the tax law has become more negative now that it has been in effect for more than a year. The 5,000 households questioned in the survey were asked how fair they felt the new law was, regardless of how it affected them personally. Fifty-three percent said they felt the new law was less fair than the old law, while 14 percent said they were fairer, and 33 percent said they saw little change from the old law, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The results contrast with a survey taken after the new law was passed in 1986. At that time, one-third of the respondents said the statute was less fair, the business research organization said. The most dissatisfaction with the new law came from upper-income households, those with incomes above $ 50,000 a year. In that group, 62 percent said the new statute was less fair, 15 percent said it was fairer and 23 percent said they saw no change. Forty-six percent of the overall respondents in the latest survey said their taxes have gone up since the new law was implemented, while 36 percent said their taxes were the same and 18 percent said they were lower. Among upper-income respondents, 63 percent reported their taxes were higher, 21 percent said they were the same and 16 percent said they were lower. The survey, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 1 percent, was conducted for the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
