<HEAD>London Share Prices Drop</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading activity; No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices fell Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as equities followed Wall Street lower, giving market players an opportunity to sell and take some profits. At the close, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index was down 7.4 points, or 0.40 percent, at 1,861.9. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 20.09 points at 2,111.31 as the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading session drew to a close, after opening about 12 points lower. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> dealers said their market moved into negative territory during the afternoon as it became evident that Wall Street was heading lower, pressured by a swift decline in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bond prices. Analysts said it was not suprising to see such a technical correction in bond prices after their sharp gains over the past several weeks. Dealers said major market players were resuming their cautious stance, as inflationary fears were thought to be creeping back into the market. One equity analyst with <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> stockbrokerage <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> said the market still is not convinced that it is on a stable footing. `` It's far too early after the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> April -RRB- trade figures to say we've seen the bottom of the bear market and there are plenty more factors for Wall Street to take account of,'' he said. A barrage of British economic data unsettled the market, raising fears that the economy may be growing too quickly for its own good, analysts said. The British <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> reported that the public sector borrowing requirement, the most widely used measure of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s government deficit or surplus, showed a surplus of 624 million pounds in May, down from a revised surplus of 1.129 billion pounds in April.
