<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-GNP Bjt   06-16 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-GNP, Bjt,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Economy Grows 4.9 Percent In Fiscal 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s muscular economy, shrugging off the burden of a strong currency, grew faster in the first three months of 1988 than at any time since 1977, according to figures released Thursday. Boosted by personal spending and housing investment, the economy grew 2.7 percent in the January-March period after adjustment for inflation, the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said. That came to an unusually robust annual growth rate of 11.3 percent, the fastest since the January-March period of 1977, when the annual growth rate was 11.7 percent, records show. Although growth rates tend to fluctuate erratically from quarter to quarter, economists said the increase was nevertheless an impressive sign of strength. The first three months of 1988 represent the final quarter of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 1987 fiscal year. Growth for the entire fiscal year came to 4.9 percent after adjustment for inflation, more than in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the agency said. A year ago, economic planners were worried that the soaring value of the Japanese yen would drive the economy into a recession by making Japanese exports too expensive for foreign purchasers. Instead, the value of the yen stabilized and Japanese companies found ways to cut costs and keep their prices competitive in world markets. `` It is easy for many Japanese exporters to overcome this yen increase. Now they're feeling very comfortable, exporting many goods to not only the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but many <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries and European countries,'' said <PERSON> Yoshihisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitai </PERSON>, a New York-based economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Term </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>. At the same time, the economy has become less dependent on exports because of a government-fueled expansion of the domestic economy. The government has provided easy credit and undertaken a multitrillion-yen housing and public works program. The 1987 real growth rate of 4.9 percent topped the government's revised target of 3.7 percent for real growth _ that is, growth after adjusting for the effects of inflation The government predicted real growth of 3.8 percent in fiscal 1988. Officials said personal spending, which normally accounts for about 55 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s gross national product, rose 4.0 percent in fiscal 1987 from a year earlier. Housing investment rose by 23.9 percent and industrial equipment investment rose by 10.1 percent, both compared with fiscal 1986, the official said. Housing investment softened at the end of the fiscal year. Housing starts in January, February and March were up 2 percent from a year earlier after a string of double-digit increases. However, consumer spending in the quarter was strong. An additional shopping day in February helped boost consumer spending, said <PERSON> Shingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Unami </PERSON>, an economist for <ORGANIZATION> Yasuda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s growth outpaced the growth in the 1987 calendar year of 2.9 percent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 4.8 percent in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, 1.7 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 2.2 percent in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and 3.1 percent in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, but trailed the growth of 12.0 percent in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, officials said
</TEXT>
