<HEAD>Report: Bundesbank to Raise Key Interest Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German financial newspaper reported Thursday that the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> planned to raise a key interest rate next week, although the central bank had no comment on the report. The article in the daily <ORGANIZATION> Handelsblatt </ORGANIZATION> disturbed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial markets, where stock and bond prices fell sharply on fears that American interest rates would rise also. The newspaper said the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> decided at its Wednesday policymaking meeting to increase the securities repurchase rate, which is the rate the central bank pays to trade in securities in the open market, a quarter percentage point to 3.25 percent. The West German central bank has kept the rate constant at 3.25 percent since Nov. 24 of last year as an indication of its policy of stable interest rates and ample money-market liquidity. A <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said he could neither confirm nor deny the rate hike report. However, a top West German banking official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said several developments have made the situation ripe for an increase. He listed those developments as a rise in interest rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries, a widening gap between German long-term and short-term rates, a climbing dollar, and a weakening West German mark. Another official, <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Huefner </PERSON>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>'s hike in the `` repo rate,'' if implemented next week, would n't necessarily cause criticism from its partners in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> or overseas. To brake the dollar's recent rise, either the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has to lower its interest rates or West German interest rates have to go up, <PERSON> Huefner </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
