<HEAD>European Industry Criticizes EEC Merger Control Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of leading European industrialists on Wednesday criticized rules for regulating mergers that has been proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. In a statement, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roundtable </ORGANIZATION> said parts of the proposals were unclear or unworkable, echoing similar criticisms leveled last month by <ORGANIZATION> UNICE </ORGANIZATION>, a federation of employer organizations. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says merger rules are necessary as the 12-nation bloc moves to create a unified market by 1992 and has proposed that it be given the power to block mergers judged to be anti-competitive. The Roundtable, which consists of about three dozen big companies, said that `` it was concerned that the present draft of the merger regulation does n't sufficiently support corporate restructuring.'' It said the commission should only be able to block a merger if it could show that competition would be eliminated `` in the relevant market.'' It also said any control by the commission should allow companies to make rapid decisions so that possible mergers would not fail simply due to administrative procedures.
