<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two former top executives of <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutritional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> were sentenced Thursday to a year and a day in prison for distributing phony apple juice intended for babies. The case, one of the largest consumer fraud prosecutions of its kind, involved the intentional shipment of adulterated and misbranded juice to 20 states, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and five foreign countries between 1978 and 1982. `` The fraud was too extensive and too involved to go unpunished,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, who also levied $ 100,000 fines against the defendants, <PERSON> Neils </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>, 54, the former president and chief executive officer of the company, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>, 56, a former vice president. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> ordered both to pay court costs, which authorities estimated would run into the tens of thousands of dollars, as well as a special assessment of $ 50 for each of the hundreds of counts on which they were convicted. Beech-Nut, a subsidary of <ORGANIZATION> Nestle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, is the nation's second-largest baby food maker after <ORGANIZATION> Gerber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> is based in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION> Prior to sentencing, <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> begged the judge to spare him a prison term. His voice was thick with emotion and at one point he wiped a tear from his eye. `` It would be so much easier to endure the torment if I had been alone without a family. ... I can not bear to look at them. I see in their eyes disappointment, hurt, disgust and fear for the future because of my condition,'' <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> said. `` I ask for them and myself, please do n't send me to jail.'' <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>, who are free on bail pending appeal, have been on full paid leave from <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION>, according to a company spokesman. Court documents show that <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> received an annual salary of $ 165,000 and <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON> was paid $ 82,000. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>, in his presentencing statement, asked that the defendants receive substantial prison terms because they had `` perpetrated a massive fraud on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and foreign consumers.'' Customers were `` deprived of the choice of what to feed their babies,'' <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> said. `` They betrayed the sacred trust accepted by anyone who undertakes to provide nutrition to infants.'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said the details of the case pertaining to economic fraud were `` pretty extraordinary.'' `` I have no alternative than to do what I am going to do,'' he said before imposing the sentences. The two executives, along with <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> and two suppliers, were charged in the phony juice scheme. The juice, labeled 100 percent apple juice for babies, was actually made from a flavored concentrate that had little or no apple juice, prosecutors charged. No evidence was presented that the phony juice caused any health problems. Beech-Nut, as a corporation, pleaded guilty in November to 215 counts of violating federal food and drug laws and agreed to pay a $ 2 million fine. After a three-month trial that ended in February, a jury convicted <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, of 358 counts of violating the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Each count carried a maximum sentence of three years in prison and a $ 10,000 fine. <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Schenectady </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, who oversaw the upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> manufacturing plant where the juice was made, was convicted of conspiracy, 18 counts of mail fraud and 429 counts of violating federal food and drug laws. Conspiracy and mail fraud carry maximum sentences of five years in prison. At the trial, the government introduced evidence to show that <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> bought adulterated and misbranded apple juice concentrate from two suppliers, who also pleaded guilty, and used this concentrate in apple juice and mixed apple products. Prosecutors said that <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON> knew of the purchase of the bogus concentrate as early as 1978 and that <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON>, who became president in April 1981, knew of its use the previous January while he was still senior vice president in charge of marketing. Both defense attorneys, <PERSON> Brendan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> for <LOCATION> Hoyvald </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimelman </PERSON> for <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON>, had urged <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> to sentence their clients to probation and community service or home detention. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hoyvald </PERSON> had been punished by the loss of his position and loss of presitige brought about by extensive media coverage of the case. `` Alternative sentencing can achieve the desire of the system to punish,'' <PERSON> Kimelman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lavery </PERSON> declined to comment before sentencing. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for the Eastern District of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he was satisfied that the sentences were a `` sufficient deterrent'' to other executives. He said economic fraud cases would continue to be a high priority, adding that `` a great effort went into fighting this major corporation with all its megabucks.'' Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Theurer </PERSON>, the current <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> president, said in a written statement said the company had invested $ 10 million in the last five years to ensure the quality of their products. `` Our products on the supermarket shelves today are pure,'' <PERSON> Theurer </PERSON> said. `` We know this because we test them every day.'' In May 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> settled a class-action suit involving the phony juice that was filed in federal court in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The company agreed to set up a $ 5 million cash fund for consumers and to provide $ 2.5 million in Beech-Nut and affiliated products to retailers.
