<TEXT>
 The stock market tumbled Thursday, mirroring a plunge in bond prices and eradicating gains in the previous two sessions that had put the Dow Jones average at a post-crash high. The key index of 30 industrial stocks, which climbed 32 points in the prior two trading days, plummeted 37.16 points to close at 2,094.24. Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5-to-2 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 435 issues up, 1,089 down and 425 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> came to 161.55 million shares, up from 150.26 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 186.038 million shares. Analysts had said there was a natural tendency for some profit-taking to set in following the Dow average's impressive advance of late. But the day's decline was exacerbated by disarray in the credit markets, which were reacting to an unsubstantiated report in a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> newspaper that indicated the central <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> might be tightening monetary policy. `` There are some indications that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> might be doing the same, and that says effectively that if the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> wants to keep the dollar stable, it will not give interest rates much room to decline,'' said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year issue finished off 1 | points, or down more than $ 16 per $ 1,000 in face value `` There was profit-taking as expected, but investors were given a shove by the suggestion that monetary policy might be tightening in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. Further pressuring the markets was a government report that showed operating rates at American factories, mines and utilities rose to 82.9 percent in May, the highest level in more than eight years. The report, well above market expectations, was interpreted as a sign that inflation may be lurking. Analysts fear a crack in investors' confidence, which has been building gradually, and described the drop as jolting. `` It just points out what thin ice we're on,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. The Dow fell through the psychologically important 2,100-point level, a mark analysts had hoped would serve as a floor for a further advance. But lower stock prices also could bring out some bargain hunters. `` We would use any weakness as a buying opportunity,'' one trader said. Among actively traded issues, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> was down -RRB- at 49 -LCB-. The oil company, which will face <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> it its annual shareholders meeting Friday, announced a joint venture with a <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> oil company. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> was off \ at 43 \ The company said it will acquire <ORGANIZATION> Borg-Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s chemical division for $ 2.31 billion in cash. <ORGANIZATION> Intermedics </ORGANIZATION> jumped 7 to 42 \ The company agreed to be acquired by Swiss-based <ORGANIZATION> Sulzer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> for $ 43 a share, or about $ 800 million. Elsewhere, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 | to 117 -LRB-, <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> fell 2 at 46 -RCB-, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 -LRB- to 83, and <PERSON> Smithkline </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckman </PE