<HEAD>Federal Criminal Probe of Alleged Payoffs by Northrop to Koreans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is investigating <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s payment of more than $ 7 million to Korean businesses in connection with its attempts to sell its F-20 jet fighter to the Korean military, an official familiar with the case said Thursday. The criminal probe, which seeks to determine if the payments in 1984 through 1986 violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, is in its preliminary stages, said the official, who refused to be identified. The act bars <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies from making direct or indirect payments to foreign government officials. The investigation, first reported in Thursday's Wall Street Journal, apparently parallels a congressional committee inquiry into <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s payments to Korean companies that were made in connection with negotiations for sale of the fighter planes. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> is n't aware of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> probe, spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON> said Thursday at the company's <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> headquarters. The company previously has portrayed itself as a victim of fraud by the Korean companies it dealt with, and has sued in <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> courts for return of its money. <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> decided against buying the F-20, which <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> never put into production because of a lack of orders worldwide. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> said it invested $ 6.5 million in a <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> hotel venture as part of a legal `` offset'' agreement to demonstrate that in return for the jet contract, the company was willing to help boost the Korean economy. The probe by a subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> focuses on that payment, along with <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s payment of $ 1.5 million to terminate a lobbying agreement with a company controlled by the late Park Chong-kyu, a businessman well connected with the Korean government. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will investigate a secret agreement for <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> to pay as much as $ 55 million to Park's company if the lobbyist persuaded the Korean government to buy 200 of the fighter planes, sources told the Journal.
