<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-SouthAfrica     06-16 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-South Africa,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Japanese Retailer Suspends Sales Of South African Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ito-Yokado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a major Japanese supermarket chain, has suspended sales of South African products because of the country's apartheid policy, a company official said Thursday. `` The decision not to deal in South African products was made in view of the growing criticism in and outside the company'' against the nation's discriminatory policy of racial segregation, said <PERSON> Yasuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Takaha </PERSON>, spokesman for the company. As a result of the decision, sales of canned yellow peaches, canned fruit cocktail and a mixed fruit juice, all imported through a Japanese trading company, were suspended at the company's 133 stores across <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in April. <PERSON> Takaha </PERSON> said the decision was made during a company meeting in March, but the supermarket chain deliberately did not make a formal announcement. He said the products have been replaced with similar items from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Takaha </PERSON> also declined to provide sales figures for the two South African products. Ito-Yokado has sold the canned peaches since 1983 and the fruit cocktail since 1985. The move by the retailer comes at a time when <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is facing rising international criticism over its trade with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Last year, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> became <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest trading partner, surpassing <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In dollar terms, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s two-way trade with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> rose 19 percent to $ 4.27 billion last year, according to preliminary Japanese figures. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> currently prohibits all direct investment by local companies in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, bans imports of South African iron and steel, and limits cultural, sports and tourism exchanges. It also bans sales of computers that might be used to enforce the apartheid system.
</TEXT>
