<HEAD>A Week After Leaving Pentagon, Paisley Took Consulting Job</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf bgng, `Paisley began,' to
UPDATE with report on former Navy Secretary Webb's comments on
Paisley, including that he was a central figure in the probe</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Within a week of his departure from the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> went to work for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as a consultant to help the firm get defense contracts, sources said Thursday. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents seized records pertaining to <LOCATION> Paisley </LOCATION> when they searched <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> offices as part of a massive fraud and bribery probe involving alleged corruption at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. The investigation involves court-authorized phone taps and bugs at <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>'s consulting office after he left the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, said other sources. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents also took from <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office documents relating to the 404 and T-406 engines which <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>' unit, builds for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> began working as a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> consultant within a week after he left his <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> job last year, according to the sources. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> was the assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> for research, and engineering and systems. He had been recruited for the position in 1981 by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>, the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>'s boss. Former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that he was briefed about the fraud and bribery probe last fall and as a result of his briefings, `` It was clear that <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> was one of the central figures'' in the investigation. In addition, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said that 10 days before <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> left the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> in March 1987, he had persuaded <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials to give him a contract as a consultant to the office he was leaving and he won approval to maintain his security clearance for access to information involving the military's most secret `` black programs.'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> for a story in Friday's editions that he canceled <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>'s contract within days after taking office in April 1987 because `` it appeared to be a conflict of interest,'' and that <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> received no fees for it. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, 63, a native of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, went to the Pentagon from the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, where he was manager for international operations in the company's space and information division. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> is still a consultant for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> and the sources said his work involves lobbying efforts on behalf of engines built by the company's <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Whitney engine division. The 404 is being built for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s F @ A-18 jet airplane, and the T-406 engine, a smaller engine which is being built for the V-22 Osprey, a vertical take-off jet that is being developed for both the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The Pentagon has awarded $ 316 million worth of 404 engine contracts to <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whitney </LOCATION> in the past two years. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> originally had the chief contract to provide engines for the F-18, but the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, seeking to drive down costs, approached <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whitney </LOCATION> two years ago and asked if the company could build engines for the plane. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingman </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>, refused to confirm or deny <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>'s status as a consultant. `` We, as a matter of policy, do not confirm who consults with <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Bingman </PERSON> said in answer to questions. While he was in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> was a key figure in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's naval build-up, which in turn was a centerpiece of the large increases in defense spending that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> won during his first term after his 1980 campaign pledge to `` re-arm <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> worked with <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyatt </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> secretary for shipbuilding. `` Everything on the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s procurement side went through those three,'' said one congressional source Thursday, speaking on condition of anonymity.
